<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     04-07 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 61-year-old college professor, infatuated
with the lilting Scottish voice recording of his bank's automated
teller, finally got to meet the woman of his cash machine dreams.
   ``I guess the first thing I should say is, `Your transaction is
processing,''' said Sally Masterson, a 29-year-old British radio
talk-show host, on meeting Dick Ferry after a trans-Atlantic flight
Wednesday.
   The encounter was arranged by the Decatur Herald & Review's
editors, who tracked down Ms. Masterson after Ferry, an education
professor, wrote a Feb. 4 newspaper column about his ``infatuation
with the talking teller.''
   ``She is very sweet, she is very charming,'' Ferry said later.
``She is a person I'd very much like to have for a friend.''
   ``I think he's smashing,'' said Ms. Masterson. ``He's what I
call wacky, because he's got that wacky sense of humor.''
   Ferry's wife, Carol, said she first heard Ms. Masterson's voice
last weekend. Before Wednesday's meeting, Mrs. Ferry asked, ``How
would anyone feel if a young sexy person wants to meet your
husband?''
   Ms. Masterson, who is single, made the teller-machine recording
three years ago in Dundee, Scotland, for NCR Corp. of Dayton, Ohio.
   ``I thought she was charming,'' Mrs. Ferry said. ``I've
thoroughly enjoyed this.'' Ms. Masterson returns to Britian on
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a short-lived stint as a party
animal, Bullwinkle the moose has come home to roost atop the pizza
palace from which he was moosenapped seven months ago.
   As you'll recall, in our our last episode, the 40-foot
inflatable effigy of Rocket J. Squirrel's best buddy vanished from
the roof of Bullwinkle's Family Food 'n Fun Restaurant in August.
   The restaurant, eager to get its $17,000 mascot back, offered
the culprits free pizza for a year for the 300-pound moose on the
loose. Suspicion soon focused on the notorious spy Boris Badenov
and his companion, Natasha.
   Finally, on April Fool's Day a deflated Bullwinkle was
unceremoniously deposited in the parking lot of the eatery along
with a 2-by-3-foot note.
   ``Hey guys! The moose is no longer loose. He wanted to party
with us so we brought him along. It turns out he was too wild for
us! Please keep an eye on him, he's dangerous! April Fools, Class
of '88.
   ``P.S. Sorry.''
   Police, who say the case is closed, believe the moose's
abductors may have been students from Santa Clara High who decided
to give back Bullwinkle after they realized what it was worth.
   The restaurant manager, however, can't just laugh it off, having
ordered a replacement moose for the roof.
   Stay tuned for the next episode: ``Wedding Bells For
Bullwinkle?'' or ``Hey, Bub, This Roof Ain't Big Enough For Both of
Us!''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ULITHI ATOLL, Yap (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While many people are griping about
having to pay a quarter to mail a letter, the U.S. Postal Service
has given the 700 residents of this West Pacific island chain
something to smile about. Ulithi Atoll finally has its own Zip Code.
   The atoll, best known as the site from where the United States
launched its World War II invasions of Okinawa and Iwo Jima, is
part of Yap State in the Federated States of Micronesia, a former
trust territory that holds a compact of free association with the
United States. It is about 1,200 miles southeast of Okinawa.
   Ulithi Atoll includes dozens of islands, but people live on just
four of them. Only about 700 people live here now, but in September
1944 hundreds of warships gathered in the atoll's sheltered lagoon
to prepare for the 1945 invasions of Okinawa and Iwo Jima. The
Ulithi rendezvous was the largest U.S. Navy task force assembled
during the war.
   A post office opened here in March to distribute mail flown in
from Colonia, the island's governmental seat about 100 miles east
of Ulithi. The postal address is Ulithi, Yap, FM 96943.
</TEXT>
