<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Cuba-Smoking     04-07 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Cuba-Smoking,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Joins International Smoke-Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba, known worldwide for making fine cigars,
will participate in an international stop-smoking day.
   The Cuban news agency Prensa Latina said Cuban participation
today should not be considered ``a novelty,'' even though Cuba is a
major tobacco producer.
   ``A strong campaign against the smoking habit has been under way
for some years and has achieved already positive results, even
though at the expense of an important reduction in income from the
sale of cigarettes and tobacco,'' said the dispatch received in
Mexico City on Wednesday.
   The campaign intensified after Cuban President Fidel Castro gave
up his trademark cigars about two years ago.
   Prensa Latina said per capita consumption of cigarettes and
tobacco has been declining since 1986 and sales dropped by $100
million last year. It also said from today onward smoking will be
banned on all Cuban domestic flights.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
