<DOCNO> AP880407-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-Teacher     04-07 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Teacher,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher With AIDS Continues Work While Fighting Illness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teacher who won a landmark court
decision allowing him to continue teaching despite suffering from
AIDS says his life has almost returned to normal even though his
body is weakening.
   ``There are some days that I think nothing is wrong, and there
are other times when I know very well something is, uh, lurking in
my body,'' Vincent Chalk said in an interview published Wednesday
in the Orange Coast Daily Pilot.
   Chalk, a vocational counselor for hearing-impaired students at
Venado Middle School and University High School in Irvine, filed a
lawsuit against the Orange County Department of Education last year
when officials reassigned him to a desk job after learning he had
AIDS.
   In November, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in what
is believed to have been the nation's first such AIDS
discrimination case, saying he could not be barred from the
classroom.
   Chalk, 43, said he never anticipated the publicity the case
generated, which forced his parents to tell their friends that
their only son was homosexual, something they had known for years.
Chalk said he felt sorry for himself at first.
   ``I'm not nor ever have been a very sexually active kind of
person,'' said Chalk, who lives in Long Beach with a companion of
six years. ``I thought, `Other people are out there doing a lot
more than I am. They would make better subjects.' But you can't go
through life dealing with `Why me's?'''
   But now, he's motivated to remain in the classroom, although he
weighs 130 pounds, down from 160, and is plagued by a chronic sinus
infection, he said. Chalk has trimmed his work week to three days
so he won't weaken.
   ``There are people who want to say, `See? Knew you couldn't do
it,''' he said.
   Chalk said he listens to motivational tapes and uses visual
imagery in fighting AIDS, and has given up casual cocaine use and
alcohol.
   ``I'm trying to create as much health in my life and my body as
possible,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
