<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HousingSurvey     04-07 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Housing Survey,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey Says Majority Of Americans Would Support More Housing
Programs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: R L Associates in 7th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A non-profit housing group says its new poll
shows that people are willing to pay higher taxes to ensure that
poor and middle-class Americans get decent, affordable housing.
   ``There's no doubt the American people support programs to
expand home ownership, help low-income renters and aid the
homeless,'' National Housing Institute chairman John Atlas said
Wednesday. ``And contrary to the conventional wisdom, they're
willing to pay.''
   The poll found that most Americans believe there is a lack of
affordable housing for the poor and middle class. Most of those
surveyed said they would pay an extra $10 to $15 a month in taxes
for programs to aid the homeless, the elderly and middle-class
families unable to make down payments to buy houses.
   The survey also found that nearly 75 percent of the American
public believes a presidential candidate who advocates housing
programs for middle-and working-class families ``understands the
real needs in America.''
   The vast majority _ 86 percent _ said they feel homelessness is
``a national disgrace'' and an even higher percentage _ 93 percent
_ said homelessness is an important problem that should be
eliminated.
   ``Politically, a presidential candidate who guarantees every
American a decent affordable home might have a new home himself _
on Pennsylvania Avenue,'' Atlas said.
   The report, ``A Status Report On The American Dream: How the
American People View Housing Problems and Programs Today,'' was
based on polling by R L Associates of Princeton, N.J. The firm
interviewed 1,001 adults by telephone during February and March.
Michael Rappaport, spokesman for the polling firm, said the margin
of error is plus or minus 4 percentage points.
   In general, the survey found that at least two-thirds of those
questioned support programs to finance renovations in housing for
the elderly, to rehabilitate old and vacant buildings, to establish
a homeless prevention program to help those close to eviction for
financial reasons, and to begin a mortgage assistance program to
help with downpayments.
   On the issue of higher taxes to support housing programs, 66
percent said they would be willing to spend $10 a month more, while
55 percent said they would agree to pay $15 a month more.
   The poll also found that half of those surveyed said they would
be more likely to vote for a candidate who supports ``a package of
housing programs,'' while only 6 percent said they would be less
likely to support such a candidate.
   Seventy-four percent said they believe a presidential candidate
who advocates housing programs for middle- and working-class
families ``understands the real needs in America.''
   ``The American people are increasingly aware that this nation
faces a housing problem,'' Atlas said. ``Our poll shows that
Americans understand that it's hard to find affordable housing and
that Americans are shocked at homelessness.''
   He said the housing institute, which describes itself as a
representative of housing interests for moderate- and low-income
families, cannot lobby Congress for housing programs because of its
non-profit status. It does plan to provide its poll data to other
groups that can promote the programs.
   Atlas said spending authority for the Department of Housing and
Urban Development dropped 57 percent from 1980 to 1987, from $35.7
billion a year to $15.2 billion. And he said that the HUD budget
last year represented 1 percent of the federal budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
