<DOCNO> AP880407-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0343EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Walton-Sprint     04-07 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Walton-Sprint,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>San Diego Man Waging Unusual Campaign For President _ Of US Sprint</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three years ago, Paul Walton set up a card
table on a downtown street corner here to preach the benefits of
long-distance telephone competition and sign up customers for a
company called US Telecom.
   The 32-year-old San Diego entrepreneur returned to that street
corner Wednesday to tell customers, shareholders and anyone else
who would listen that the company, now called US Sprint
Communications Co., is plagued by billing and management problems
that are costing millions in lost business.
   Walton, who says he signed up more than 600,000 residential
customers for US Sprint, has been waging an unusual grass-roots
campaign to oust the company's management and install himself as
president to clean house.
   ``I'm appealing to customers and shareholders not to rely on the
present management to correct the problems,'' Walton said in an
interview before a speech to a curious lunchtime crowd outside the
Federal Communications Commission's headquarters.
   ``Management has been totally unresponsive'' to the problems,
which Walton says cost him millions in lost commissions for his
sales efforts as well as millions in lost business for the company.
   US Sprint, the nation's third-largest long-distance carrier, has
acknowledged its billing problems and admitted that bad debt has
contributed to the company's losses. Spokesman Syd Courson said the
firm plans to have new computer software installed by January to
take care of the problem.
   ``We've owned up to our billing problems and we've done a lot to
correct them,'' Courson said, adding that Walton has become a
``nuisance.''
   Last week, Walton took his entourage _ complete with a large
campaign banner _ to Los Angeles, Dallas, St. Louis, Chicago and
Atlanta. This week he touched down in San Francisco and Denver
before arriving in Washington.
   All this is leading up to ``election'' appeals he hopes to make
personally to shareholders at meetings April 12 for United
Telecommunications Inc. in Kansas City and April 20 for GTE Corp.
in Stamford, Conn. US Sprint was formed as a joint venture by those
two companies in July 1986.
   But he faces one big stumbling block: Shareholders do not elect
the president.
   Shareholders, however, can raise issues like his at annual
meetings, and since he owns United Telecommunications stock, he can
make comments at that meeting. ``But since there is no election, I
don't know what his purpose is,'' said United Telecommunications
spokesman Don Forsythe. Walton is not a GTE shareholder.
   Walton worked as an independent sales contractor for US Telecom
and US Sprint from 1984 to 1986. During that period, the former
high school teacher hired a sales force of about 400 young people
who worked street corners and college campuses across the country,
signing up new customers.
   But many of those they signed up never got service, were billed
for calls never made, never received bills from US Sprint but were
contacted by collection agencies or had other problems with
service, he said.
   For Walton, this meant problems receiving his commissions. He
was supposed to be credited when customers made their first US
Sprint calls. But because of problems installing service and
billing customers, Walton estimated that about half his recruits
were never counted for a commission.
   After his contract with US Sprint was ended in September 1986,
Walton wrote scores of letters to US Sprint executives about his
lost commissions and the company's billing problems.
   At the time, Walton said, the company owed him between $3
million and $8 million in unpaid commissions. He eventually settled
for nearly $2 million, including a $1.7 million payment in January.
   In total, he said he received about $6 million from US Sprint
during his 2{ years of recruiting. He said he paid close to $5
million of that to his young workers.
   But Walton says it is not the money that is driving his campaign
to oust US Sprint President Robert H. Snedaker.
   ``My integrity is at stake,'' Walton said. ``I wanted to make
more money and feel good about it at the same time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
