<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HensonBurial     04-07 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Henson Burial,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Explorer Given Full Recognition 79 Years Later</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They were together at the discovery of the
North Pole in 1909. But in death, Matthew Alexander Henson was in a
shared grave in New York while Adm. Robert E. Peary was honored at
Arlington National Cemetery.
   Henson was black, and for that reason, said supporter Dr. S.
Allen Counter, ``he was denied proper recognition because of the
racial attitudes of his time.''
   On Wednesday, 79 years to the day after Henson planted the
American flag on the North Pole, the two explorers were reunited as
Henson's remains and those of his wife were reinterred with full
military honors at Arlington.
   ``Now, finally, Matthew Henson and Robert Peary can talk about
old days out there,'' a part-Eskimo grandson, Qitdlaq Henson of
Qaanaaq, Greenland, said through a translator _ his cousin Navarana
Harper _ at a news conference following the ceremony.
   ``I have waited for this day for over 30 years,'' Henson's great
niece, Olive Henson Fulton of Roxbury, Mass., told the gathering of
about 100 relatives and admirers at the windswept hilltop burial
site.
   Recalling that she was expelled from school because she had
written a paper about Henson when her assignment had been to write
about a hero, Ms. Fulton said: ``Finally, my uncle is given his
place in history.''
   Counter said the reinterment of Henson and his wife, Lucy Ross
Henson, was ``long overdue recognition for our hero ... (that
would) right a tragic wrong.''
   ``Welcome home, Matthew Henson,'' he said. ``Welcome home to a
new day in America. ... May your presence here inspire generations
of explorers.''
   Last October, President Reagan approved Counter's petition to
allow Henson's remains to be reinterred at Arlington. He had been
buried in 1955 in Woodlawn Cemetery in New York.
   Among those honoring Henson at the ceremony were Gen. Julius
Beckton of the White House military office, who conveyed greetings
from Reagan; John H. Johnson, the chairman and chief executive
officer of Johnson Publishing Co., which publishes Ebony and Jet
magazines; Col. Guion S. Bluford, the first black astronaut; and
Dorothy Height, the president of the National Council of Negro
Women.
   Counter, an associate professor of neurophysiology at Harvard
University who previously had brought together Henson's and Peary's
part-Eskimo offspring, said Peary had insisted before his own death
in 1920 that Henson's achievements be recognized.
   Descendants of Matthew and Lucy Henson were joined at the
ceremony by Henson's part-Eskimo descendants.
   ``This is a very special day for them,'' Ms. Harper said at the
news conference, translating for another of Henson's grandsons,
Ajako Henson of Morriussaq, Greenland. ``They don't even know how
to express that.''
   Henson's eldest part-Eskimo grandson, Avataq Henson, also of
Morriussaq, clutched to his chest the flag that had draped his
grandfather's coffin.
   ``When he visited Matthew Henson's grave the first time in
Woodlawn Cemetery in New York, he expected it to be a hero's
gravesite,'' Ms. Harper said as she translated for Avataq. ``He was
disappointed to see him among ordinary people.''
</TEXT>
