<1ST_LINE>r p PM-BushMoney     04-07 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush Money,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Bumps Up Against Fund-Raising Limit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's campaign treasury is filled to
the brim and campaign officials say the biggest worry now is
guarding against spending more than the $27 million pre-convention
limit set by federal election law.
   The vice president's campaign has already spent all but $4
million of that cap, with more than four months yet to go to the
Republican convention this August, said campaign treasurer Fred
Bush.
   The Bush campaign hit the contribution limit on Wednesday,
reporting that it had raised a total of $30 million, including
$22.5 million in direct contributions and commitments for another
$7.5 million in federal matching funds.
   This total includes about $3 million earmarked for legal and
accounting expenses which are exempt from the $27 million-limit.
   ``The challenge is to take that $4 million we have left and
maximize it so that George Bush gets the best benefit out of that
he can,'' said the campaign official, who is not related to
candidate Bush.
   ``I'm thrilled,'' Fred Bush said in an interview. ``As far as
this process is concerned, we're finished.''
   The cap applies to both raising funds and spending them.
   GOP contender Pat Robertson was the first candidate to actually
bump up against the spending ceiling.
   The former televison evangelist said after the costly Super
Tuesday contests on March 8 that he was within $2 million of the
spending cap. Since then he has laid off staff and dropped an
extensive television marketing operation. Though he has only 17
delegates to Bush's 888, he remains in the race and is spending the
rest of his money primarily on personal travel.
   Fred Bush said staying within the limits is far easier because
Bush is now running virtually unopposed among Republicans.
   ``It's a fait accompli as far as the nomination. You don't have
to go on advertising, you don't have to buy more TV ads, you don't
have to have a huge entourage,'' he said.
   The vice president had already scaled down his campaign schedule
in the aftermath of Sen. Bob Dole's withdrawal last week from the
race.
   The vice president plans to go ahead with fund-raising events
scheduled for this weekend in Texas and Florida, next week in New
York and Connecticut and later in the month in Washington, D.C.
   The reason? Fred Bush said that the campaign is still entitled
to raise another $2.8 million to go into a ``compliance fund,''
money needed for complying with various provisions enforced by the
Federal Election Commission.
   He said the campaign will still continue to raise funds until
that $2.8 million has been met, and then will close up its
fund-raising operation.
   Funds for the general election campaign are provided from tax
dollars and from a ``presidential trust'' _ funds that can be
raised and spent by the national parties on behalf of their
nominees.
   Fred Bush said contributors who have written checks to the
George Bush campaign that haven't yet been cashed soon will be
receiving letters.
   ``We will write those people and explain to them that we are
over the legal maximum, and would they allow us to use that check
for the compliance fund. We have to have their signature.
Otherwise, we will have to return the check.''
   ``I think it will be a pretty easy $2.8 million to raise,'' he
added.
</TEXT>
