<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Democrats-Optimism     04-07 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrats-Optimism,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Look To New York To Annoint Front-Runner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Party leaders are looking to New
York and asking if Michael Dukakis can extend his winning streak to
four _ and finally give the party a presidential front-runner.
   While many Democrats were sounding optimistic about the
prospects of a breakthrough in the long, roller-coaster race, they
also were painfully aware of the many occasions one or another
candidate looked on the verge of claiming the title of front-runner.
   ``Every time we get a front-runner, it seems folks want to slow
it down,'' said John C. White, a former national party chairman who
is advising Jesse Jackson.
   Watching most closely are those elected and party officials _
645 strong _ designated as uncommitted delegates to the Democratic
National Convention, the so-called super delegates expected to hold
the balance of power.
   ``The super delegates are looking for a candidate who can rattle
off a big string of wins,'' said Rick Wiener, Michigan Democratic
Party chairman.
   It was in Michigan's caucuses in March 26 that Jackson trounced
Dukakis and surged to the forefront of the contest, raising talk of
the likelihood of a brokered convention. Michigan came shortly
after a Dukakis loss in Illinois.
   But since then, the Massachusetts governor has scored victories
in Connecticut, Colorado and Wisconsin and now is favored to extend
his streak in New York which holds its primary on April 19.
   ``The nominee will be determined in New York and Pennsylvania,''
said Rachelle Horowitz, political director of the American
Federation of Teachers and a member of the Democratic National
Committee. ``I think we have a two-person race and we have a
front-runner. The likelihood is we'll have a nominee and not a
brokered convention.''
   The Wisconsin vote ``gives a little boost to Dukakis,'' said
Joseph Crangle, Erie County, N.Y. Democratic chairman, and one of
the party's super delegates. ``But you've got to put a qualifying
clause there that you've got to have a pattern, you've got to go
two or three states in a row in order to say that you're a
front-runner.''
   Party chairman Paul G. Kirk Jr. predicted the Democrats would
choose their nominee on the first ballot of the Atlanta convention
and he vowed to oppose any effort to organize a stop-Jackson
movement.
   ``There's not going to be any organized cabal of party leaders
trying to hobble one candidate as opposed to another,'' said Kirk.
   A total of 2,082 delegates is needed for a convention majority.
To reach that number, either Dukakis or Jackson would need to win
more than 1,300 of the 1,600-plus committed delegates yet to be
chosen or draw strong support from the super delegates.
   ``The super delegates are going to stay frozen for a while,''
predicted White.
   Wiener said the super delegates were ``looking for a candidate
who can rattle off a big string of wins.'' He said most of those
delegates accept the view that ``if there is a clear leader after
California and New Jersey (the last two big states to hold
primaries), that super delegates ought to play a leading role in
propelling that person over the top. At three in a row, Gov.
Dukakis has gotten a very good start on that.''
</TEXT>
