<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra     04-07 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says Prosecution Plan For Release Of Documents Too
Cumbersome</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Iran-Contra case says he
wants to streamline procedures for pre-trial disclosure of 150,000
pages of classified documents to the four defendants.
   Signaling his intention to move the case to trial as quickly as
possible, U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell on Wednesday
rejected independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh's proposal to
prevent unauthorized disclosure of the classified material as too
cumbersome.
   The proposed procedure for three months of pre-trial discovery
``appears to be far too complex, lacks definite time restrictions
and creates undue obstacles to the fair and expeditious disposition
of this case,'' Gesell said in a brief opinion.
   At a hearing scheduled for next Tuesday, Gesell said he
``intends to determine the timing of discovery disclosures in
relation to a realistic trial date.''
   Gesell said he will ask Walsh to say which documents ``will be
made available immediately'' to the defense. Walsh had said in
pleadings filed Monday that he planned to turn over the material to
the defendants in the next three months.
   The judge also said he wants to set a deadline this month for
completion of an interagency review of the documents, which Walsh
says ``describe in detail some of the nation's most carefully held
secrets about its foreign policy, its intelligence activities and
its covert activities.''
   An objection to Walsh's plan was filed by defense lawyers for
former national security adviser John M. Poindexter, Lt. Col.
Oliver L. North and arms dealers Richard V. Secord and Albert Hakim.
   The four are accused of conspiring to illegally divert proceeds
from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   Among elements of the security plan the defense found
objectionable was a requirement that the defendants and their
lawyers answer detailed government questionnaires in order to
obtain security clearances to review the documents.
   Requiring the defendants to answer detailed questions about
their travel, aliases, corporate affiliations ``and other matters
potentially at issue in the case'' could violate their Fifth
Amendment protection against self-incrimination, the defense said.
   The joint opposition also noted that North and Poindexter had
previously had access to many of the documents when they worked at
the National Security Council.
   Gesell said ``it will be necessary to frame a more limited
protective order fashioned to the nature of this case, which in
essence alleges a course of conduct carried out using classified
materials in classified channels from a highly classified site.''
</TEXT>
