<2ND_LINE>AM-Republicans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0765,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dole Meet To Discuss ``Beating Democrats''</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 3 grafs with Robertson saying he won't campaign actively
in New
   York, giving up Secret Service</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush met Wednesday with
Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, his vanquished rival for the
Republican presidential nomination, in their first private session
since a stormy confrontation in February on the Senate floor.
   Bush told reporters that the men had a ``good, friendly
discussion'' during which they talked ``about how to beat
Democrats.''
   The meeting, held in the Capitol, followed an earlier session in
the same building between Dole and Pat Robertson. The former
television evangelist is continuing his quest for the GOP
presidential nomination but has all but conceded that Bush will be
his party's selection.
   Asked after his meeting with Bush whether the two men had buried
the hatchet, Dole said, ``I don't have a hatchet. I'm a nice
fellow.''
   Bush said he envisioned a role for Dole in the general election
in which the Kansan would work ``as much as he possibly has time to
give. A lot of it's here and a lot of it I hope will be around the
country.''
   Dole said that Bush had asked for the meeting and said the
discussion was ``about getting George elected in November.''
   Dole spokesman Walt Riker said later that the men talked about
``keeping the Republican nomination interesting until the
convention'' in August and ``ways to get the issues out there.''
   In an unusual floor confrontation Feb. 4 amid a Contra aid vote,
Dole accused Bush of condoning a campaign attack that amounted to
``groveling in the mud.''
   The face-off was sparked by a Bush campaign statement headlined
``Dole's cronyism and mean-spiritedness questioned.'' The statement
by an Iowa aide implied that Dole accepted favors from the wealthy
and said three federal agencies were examining a defunct blind
trust once held by his wife, former Transportation Secretary
Elizabeth Hanford Dole.
   Dole called the statement ``nasty, mean, personal and
vindictive.'' Bush's campaign manager, Lee Atwater, said Dole was
over-reacting and behaving like ``a typical schoolyard bully _ he
can dish it out, but if someone hits him back, he starts whining.''
   The incident epitomized the bitterness of the campaign between
the two men. But Dole dropped out of the race and endorsed Bush
last month.
   After his meeting with Dole, Robertson said he would stay in the
race until he was assured that the GOP platform would be
conservative enough to keep his supporters active in the campaign.
He promised he would be loyal to the party's candidate.
   ``There's no question that we plan to support the Republican
nominee, and it looks as though it's going to be George Bush,''
Robertson said.
   Robertson said he wanted to be ``a rallying point for
conservatives'' at the GOP convention in New Orleans so he could
encourage his supporters to remain involved in Republican politics.
   ``I want to make sure that it's the type of platform that will
make them get in with both hands and both feet and go to work,'' he
said.
   Robertson told The New York Times he would not campaign in New
York before the April 19 primary, and said he would ask for the
termination of his Secret Service protection.
   In an interview published in Thursday's editions of the paper,
he said it would be ``more quixotic than it is realistic'' to
continue actively campaigning.
   Robertson had already laid off most of his campaign staff and
has made only a few campaign appearances recently, because he is
bumping up against federal campaign spending limits.
</TEXT>
