<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSCommission     04-07 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Commission,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Laws Urged For Those Who Act To Spread AIDS Infection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The need to protect against people with the
AIDS virus who knowingly try to spread the disease must be balanced
against the need to protect individual rights, a public health
expert told the White House AIDS commission.
   ``An isolation statute could require a due process determination
that a viral carrier is unwilling or unable to refrain from
engaging in conduct likely to spread the disease,'' Larry Gostin
testified Wednesday before the panel.
   ``Constitutionally allowable isolation would not focus on a
person's status as having an infection or a disease, but upon his
or her behavior leading to transmission,'' said Gostin.
   Gostin, executive director of the American Society of Law &
Medicine and associate professor at the Harvard School of Public
Health, was among 28 witnesses appearing before the panel in two
days of hearings this week.
   The commission, working toward a June 24 final report, has
scheduled three more days of hearings later this month.
   A Michigan prosecutor told the commission that existing laws are
inadequate to deal with people who know they are infected with the
virus and behave in a manner that could spread it to others.
   ``The citizens of this country deserve protection from being
recklessly or intentionally targeted for exposure to this dreadful
disease,'' said Robert E. Weiss of Flint, Mich.
   Weiss, the elected prosecuting attorney in Genesee County,
explained his rationale for filing assault with intent to murder
charges against a man infected with the virus who tried to spit on
police after being arrested for drunken driving.
   ``He fought with the arresting officers and, once lodged, kept
spitting through the bars of his cell, taunting the officers and
daring them to come closer so he `could give them AIDS,''' said
Weiss.
   ``We filed ... under the theory that his expressed intention to
communicate an incurable, terminal disease amounted to an intent to
cause death,'' he explained.
   The court reduced the attempted murder charge to assault on an
officer, partially on grounds there is insufficient evidence that
the virus can be spread by spitting, said Weiss.
   He said that although the ``percentage of AIDS carriers who will
maliciously or irresponsibly place others at risk is largely
speculative, this fact should not deter us from developing a
legislative framework to control such conduct.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
