<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CrashTests     04-07 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash Tests,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peugeot Shows High Head-Injury Potential, NHTSA Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration says crash tests of nine 1988 vehicles show drivers
of the Peugeot 505 GLS have the greatest chance of sustaining a
head injury.
   A 35 mph crash of the four-door compact into a fixed barrier
produced a head-injury criterion of 1701 on the driver, the highest
recorded among this year's tests.
   The head-injury criterion is an index of the force experienced
by occupants of the car, as measured by a test dummy. The
passenger-side dummy recorded a head-injury criterion of 1457.
   The Peugeot results were among six released Wednesday by NHTSA.
The agency had tested three vehicles earlier in the year.
   The Toyota Corolla FX two-door hatchback, a subcompact, produced
a head-injury criterion of 593 for the driver, and 397 for the
passenger. The driver head-injury criterion was the least among the
nine models tested this year.
   A second subcompact, the Toyota Tercel two-door hatchback,
produced a head-injury criterion of 1005 for the driver and 398 for
the passenger.
   In compact car crash tests, the Nissan Maxima SE four-door
produced a head-injury criteria of 907 for the driver and 861 for
the passenger, and the Pontiac Le Mans two-door Aerocoupe produced
head-injury criteria of 819 for the driver and 897 for the
passenger.
   Wednesday's test results included one van, the Volkswagen
Vanagon, with head-injury criteria of 1320 for the driver and 899
for the passenger.
   Earlier, NHTSA had released test results on the 1988 Volkswagen
Fox, Ford Taurus and Mercury Sable.
   The crash-test results are intended to help consumers compare
vehicles when deciding which to buy, NHTSA said. Only one vehicle
of each model is tested, and further crash tests could produce
different results, NHTSA said.
   The 35 mph crash speed was 5 mph faster, or one-third more
severe, than that specified by federal motor vehicle safety
standards. The 30 mph standards permit a maximum head-injury
criterion of 1000, and higher figures can be expected at the higher
speed, NHTSA said.
</TEXT>
