<1ST_LINE>r p PM-GOP-Dukakis     04-07 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GOP-Dukakis,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Troops Gather Ammunition Against Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two local Republicans riding with George Bush in
the vice presidential limousine were serving as a welcoming
committee _ but Bush wanted to talk business.
   ``If Dukakis wins this thing on the other side, you guys are
going to have to help me in setting the record straight,'' Bush
told them as his motorcade wound through narrow city streets from
the Coast Guard station in Boston's North End to a political rally
at Faneuil Hall.
   The vice president was talking about Massachusetts Gov. Michael
S. Dukakis, who has a strong shot at facing Bush in the general
election next fall. Bush wanted to make sure he knows the full
details of the governor's record, said state Sen. Paul Cellucci,
who sat next to Bush.
   Riding in the jump seat was state Sen. David Locke, who along
with Cellucci is co-chairman of the Bush campaign in Massachusetts.
   ``If we can help you understand the Dukakis philosophy, we will
do that,'' Locke told Bush.
   That conversation, as recalled by the two senators, occurred
Feb. 24, two weeks before Bush's Super Tuesday landslide. Since
then, his principal rival, Bob Dole, has bowed out.
   With the nomination virtually locked up, Bush is plotting
strategy against the Democrats.
   Dukakis, whose treasury and organization far outstrip those of
the other Democrats, has drawn by far the most attention. With
three wins in a row under his belt _ in Connecticut, Colorado and
Wisconsin _ he is well positioned for the New York primary later
this month.
   In addition, Dukakis is the only Democrat who competes well
against Bush in hypothetical matchups in recent public opinion
polls.
   ``There's a perception within the Bush campaign that Dukakis is
in a strong position to win it,'' Cellucci said. ``We're compiling
data that will indicate that the governor did not have much to do
with the strong economy in Massachusetts.''
   He maintained that military spending, tax cuts, a property tax
limitation law and Reaganomics are responsible.
   ``We also want to be in a position where the vice president can
demonstrate that Mike Dukakis is a liberal and he believes in big
government,'' Cellucci said. ``I don't think that's anything that's
going to be too difficult to demonstrate.''
   Dukakis, Cellucci said, has been ``trying to move to the
middle'' by touting his own tax reductions, his record of balancing
budgets and his opposition to communist expansion in Central
America. But Cellucci said, ``the change is so startling and
dramatic that you have to question its sincerity.''
   The intelligence-gathering effort on Dukakis is not limited to
the material Locke and Cellucci can provide.
   The Republican National Committee, which looks into the
background of all the Democratic candidates, has had a researcher
assigned to Dukakis for nearly a year, according to RNC spokesman
Albert Maruggi. The researcher spent a full week at Republican
state committee headquarters in Boston poring over clippings, files
and old speeches.
   The RNC now has an extensive computer file at its fingertips
into which key words like ``taxes,'' ``budgets'' and ``welfare''
can be punched to yield whatever Dukakis has said on the subjects.
   Citizens for Limited Taxation, a conservative taxpayer advocacy
group in Boston, has distributed a 60-page information packet to
reporters, Republican researchers and operatives for Dukakis'
Democratic opponents.
   The packet _ color-coded by issues _ includes newspaper
clippings with headlines like, ``Tax cut is vetoed by Dukakis,''
and ``Report downplays Dukakis impact on economy.''
</TEXT>
