<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--France-Chateau     04-07 0135</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--France-Chateau,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Old Fortress Slated For Renovation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chateau of Vincennes, the former royal palace
where Louis XIV spent his honeymoon, will be renovated, the
government said.
   ``The chateau, as it stands, is a discouraging site,'' said
former culture minister Jean-Philippe Lecat, head of the renovation
committee.
   The government announced Wednesday that the fortress will be
renovated. Lecat proposed a five-year, $30 million plan to turn the
picturesque complex into a cultural facility to accomodate about
400,000 visitors yearly.
   The castle currently receives about 30,000 visitors each year.
   Completed in 1370 by King Charles V, the castle originally was
conceived as the cornerstone of a vast royal city he planned to
control.
   Centuries later the young Louis XIV spent his honeymoon there
but he preferred to live in Fontainebleau and Versailles.
</TEXT>
