<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-EastEurope     04-07 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-East Europe,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Meeting East German, Bulgarian Leaders This Spring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High-ranking officials of East Germany and
Bulgaria, long regarded among Moscow's staunchest allies, have
dates in the coming weeks with Secretary of State George Shultz.
   They are Herman Axen, a member of East Berlin's ruling
politburo, and Andrei Lukanov, Bulgarian minister of foreign
economic relations and alternate politburo member. Both are
described by U.S. officials as the highest-ranking members of their
respective communist hierarchies ever to visit Washington.
   U.S. and East German sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said a May 3 meeting between Shultz and Axen was
arranged after the East German leader was invited to speak May 4 at
the Johns Hopkins University Institute for Contemporary German
Studies.
   Axen holds no office in the East German government, but is the
top international affairs officer of the Socialist Unity Party, the
official name of the governing communist organization.
   Lukanov is scheduled to meet Shultz during an April 25-26 visit
to Washington, followed by a coast-to-coast trade promotion tour
with a high-level delegation. Noted as an economic reformer,
Lukanov will be the first senior Bulgarian cabinet minister in
Washington since World War II.
   Since 1984, the State Department has focused overtures toward
Moscow's East European allies on human rights and economic issues.
   Over the past two years, Deputy Secretary of State John C.
Whitehead has told leaders in East Germany, Czechoslovakia, Poland,
Bulgaria, Romania and Hungary that U.S. readiness to expand
commercial ties will depend on their willingness to strengthen
respect for human rights.
   The U.S. source said that during Axen's talks, State Department
officials will renew pleas for more religious freedom in East
Germany. That country last year allowed two massive religious
assemblies and permitted the Jewish community to install its first
rabbi since 1967. In recent weeks, however, there has been a
crackdown on environmental groups affiliated with churches, the
official said.
   In talks with Lukanov, the State Department is expected to
request better treatment of Bulgaria's sizable Turkish and Islamic
minorities.
   Lukanov, accompanied by two deputy ministers, the chairman of
the foreign trade bank and presidents of several leading Bulgarian
foreign trade companies, has been invited to an April 25
question-and-answer session at U.S. Chamber of Commerce
headquarters in Washington.
   Lukanov ``has a reputation throughout West and East Europe for
his creative mind and ability to articulate issues,'' the chamber
said in its announcement. Formerly deputy prime minister, he
assumed the new post of minister of foreign economic relations last
Jan. 1 ``in recognition of the importance Bulgaria places on
foreign trade and investment,'' it added.
   Bulgaria wants to expand trade with the United States beyond the
current $130 million annual level. The Bulgarians plan to visit Los
Angeles, San Francisco, Chicago and New York on a U.S. tour lasting
through May 2.
   Axen and Shultz also were expected to discuss efforts to settle
financial claims estimated at more than $70 million by Americans
whose property on East German territory was taken during and after
World War II.
   The U.S. and East German officials said they doubted there would
be serious talk about a visit to the United States by East German
leader Erich Honecker, as was reported in a West German magazine.
Honecker is known to be interested in such a visit ``but it isn't
ripe for discussion,'' the U.S. official said.
</TEXT>
