<HEAD>Italian Questioned About Antiquities Found In His Apartment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian professor was questioned by
police after 250 artifacts from as early as Egypt's Pharaonic
period were found in his apartment, a police source said.
   The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said on
Wednesday that police searched the apartment in Cairo's fashionable
Zamalek suburb on a tip that the Italian was dealing in stolen
artifacts.
   In addition to the Pharaonic relics, searchers found artifacts
from the Greco-Roman, Coptic and Islamic periods of Egyptian
history.
   Italian Embassy spokesman Vincenzo Grassi identified the man a
professor at an Italian government-run technical school in Cairo.
Grassi said although an investigation was under way, the professor
had not been charged in the case.
