<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Judge-Hope     04-07 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Judge-Hope,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Comedian's Daughter-in-Law in Line to Replace Bork on Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judith Richards Hope is the likely nominee to
replace defeated Supreme Court nominee Robert H. Bork on a federal
appeals court here, a Justice Department official says, but the
daughter-in-law of comedian Bob Hope won't comment on the
possibility.
   President Reagan's nomination of Ms. Hope as a judge of the U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia is ``on
course,'' the official, who asked to remain anonymous, said
Wednesday.
   The FBI and the American Bar Association have been conducting
background investigations of Ms. Hope, a lawyer in private practice
here.
   Bork resigned from the bench in February, four months after his
nomination to the Supreme Court was defeated by the Senate in a
bitter fight.
   Ms. Hope reportedly turned down the judgeship originally but
changed her mind after a call from Reagan. She declined to comment
on her possible nomination.
   Ms. Hope, 47, was national co-chairwoman of Lawyers for
Reagan-Bush in 1984 and was general counsel to the presidential
campaign of Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan.
   She is a partner in the Washington office of Paul, Hastings,
Janofsky & Walker, which has its headquarters in Los Angeles. She
is married to Hope's son, Tony Hope, also a lawyer here.
   The opening on the appeals court here is potentially a crucial
one for the Reagan admnistration. The 11 judges on the court are
sharply divided ideologically, with six generally regarded as
conservatives and five as liberals.
   The court is considered among the most important federal appeals
courts because it handles disputes over governmental regulations
and programs.
   Judges are appointed for life. The current annual salary is
$95,000.
</TEXT>
