<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BinderTwins     04-07 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Binder Twins,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Binder Twins En Route To West Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Separated Siamese twins from West Germany were
sent home from Johns Hopkins Hospital on Wednesday, seven months
after an operation to separate their skulls and circulatory
systems, the hospital said.
   With gifts of toy blue jays _ the symbol of Johns Hopkins
University _ Benjamin and Patrick Binder, 14 months old, were
discharged to return home with their parents to Ulm, West Germany.
   They were accompanied by several friends and a doctor from
Hopkins, who traveled with the boys as a precaution.
   Benjamin will go home immediately, but Patrick will spend at
least several days in a West German hospital for observation. He
stopped breathing March 13 after choking after a feeding.
   They were separated in a lengthy operation in September.
   Doctor said Tuesday the boys have the potential to lead normal
lives, but emphasized that their development has been severely
delayed. They function at the level of an infant 2 to 5 months old,
doctors said.
   The plans for the 14-month-old twins' trip were kept secret at
the request of the parents.
</TEXT>
