<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     04-07 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Works On New York, Pennsylvania Primaries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SWARTHMORE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis'
effort to widen his delegate lead in the race for the Democratic
presidential nomination took him briefly out of New York and into
Pennsylvania, where he visited his alma mater.
   The visit to Pennsylvania was one of dozens expected from
candidates in the three weeks before the state's April 26 primary,
when 178 Democratic delegates are at stake.
   ``We're going to pick up probably half of their time while
they're in New York'' campaigning for 225 delegates at stake there
April 19, said Larry Yatch, state Democratic Party chairman.
   Dukakis, holding a slight edge over Jesse Jackson after winning
the Wisconsin primary Tuesday, spent the first part of the
following day in New York. There he promised to be a president who
wars on drugs and homelessness at home and supports Israel abroad.
   In Pennsylvania, he visited Swarthmore College, where he
received a bachelor's degree in political science in 1955.
   Dukakis said he was optimistic about his chances in the
Pennsylvania primary and he expects to win his share of the state's
large black and ethnic populations, despite the presence of Jackson.
   ``Both of us care about people,'' he said. ``We care about
important human values.''
   Dukakis said he had sought Pennsylvania Gov. Robert P. Casey's
endorsement, as he has Gov. Mario Cuomo's in New York, ``but, as in
the case of Governor Cuomo, that's a decision that only he can
make, and I respect whatever decision he does make.''
   Casey has said he will not make an endorsement.
   During his visit to Swarthmore, a 1,300-student liberal arts
college, he was reintroduced to old classmates and professors and
given such mementos as a college baseball cap and a physics book.
   Dukakis also met with local Democratic officials and his
southeastern Pennsylvania finance committee.
</TEXT>
