<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lifer-Bride     04-07 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lifer-Bride,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Marries Man Just Before He's Sentenced To Long Prison Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 18-year-old man married a woman he had
never seen outside of jail or the courtroom five minutes before he
was sentenced to 27-years-to-life in prison for murder.
   Joseph Mastropietro and his 30-year-old bride, Antoinette Natale
exchanged vows in a state Supreme Court judge's chambers shortly
after his sentencing judge refused to perform the ceremony, said
defense attorney Gaspar Castillo Jr.
   Mastropietro, of Troy, was convicted for his role in the 1987
stabbing death of 81-year-old Irene Farrell in the Albany suburb of
Watervliet. A companion, Lloyd Cummings, received an
18-years-to-life sentence.
   Mastropietro was introduced to Natale, an Albany hairdresser,
during a jailhouse visit shortly after he was arrested in March
1987, Castillo said.
   The pair corresponded frequently and Natale visited Mastropietro
in jail, the attorney said. She faithfully attended her future
husband's murder trial. A few days before the sentencing,
Mastropietro told his lawyer he wanted to get married.
   ``I attempted to discourage them because they really didn't have
an opportunity to formulate a relationship,'' Castillo said. ``They
insisted that they wanted to get married.''
   Natale, dressed in a plain white dress for her wedding, said she
didn't want people thinking she's foolish for marrying
Mastropietro. ``I love him and I believe he's innocent,'' she said
before ducking away from reporters.
   Castillo said Albany County Court Judge Joseph Harris refused to
marry the couple, but delayed sentencing to give the lawyer a
chance to find a judge who would perform the ceremony. Supreme
Court Judge Edward Conway agreed.
   Mastoprietro couldn't have been married after the sentencing
because under state law, prisoners serving life sentences cannot
get a marriage license, Castillo said.
   During the ceremony, Natale gave a ring to Mastropietro, who
couldn't reciprocate.
   The lawyer said he wasn't sure when the couple will have the
chance to be alone together. Only some New York prisons allow
conjugal visits, but there's a long waiting list for the privilege,
he said.
   ``I spoke to this woman at length and she's committed to this
young man,'' Castillo said. ``I'm not sure if it's love or the kind
of human concern that develops for another person that doesn't have
anything to do with romantic love.''
   Castillo said he's appealing Mastroprietro's conviction.
   Mastroprietro was given the maximum sentence.
   Harris rejected Castillo's bid for leniency in sentencing
Mastropietro, saying ``what happened here transcended the normal
bounds of society.''
   Farrell was found stabbed in her home on March 8, 1987.
Mastroprietro and Cummings had gone there with the intent of
stealing her car. The woman's hands were tied and she was stabbed
three times in her side. Doctors said she lingered for several
hours before dying.
</TEXT>
