<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GangSweep     04-07 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gang Sweep,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Task Force Moves Against Gangs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Police Department launched a new
enforcement sweep Wednesday night against gang members whose
violent behavior has shocked the nation's second-largest city in
recent weeks.
   About 260 officers joined in Wednesday night's sweep. The task
force concentrated on gang ``hot spots'' in four police
jurisdictions, said police Lt. John O'Connell.
   ``There's been scattered reports of shots fired,'' O'Connell
said, indicating accounts of police hearing gunfire. ``But as of
right now we haven't had any shootings.''
   Officers set up a mobile booking unit in the Los Angeles
Memorial Coliseum where they were processing dozens of people
arrested for a variety of suspected offenses, including parole
violation and weapons possession.
   A department bus was taking those arrested to jail.
   Last year, more than 400 people died from gang violence.
District Attorney Ira Reiner said if current trends hold, that
number will be topped this year.
   On Tuesday, a city finance committee approved an additional $2.5
million for police to use in fighting the city's unrelenting gang
violence.
   The added $2.5 million was expected to win final approval from
the City Council on Friday. It would pay for 1,000 extra officers
to be deployed in gang-infested areas and would cover police
overtime costs in fighting gang violence.
   Shootings like one Friday that killed one person and injured a
dozen others have created an emergency situation, city officials
say.
</TEXT>
