<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0409EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugTown     04-07 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Town,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Ring and Bribes Ensnare Police, Fire Chiefs and County
Officials</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Johnie in 7th graf is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drug ring openly run by a small-town
fire chief, police chief and their families was protected by a web
of bribes that has implicated two county sheriffs and
commissioners, according to court documents.
   The latest to agree to a plea bargain in the case involving the
town of Kermit was Mingo County Sheriff Charles E. ``Eddie''
Hilbert, who is trying to avoid trial on 13 felony counts alleging
that he bought his job for $100,000 and then protected the ring,
court documents say.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Joseph F. Savage called Hilbert's
alleged activities ``the most appalling abuse of public office
since Napoleon gave away the monarchies in Europe to his
relatives.''
   The joint federal-state probe began two years ago when
investigators discovered drugs being sold so freely in Kermit, a
town of 700 in Mingo County, that undercover officers were able to
photograph a ``No Drugs Today'' sign posted outside a trailer.
   So far, the investigation of the ring, which sold cocaine, PCP
and other drugs, has netted more than 50 convictions or guilty
pleas, with no acquittals.
   Among those serving sentences of up to 16 years for operating
the ring are former Kermit Fire Chief Wilburn Preece; his wife,
Virginia; their son-in-law, former Police Chief David Ramey; and
their four sons and two of their daughters. A third daughter was
placed on probation.
   Hilbert will be sentenced in federal court on April 18, the same
day as Johnie Owens, a one-time Mingo County Democratic chairman
and sheriff accused of selling his sheriff's job to Hilbert. Owens
faces up to 14 years in prison and $700,000 in fines.
   An court order filed Tuesday provided no further information on
Hilbert's proposed plea agreement. Hilbert would face a maximum
sentence of life imprisonment without parole if convicted of all 13
counts.
   In an interview this week, Owens denied knowing about the Preece
drug operation when he sold his job, but said ``it's going to be a
better Mingo'' because of the investigation.
   ``If nothing else, it's made people realize that it was wrong.
Even if they knew it was wrong, they didn't know the extent it was
wrong,'' he said.
   Hilbert, who is free on $100,000 bail and continues to serve as
sheriff, could not be reached at his office Wednesday night, and
his home number was unlisted.
   Owens said he accepted a $20,000 downpayment on the $100,000
bribe from Hilbert, then persuaded the three county commissioners
to accept his resignation and appoint Hilbert in exchange for half
of the bribe.
   Former Commissioner Rastie Runyon Jr. has pleaded guilty to
federal income tax evasion charges related to the bribe and awaits
sentencing later this month. Commissioner Steve Adkins, the only
member of the 1982 panel still in office, was indicted Jan. 15 on
one count of bribery. He has denied the charge but is not running
for re-election.
   The third commissioner, state Sen. H. Truman Chafin, has not
been charged in federal or state court. He has adamantly denied any
knowledge of the sale of the sheriff's office.
   Also caught by the investigation was county political boss Larry
Hamrick, who pleaded guilty to three felony charges of protecting
the Preece drug ring, using public funds for political campaigns
and intimidating a witness.
   The indictment against Hilbert accuses him of two counts of
racketeering in connection with buying both his office and a spot
on a powerful county political slate from Owens. He also faces two
counts of aiding and abetting the Preece family drug operation ``by
seeing to it the law wasn't enforced'' in return for illegal
campaign contributions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
