<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     04-07 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Pleads For Money, Respect For His Qualifications</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson gave a spirited defense of his
credentials as he pleaded with supporters to provide him the funds
to finish the last stage of the race for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
   ``The only hope for the campaign's success is to believe in it
enough to invest in it,'' Jackson said Wednesday at a fund-raiser
at an Indianapolis nightclub, which approximately 650 people paid
$20 apiece to attend.
   Jackson is a close second to Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
in the number of delegates won. Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore is a
distant third.
   Jackson said his campaign's ability to survive financially
through delegate-selection procedures in 40 states shows his
management skill.
   That skill plus his ability to set a moral tone for the nation
and to voice the concerns of the averae American make him qualified
to be president, Jackson contended.
   ``Some officeholders are not leaders, and some leaders are not
officeholders,'' Jackson said. ``If tomorrow morning, you were
about to lose your job, among those who are running, Republican or
Democrat, who would you want to argue your case?''
   In a 30-minute speech, Jackson said that although he hasn't held
public office, he has experience negotiating in labor disputes, the
Middle East and in farm crises.
   Holding office shouldn't be a criterion for running for
president, he said.
   ``Most Cabinet members who run the government on a day-to-day
basis haven't held a government office,'' said Jackson. ``You want
somebody to argue your case, here am I.''
   At his first stop in Indianapolis on Wednesday, Jackson
predicted that his campaign stands against drugs and for farmers
will inspire a wide range of people to vote for him in Indiana's
May 3 Democratic presidential primary.
   Jackson declined to say that he will win the primary and the
largest share of Indiana's 79 delegates, but he said his
involvement should stir voter interest and increase participation.
   The 2{-hour event was also beamed by satellite to seven other
locations in Indiana and sites in eight other states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
