^___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Governor Names Team for April 19 Primary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis, wooing New York state's
255 Democratic convention votes, is promising to be a president who
wars on drugs and homelessness at home and supports Israel abroad.
   Dukakis issued a list of more than 200 prominent New York
Democrats supporting his candidacy and formally named Reps. Gary
Ackerman of Queens and Louise Slaughter of Rochester as his
chairmen in the campaign for the April 19 primary at a rally in a
senior citizen center in part of the city's biggest Greek-American
enclave.
   Among the four cochairman of the Dukakis state campaign was
Michael Del Guidice, Gov. Mario M. Cuomo's former chief of staff.
   Cuomo has not endorsed any of the Democratic hopefuls and the
state's other top elected Democrat, Mayor Edward I. Koch, says he
wants Cuomo for president.
   The other state cochairmen for Dukakis are former New York City
Council President Carol Bellamy, former Congressman Herman Badillo
and labor leader Victor Gotbaum.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senator's Wife Says Don't Count Him Out of Democratic Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
says her husband shouldn't be counted out of the Democratic
presidential race or chastised for criticizing the other contenders
for the nomination.
   His message is that he is the only Democratic candidate with
experience in both the federal government and foreign policy, Mrs.
Gore said Wednesday during a series of stops in Indiana to help
kick off her husband's campaign for the May 3 Hoosier primary in
which 79 delegates are at stake.
   ``I think it's a three-man race,'' she said during a stop at a
Salvation Army center in Indianapolis. ``I think we did very well
in Wisconsin considering we got a late start there.''
   Gore polled 17 percent of the votes in Wisconsin to finish third
behind Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson.
   Gore was criticized by Jackson supporters after he said recently
that Americans are choosing a president, not a preacher, and should
look at candidates' experience in public service.
   ``He's just drawing the differences between his leadership and
the other candidates in the race,'' Mrs. Gore said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kean Says Equal Rights Amendment, Urban Issues Should Be In GOP
Platform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Thomas H. Kean says he wants the Equal
Rights Amendment and urban issues to be addressed at the Republican
National Convention in August.
   Kean made the remarks at an impromptu news conference following
a public ceremony in his outer office.
   He said he has long pressed for the ERA to be a plank in the GOP
platform. At the party's convention in New Orleans, Kean said, he
will again push the amendment, as well as proposals to boost aid to
cities and improve the quality of education.
   Kean said he is ``trying to see that many of those things get
into the platform as possible'' although he acknowledged that
``what does make a difference is what the candidate says, because
that will be, in effect, the platform.''
</TEXT>
