<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Conservatives Will Hold Out For Delegates Of Their Own Choosing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington's conservative Republicans concede
Vice President George Bush will win a first ballot nomination to be
their party's presidential candidate.
   But they say they still stand ready to fight for delegates of
their own choosing because they believe Bush delegates might not be
conservative enough.
   ``We want to send delegates to the national convention that
believe in the traditional conservative set of principles that have
governed the party in this state since 1976,'' said Steve Sego, who
was Sen. Bob Dole's Western-states coordinator.
   ``Republicans in Washington State have steadfastly supported the
Reagan Revolution and its conservative principles. It's imperative
that we continue to support these principles in New Orleans,'' said
Jim Summers, the Dole for President Washington State co-chairman.
   This weekend the second phase of selection of 41 Washington
Republican delegates begins.
</TEXT>
