<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GridlockBuster Bjt   04-07 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gridlock Buster, Bjt,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Electronic Device Would Help Drivers Beat Gridlock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relief may be in sight for frustrated
motorists trapped on California's gridlocked highways _ in sight,
that is, on a 4-inch dashboard video screen.
   As part of a pilot traffic management program unveiled Wednesday
by the state Department of Transportation, little black boxes will
alert drivers to road congestion and traffic accidents on
electronic road maps displayed on the dash.
   The sophisticated devices, which transportation officials used
last year to help monitor traffic during Pope John Paul II's visit
to Los Angeles, will then help motorists snake their way around
traffic problems by flashing alternate routes on the screen.
   ``This system will help the user avoid problems rather than
driving into and becoming part of the problem itself,'' Department
Director Robert K. Best said at a news conference announcing the
project.
   The $1.6 million test of the system will begin this summer in
Los Angeles. During the study, which is a joint project involving
the department, the Federal Highway Administration and General
Motors, drivers hired by the state will cruise the congested Santa
Monica Freeway in 25 cars equipped with the units.
   On-board computers will relay the location and speed of the cars
to the the state agency's traffic operations office in Los Angeles,
improving the accuracy and timeliness of traffic reports the
department relays to media outlets.
   To operate the device, a driver inserts a cassette containing an
electronic map of an area up to 10 miles from the car and selects a
destination. An arrow on the 4-inch-square screen then traces the
vehicle's progress along roads.
   The state agency currently uses television monitoring and
electronic road sensors placed every quarter-mile along 300 miles
of Los Angeles' most congested freeways to gather road information.
   Los Angeles, notorious for its rush-hour traffic, is the only
area now wired to accommodate the two-way, high-tech navigational
system, which will utilize the sensor monitoring system.
   A similar system for 215 miles of congested freeways in San
Francisco would cost $130 million, officials said.
   The units, which are commercially available for about $2,500
apiece, will cost between $300 and $500 when they are
mass-produced, officials said. But even if the pilot program goes
well, it may be 10 years before the technology is perfected and the
system is available to most drivers.
   In a test run after the news conference, officials were
embarrassed when one of four units failed to work properly.
   ``This one needs to be recalibrated, I guess,'' said driver Don
Juje, of the state agency. ``I guess we pushed too many buttons.''
   Nevertheless, officials heralded the beginning of the project as
an important next step.
   ``If we want to continue to make owning and operating a car a
pleasure instead of a chore, one challenge our industry must take
up _ and quickly _ is improving the commuting experience,'' said
Dr. William G. Angew, director of programs and planning for General
Motors.
   GM is providing the cars and support personnel for the project.
   The state is contributing $900,000, and the federal agency is
providing $750,000 and technical assistance.
   More than half of all congestion is caused by accidents and
incidents that distract drivers' attention, officials said.
   Urban congestion ``can't be solved entirely by more asphalt and
concrete,'' said Robert E. Farris, an official with the federal
agency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
