<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FamilyHouse     04-07 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Family House,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parents of 28 Children Get Keys To 15-Bedroom Dream Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM COUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FIFE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob and Linda Cornyn and 23 of their 28
children pulled up in the family bus and then received the keys to
a 15-bedroom, eight-bathroom dream house remodeled for them with
government help.
   ``This is all very exciting,'' said Cornyn, a 42-year-old chief
warrant officer stationed at nearby Fort Lewis who has been in the
Army for 24 years. ``We're all very ecstatic.''
   The Cornyns adopted 25 of their children, including some who are
South Korean, Colombian, Indian, Amerasian and black and some with
disabilities.
   Some are wheelchair-bound or move about on crutches. They all
help care for each other.
   ``We have a rainbow family,'' said Cornyn. ``We have just about
every color there is. We look at the rainbow as God's promise.''
   The family, except for three children who were in school and two
in a hospital, were at Wednesday's ceremonies.
   ``Perhaps in the future we'll need more bedrooms,'' said Mrs.
Cornyn. ``But this is a dream come true. Somebody believed in us
enough to help us. This is something we thought would never
happen.''
   Excited smiles shone on the faces of the children, who range
from age 8 months to 26 years, as they explored the
5,620-square-foot house.
   It has eight bathrooms, a downstairs family room that takes up
nearly the entire floor and two washing machines, dryers and
dishwashers. A yard big enough for a softball game surrounds the
rambling white house at the end of a tree-lined road in this rural
town 30 miles south of Seattle.
   ``I have two children. Believe me, you've got to be
courageous,'' said Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., who presented the keys
to the Cornyns. ``It's touching and rewarding to see a family like
this.''
   The house was remodeled at a cost of $60,000 by the Pierce
County Housing Development Association, which was formed last April
24.
   Called Project 30 because the Cornyn family numbers 30, the home
purchase and remodeling job is the first project undertaken by the
association, which is leasing the house to the Cornyns.
   The Cornyns were high school sweethearts in Michigan who married
as soon as Linda graduated. They adopted their first child when the
family was stationed in South Korea in 1979.
   ``I guess we do it because it feels good and it's the right
thing to do,'' Coryn said. ``It just makes us feel good to help
someone else. We enjoy seeing these children grow physically and
mentally.''
   He noted that many of his adopted children would be in
institutions if he and his wife hadn't adopted them.
   Cornyn said some of his adopted children received supplemental
Social Security benefits and the family also receives food from
local food banks and clothes from ``lots of people.''
   The Cornyns are the largest family housed under the U.S.
Department of Housing and Urban Development's housing voucher
program, receiving $700 monthly toward rent and utilities.
   The Cornyns are moving from a six-bedroom home in Puyallup to
their new home, which has been expanded during the past six months
from eight bedrooms.
   ``It seems like we've never had enough room,'' said Cornyn.
</TEXT>
