<HEAD>Pleads Innocent To Drug Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigator in the state attorney general's
office who worked on the Tawana Brawley case pleaded innocent to
drug charges and was being held early today on $100,000 bail.
   William West, 39, a state investigator for 14 years, and
Clarence Holder were arrested early Wednesday after selling three
ounces of cocaine to an undercover officer for $2,800, police said.
   West pleaded innocent to one felony count of criminal sale of a
controlled substance, two felony counts of criminal possession of a
controlled substance and other minor charges. Holder was being held
pending arraignment.
   State Attorney General Robert Abrams said West was one of 12
investigators on the Brawley case, but was taken off the case
Monday. He joined Abrams' staff in 1987 and has no record of legal
or disciplinary problems, Abrams said.
   Miss Brawley, a 16-year-old black from Wappingers Falls, says
she was abducted, raped and abused by six white men in November.
She has refused to cooperate with authorities investigating the
case.
