<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0615EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DoctorGlut     04-07 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Doctor Glut,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Aging Baby Boomers May Run Out of Doctors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The aging baby boom generation may run out of
doctors early in the next century as a widely predicted surplus of
physicians turns into a shortage, according to reports released
today.
   The authors of two reports, both published in the New England
Journal of Medicine, contend that a feared doctor glut won't
happen. But at least one of the experts who has forecast an
overabundance of physicians says he is not ready to change his mind.
   Several studies during the past decade have forecast that the
United States will have too many doctors by the year 2000, and
recommend that the nation train fewer of them. But now, with that
date just 12 years away, there are signs that opinion may be
swinging the other way.
   In one of today's reports, Drs. William B. Schwartz of Tufts
Medical School and Frank A. Sloan of Vanderbilt University predict
that at best, there will be just enough doctors by 2000 but a mild
shortage is possible.
   In the other, less detailed paper, Dr. Ernest P. Schloss of the
University of Arizona looks into the early decades of the next
century.
   ``It is entirely possible that for the majority of people who
are alive today, there may be another shortage just when they will
need doctors the most _ after 2011, the year in which the first of
the baby boom generation will turn 65 and enter their retirement
years,'' he concludes.
   In general, the doctors argue that the earlier predictions
overstated the supply of doctors and underestimated the demand for
their services. However, Schwartz said those predictions already
have had an impact.
   ``Many college students are looking on medicine as an
unpromising career, in part because they are being told that there
is going to be a huge physician surplus,'' he said in an interview.
``That is undoubtedly one of the factors that has led to a sharp
reduction in the number of applications to medical school,'' which
have fallen 15 per cent since 1981.
   Schwartz' report projects that 592,000 physicians will be needed
by the turn of the century, and 585,000 will be available.
   Dr. Robert G. Petersdorf, president of the Association of
American Medical Colleges, has been warning of a coming doctor glut
for years. He said Schwartz' study makes assumptions about
physician supply and demand that may be wrong.
   ``I agree with the authors that the presumed projected
oversupply should not act as a deterrent to choosing medicine as a
career,'' Petersdorf said. ``At the same time, I am not prepared to
state that an oversupply does not exist. The support for such an
assertion is based on assumption and not on fact.''
   One of the most widely quoted of the earlier projections was a
report in 1980 of the Department of Health and Human Service's
Graduate Medical Education National Advisory Committee. It
predicted that in 2000, there will be 144,700 too many physicians.
   However, Schwartz said that and other predictions greatly
overstated the supply of doctors. The biggest mistake was assuming
that all of the nation's doctors will be treating patients.
Instead, Schwartz said that about 93,000 of them will be
administrators, teachers and researchers.
   Another miscalcuation, he said, was failing to take into
consideration the impact of the growing proportion of female
doctors, who, studies show, work about 10 percent fewer hours than
their male counterparts.
   The researchers also did not foresee a movement to require
resident physicians to work shorter hours in large teaching
hospitals.
   Schwartz said the earlier predictions also made a mistake by
assuming that the demand for physicians will remain constant.
Instead, he said, the demand for care has been growing at an annual
rate greater than 1 percent for several decades. The availability
of new kinds of care, such as exotic imaging machines, transplants
and genetic analysis, may speed up the demand for more doctors.
   Other factors that could increase demand, he said, include the
increasing age of the population, wider medical insurance coverage
and the AIDS epidemic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880407-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0648EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpaceShuttle     04-07 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Shuttle,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aug. 4 Space Shuttle Launch Threatened By Engine, Rocket Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discovery, scheduled to make the
first post-Challenger space shuttle flight, is beset by persistent
technical problems which could delay its scheduled Aug. 4 liftoff.
   In recent weeks, there have been troubles with fuel and oxidizer
pumps, engine controllers and booster rocket insulation.
   ``We've always said Aug. 4 is the target, and like most targets,
it's the bull's eye,'' said Thomas Utsman, deputy director of the
Kennedy Space Center. But the technical troubles ``certainly are
going to make that target a small bull's eye.''
   ``I still think from where we are today, an August launch is
achievable,'' he said.
   The problems have forced NASA to delay the rollout of the
shuttle to the launch pad by a week, from May 24 to June 1. Also
delayed a week, until June 22, is a 20-second firing of Discovery's
three main engines with the vehicle locked onto the pad.
   Hugh Harris, a NASA spokesman, said there are several days of
contingency time built into the launch preparation after June 22,
and ``although there are problems, we haven't given up on early
August.''
   A decision on whether to postpone could be made April 14 when
senior NASA managers meet at the Johnson Space Center in Houston.
However, officials said a launch date assessment might not be made
until after technicians finish assembling the two soild fuel
booster rockets in late May.
   The newest problem cropped up Tuesday: a faulty controller in
one of Discovery's in-flight maneuvering engines. Replacement is
expected to take two or three days.
   Workers also are removing and checking the high-pressure
oxidizer turbopumps from each of the three main engines, a
procedure that is taking several days.
   Earlier, the hydrogen fuel turbopumps in all three main engines
had to be replaced after a defective weld was found in a non-flight
pump.
   Technicians also are repairing several small areas on a segment
of a solid fuel booster rocket. In these areas, insulation
separated, or debonded, from the steel rocket casing either before
or during shipment here from the Morton Thiokol plant in Utah.
   Failure of a joint on one of Challenger's two solid fuel
boosters caused the shuttle's explosion and loss of its seven crew
members in January 1986. The shuttle fleet has been grounded since
then.
   The redesigned booster has undergone extensive redesign and
successful test-firings in Utah. Three more full-scale tests must
be passed before the rocket is certified for flight. These are
scheduled April 20, June 3 and July 6.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
