<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brite--StrandedSeals     04-07 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brite--Stranded Seals,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stranded Seals Need New Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGANTINE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two young hooded seals that beached
themselves earlier this year are now healthier and in need of a new
permanent home, but finding one isn't as easy as calling a zoo.
   Wookie and Sweet Pea may be adorable seal pups now, but they
eventually will become rather ferocious adults weighing more than
700 pounds each, said Robert Schoelkopf, director of the Marine
Mammal Stranding Center.
   In addition, a zoo or aquarium must have the proper refrigerated
pool to keep the seals comfortable, he said.
   ``I'm afraid this is a passing-through facility only,'' he said
of the non-profit center he runs.
   The two female seals beached themselves on Long Beach Island in
late January and early February, Schoelkopf said. Wookie was sickly
and bald; Sweet Pea was extremely ill and emaciated. Both had
bronchial infections that took weeks to clear, Schoelkopf said.
   The seals have regained their strength, fat and rambunctious
energy, barking at each other and romping in the center's pool, he
said. Now they must find a colder home ``or else I'll have to start
buying a lot of ice cubes,'' he said.
   ``Refrigeration is not so much the problem at this point, but we
start seeing stranded porpoises and sperm whales this time of
year,'' Schoelkopf said. ``There's no way I can put them in with
the hooded seals. ... These seals are not known for their
friendliness.''
   He said that releasing the seals to the wild would also be a
poor solution because they have become fairly docile.
   Sweet Pea is estimated to be only a few months old and eats only
when hand-fed. Wookie, believed to be about a year old, has bald
spots and could not survive sunburn, her rocky native coast of Nova
Scotia or skirmishes with other animals, Schoelkopf said.
   Hooded seals, named for the fleshy snouts of the adult males,
normally are never found south of Nova Scotia, Schoelkopf said.
That made them 1,500 miles off course when the reached New Jersey.
   ``It's like us planning to go to Florida and winding up in South
America instead,'' he said.
   He said the ideal situation would be to find a benefactor
sympathic to the plight of the stranded seals and other stranded
marine mammals who would donate enough money to build a nearby
facility for them.
   ``It would be a great tax writeoff, and we'd even name the place
after them,'' Schoelkopf said, only half-jokingly.
   The marine specialist has contacted an animal placement agency
in Texas that spread the word about the seals. In the past two
weeks, however, no one has expressed an interest.
   ``We're not trying to find just anyplace _ we want the animals
to go somewhere where they will be cared for properly,'' Schoelkopf
said. ``I want somewhere that has federal permits to handle these
animals, not a roadside attraction.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
