<2ND_LINE>PM-Binder Twins,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Siamese Twins Return Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Separated Siamese twins Benjamin
and Patrick Binder returned to West Germany today, seven months
after an operation in the United States separated their skulls and
circulatory systems.
   The twins arrived at Frankfurt airport this morning on a
Lufthansa flight from Washington, D.C., Lufthansa spokesman Richard
Gessner said.
   He said the twins were immediately taken by a private jet to an
undisclosed destination in southern West Germany. Gessner said he
did not know who had arranged for the private jet.
   The boys, now 14 months old, were released from Johns Hopkins
Hospital on Wednesday. Their parents, Theresia and Josef Binder,
accompanied them on the flight.
   The were also joined by several friends and a doctor from Johns
Hopkins, who traveled with the boys as a precaution.
   Benjamin will be allowed to go home immediately, but Patrick is
to spend at least several days in a West German hospital for
observation. Patrick's progress has been slower since he stopped
breathing briefly when he choked during a feeding on March 13.
   The two were separated during a lengthy operation in September.
   Doctors at Johns Hopkins said on Tuesday the boys have the
potential to lead normal lives, but emphasized that their
development has been severely delayed.
</TEXT>
