<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SovietTrade     04-07 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Trade,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Initiative Will Spur U.S.-Soviet Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration cabinet has approved a
plan to spur trade with the Soviet Union despite worries that a
stronger Soviet economy could help its military, The New York Times
reported today.
   Commerce Secretary C. William Verity won the approval for the
initiative after two months of discussions in which the Pentagon
raised reservations while the Treasury and State departments gave
strong support, the newspaper said.
   The plan calls for the two countries to form high-level working
groups to prompt exchanges in the areas of food processing, energy,
construction equipment, medical products and the services sector.
   The meetings are scheduled to be held in Moscow next week, when
Verity and 500 American business executives will meet with Soviet
officials including leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Last year, U.S.-Soviet trade totaled $2 billion, down from $4.5
billion in 1979. Verity has said he hopes to see bilateral trade
reach $5 billion to $10 billion a year.
   ``The U.S. is going to have to get used to the idea that the
Soviets are good trading partners,'' Verity said. ``It's going to
take time to prove that this is beneficial to both sides.''
</TEXT>
