<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Turner'sCastle     04-07 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turner's Castle,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Glenn Turner Property To Go On Auction Block</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-story, 16-room castle owned by
onetime motivational entrepreneur Glenn Turner is going on the
auction block, with the Internal Revenue Service and other
creditors splitting the proceeds.
   Turner, 53, created a $300 million empire in the 1970s by
selling distributorships in his Dare to be Great and Koscot
International companies. But his empire collapsed after state and
federal investigators accused him of operating pyramid schemes that
bilked thousands of investors.
   Turner, imprisoned in Arizona prison for fraud, has owed the IRS
millions of dollars in back taxes for more than a decade, and the
agency has succeeded in foreclosure proceedings against the
property in Seminole County.
   The unfinished castle, its boathouse, stables and surrounding 79
acres will be sold to the highest bidder after a federal court
hearing April 26, according to court documents.
   The IRS, which had a $15 million claim, has been awarded a
judgment of $9.275 million, but appraisals put the value of the
Turner property at $1 million to $2 million.
   Before the IRS gets its share, Seminole County has the right to
collect $16,900 in unpaid property taxes for 1987, said county Tax
Collector G. Troy Ray.
   Private investors also have claims against the property for
$200,000 in tax certificates, under which they paid the taxes and
earn 18 percent interest until the property is sold and the tax
amounts are paid back to them..
   Turner and his family haven't paid property taxes since 1979,
but investors bought tax certificates equal to the back taxes each
year.
   U.S. District Court documents in Orlando indicate there are
dozens of other Turner creditors, but it is unlikely they will be
paid from any proceeds from the Castle's sale, officials said.
   Bids on the Castle property will be advertised over the next few
weeks to notify any other bidders of the pending sale.
   The castle and boathouse have been vacant for several years, and
the castle has been used only for tours by the public for
charitable events.
   Turner, the son of a South Carolina sharecropper and a
self-styled country boy, rose to fame in the early 1970s through
inspirational speeches that promised great wealth if people bought
distributorships in his operations.
   The companies collapsed in 1973 under lawsuits filed by
investors and investigations by state and federal agencies.
   Turner and a partner, Edward Rector, 57, were sentenced to seven
years in prison in Arizona in August on charges of operating a
pyramid scheme there and defrauding investors through a
self-motivational company called Challenge Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
