<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0730EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     04-07 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain in Michigan After Floods; Thunderstorms, Showers Over East
Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell across eastern Michigan today after causing floods
that washed out roads and flooded basements, while scattered
showers and thunderstorms dampened part of the East Coast.
   Stormy weather Wednesday brought winds gusting to 75 mph to
Indiana, Illinois and Kentucky, cutting power to thousands of
people and damaging buildings, including the world's highest, the
Sears Tower in Chicago.
   Rain today also fell in much of the Ohio Valley and the central
and southern Appalachians.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms fell in Maryland, Delaware
and eastern sections of Virginia and North Carolina. Thunderstorm
winds gusted to 49 mph on Cape Hatteras, N.C.
   Scattered rain dampened extreme Northern California and the
Northwest, with snow in the Cascade Mountains. Accumulations of 6
inches or more were expected in the Cascades in Washington and
northern Oregon.
   On Wednesday, a storm dumped more than 2{ inches of rain in
southern Michigan, flooding small streams and creeks and washing
out or flooding roads in Eaton, Clinton and Calhoun counties.
Basements were flooded in Eaton County.
   In Ohio, flood warnings remained in effect for the Saint Joseph
and Tiffin rivers.
   Winds gusting to 75 mph in Chicago cracked or blew out more than
60 windows in the Sears Tower, sent a 13-foot spire plummeting 28
stories from the top of the Wrigley Building and whipped waves up
to 20 feet high in Lake Michigan.
   High winds knocked out power to 30,600 customers in northern
Illinois, but most were expected to have electricity restored
today, utility spokesmen said.
   Gusts up to 74 mph were reported in Indiana and Kentucky.
Scattered power outages, minor building damage or downed trees were
reported. Winds of 40 to 50 mph were reported in northeast
Tennessee.
   High temperatures set records for the second straight day
Wednesday. Records dating back to 1910 were broken or tied in 14
cities in California, Arizona, Montana, North Dakota, New York,
Florida and Ohio.
   The mercury hit 93 degrees in Bakersfield, Calif., exceeding the
record set in 1960 by 3 degrees. In Tucson, Ariz., it was 92
degrees. The old mark of 91 degrees was set in 1952.
   Today's forecast called for rain across the upper Ohio Valley
and from New York to North Carolina; scattered showers, with snow
in the mountains, from the northern Pacific Coast to the northern
Rockies; strong gusty winds in the northern half of the Rockies and
much of Georgia and Alabama; and sunny skies across the Midwest and
the southern third of the nation.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 60s or 70s in much
of the nation; 40s and 50s from the northern Pacific Coast to
western Montana and from the Great Lakes to much of the Ohio
Valley, the Appalachians and the northern half of the Atlantic
Coast; 80s in the southern and central Plains and South Florida;
and 80s and 90s across the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 26
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 77 degrees at Key
West Naval Air Station, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 53 windy; Boston 40 cloudy; Buffalo 49 rain;
Charleston, S.C. 52 fair; Cincinnati 41 rain; Cleveland 39 foggy;
Detroit 43 windy; Miami 70 partly cloudy; New York 42 cloudy;
Philadelphia 43 drizzle; Pittsburgh 47 rain; Portland, Maine 38
showers; Washington 50 drizzle.
   _Central: Bismarck 44 fair; Chicago 42 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
53 fair; Denver 51 partly cloudy; Des Moines 41 fair; Indianapolis
42 windy; Kansas City 47 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 45 fair;
Nashville 51 windy; New Orleans 56 fair; St. Louis 47 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 53 fair; Anchorage 25 fair; Las Vegas 63
fair; Los Angeles 63 fair; Salt Lake City 59 cloudy; San Diego 65
fair; San Francisco 52 partly cloudy; Seattle 39 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 39 cloudy; Toronto 46 showers.
