<2ND_LINE>PM-Musician Shot,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jazz Guitarist in Serious Condition After Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police searched today for two teen-age
suspects in the shooting of Grammy Award-winning jazz guitarist
Larry Carlton, who was wounded when he apparently surprised
intruders at his Hollywood Hills home.
   Carlton, 40, was in serious but stable condition today at St.
Joseph Medical Center in Burbank after undergoing four hours of
surgery, said nursing supervisor Debbie Fox.
   Police say he was wounded in the neck Wednesday afternoon after
he apparently encountered intruders in his hillside home in the
exclusive Lake Hollywood area, 10 miles northwest of downtown.
Detectives were looking for two teen-agers between the ages of 14
and 17.
   ``They were seen with a small German shepherd puppy,'' said
police Detective Ron Ito. ``We have no description of any vehicles.
All we know is they fled on foot down the hill.''
   Carlton's secretary was working at an office in the home when
the shooting occurred.
   ``She has no idea why it happened. We have no motive at this
time,'' Ito said.
   Carlton won a best pop instrumental performance Grammy this year
for his version of the Doobie Brothers' ``Minute By Minute,'' and
shared the same award in 1981 with pianist Mike Post for their work
on the ``Hill Street Blues'' theme.
   The musician toured with the Fifth Dimension vocal group during
the 1960s and was a member of the Jazz Crusaders during the early
1970s.
   His most recent work is the ``Discovery'' album, released by MCA
Records in last June.
</TEXT>
