<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Pozderac     04-07 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Pozderac,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Yugoslav Vice President Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hamdija Pozderac, who quit as vice
president in September after being linked to the nation's biggest
postwar financial scandal, died in Sarajevo, the Tanjug news agency
reported. He was 64.
   The official agency said Pozderac died in a hospital Wednesday
``as a result of a brain stroke which he suffered on March 29.''
   He resigned the vice presidency Sept. 12, 1987, after his name
was associated with the scandal surrounding Agrokomerc, a Bosnian
food-processing company that issued more than $1 billion worth of
uncovered bills of exchange.
   At the time, Pozderac said his resignation was of a ``principled
nature.'' If he had stayed in office, he would have taken over
Yugoslavia's rotating presidency this May.
   Pozderac's stance last September suggested he accepted no blame
for the Agrokomerc scandal.
   Several Yugoslav media reports have suggested, however, that
such fraud could not have taken place without the knowledge of
Pozderac and other Bosnian Communist leaders.
   Tanjug said the Yugoslav Communist Party chief, Bosko Krunic,
expressed condolences to the Pozderac family and praised Hamdija as
a man ``who dedicated his life to socialism.''
   Funeral plans were not immediately announced.
</TEXT>
