<2ND_LINE>PM-Penn-Trespassing,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Juveniles Sentenced In Penn Trespass, But Sentence Undisclosed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FERNANDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two juveniles convicted of
trespassing at the Malibu home of actor Sean Penn and rock star
Madonna have been sentenced, but authorities refused to disclose
the outcome of the case.
   Authorities say Penn and Madonna confronted three men in their
home when they returned home shortly after midnight on Jan. 20.
Penn subdued one of them after a struggle by hitting him on the
head with a bottle of salad dressing.
   One alleged burglar was identified as Richard Barcelo, 20, of
Chino. He has pleaded innocent to misdemeanor charges of prowling
and assault.
   But authorities never released the names of the two juveniles,
who faced sentences ranging from confinement at the state youth
authority to probation.
   Prosecutors refused to discuss the case after Wednesday's
sentencing, citing state law involving juveniles.
   ``They were disposed of,'' said Andy Reynolds, a spokesman for
the Los Angeles District Attorney's office.
   Penn plays a rookie cop in ``Colors,'' a film about Los Angeles
gangs scheduled to be released next week, and starred in ``Bad
Boys'' and ''The Falcon and the Snowman.''
</TEXT>
