<DOCNO> AP880407-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0908EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pakistan-Afghan     04-07 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Afghan,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says U.S., Soviets Agreed on Aid Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Afghan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq was
quoted as saying today that the United States and Soviet Union have
agreed to continue aid to the warring sides in Afghanistan, so a
peace accord can be signed ``any time.''
   The official Pakistani News Agency quoted Zia as telling
Parliament: ``According to unofficial reports, the two superpowers
have agreed on the symmetry under which both would be able to
provide continued assistance to their respective allies in
Afghanistan.''
   The issue of a cutoff of aid to the U.S.-backed Afghan
guerrillas and the Soviet-backed Afghan government has stalled the
Geneva peace talks.
   The Soviets have rejected U.S. demands that the cutoff be
simultaneous. The Soviets say their aid to Afghanistan's government
can't be compared to foreign aid to the insurgents, and they
maintain the issue is outside the scope of the Geneva talks.
   The news agency's report didn't elaborate on the ``unofficial
reports'' that Zia mentioned. It quoted the president as saying
that ``the Geneva accord could now be signed any time.''
   Zia also was quoted as saying that his country would continue
providing humanitarian assistance to the estimated 3.5 million
Afghan refugees in Pakistan until they can return home with
``dignity and honor.''
   According to the report, Zia told Parliament that Pakistan,
which has not provided military assistance to the Afghan
guerrillas, will not do so in the future. He said the United States
will continue to carry out that task.
   He said the United States was Pakistan's ``old ally'' with which
it enjoyed positive relations, the report said. The Afghanistan
situation had brought the two countries close, the president was
quoted as saying.
   On relations with the Soviet Union, Zia said there was no
dispute between the two countries.
   ``With the resolution of the Afghanistan issue, friendship
between the two countries would be strengthened. There exist
avenues for it,'' the news agency quoted him as saying.
   Zia also praised the Soviet leadership which, he said, had
``carried forward possibilities of friendship.''
   Zia also thanked individuals who he said had contributed to
reaching an Afghan settlement.
   In particular, he noted Diego Cordovez, the mediator in the
U.N.-sponsored peace talks, and U.N. Secretary-General Jose Perez
de Cuellar.
   He also praised the Western press, which he said had played a
``commendable role'' in keeping the Afghan issue alive.
</TEXT>
