<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru   04-07 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0531,0759</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Claims Warplane Raid On Baghdad, Iraq Responds With Six
Missiles</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq bombed each other's
capitals and other towns today in one of the fiercest exchanges in
their ``war of the cities.'' Scores of people were reported killed
and wounded.
   The deadly duel erupted at dawn after Iran said squadrons of its
warplanes bombed Baghdad twice in the first air raids on the Iraqi
capital in more than two years.
   The official Iraqi News Agency said only one Iranian jet got
through to Baghdad and was shot down by an Iraqi interceptor inside
Iran after being driven away from the capital by heavy
anti-aircraft fire.
   But Iraq then loosed six long-range missiles against Tehran and
the cities of Karaj, the holy city of Qom, Isfahan and Tabriz, the
agency reported. Iran also reported bombing the northern Iraqi city
of Erbril and the southern ports of Basra and Umm Qasr.
   The sudden escalation overshadowed talks to resume in New York
between United Nations Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
and Iran's deputy foreign minister, Mohammed Larijani, on efforts
to arrange a cease-fire in the 7{-year-old Persian Gulf war.
   ``Iran is determined more than ever to punish this criminal
regime in Iraq for its aggression,'' Larijani said after a meeting
Wednesday, indicating little change in Tehran's refusal to accept
the U.N. Security Council's July 20 cease-fire resolution.
   Today's sharp upsurge in hostilities came on the eve of
parliamentary elections in Iran. Officials fear the Iraqis will
launch a missile blitz when voters go to the polls Friday.
   Both sides reported scores of civilians killed or wounded in
today's missile attacks on Tehran and Baghdad and other cities as
well as air raids and artillery bombardments.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia,
said Iranian jets penetrated ``sophisticated radar and
anti-aircraft defenses'' ringing the Iraqi capital to ``heavily
bomb selected targets.''
   It said the first raid at 6:05 a.m. scored ``accurate hits.''
   Another formation of fighter-bombers streaked above the city of
5 million people 10 minutes later, IRNA reported.
   IRNA said all the jets returned safely to their bases, but did
not say how many were involved in the attacks or give any details
of their targets.
   Although Iraq said only that one Iranian jet got through to
Baghdad and was shot down, the ferocity and scale of the Iraqi
bombardment indicated that the Iranian claim was probably true.
   It was one of the most widespread missile barrages the Iraqis
have unleashed since the latest bout of the ``war of the cities''
exploded Feb. 29.
   Iran said Iraqi warplanes also bombed Tabriz and other cities in
western Iran. In retaliation, the Iranians said they fired two
missiles into Baghdad and battered ports of Basra and Umm Qasr, an
Iraqi naval base, with 13 short-range missiles.
   Basra and other Iraqi border cities were hammered with artillery
fire, IRNA reported.
   IRNA said that other formations of Iranian warplanes attacked
Iraqi troop concentrations in Al-Amara, north of Basra, and other
areas in the southern front, ``inflicting heavy losses.''
   The Iranians have had some 250,000 men massed east of Basra for
weeks. But despite repeated air raids on Iraqi defenses, they have
made no move to launch a long-awaited offensive against the city.
   INA said two Iranian warplanes also bombed the northeastern city
of Erbil, killing several civilians.
   IRNA said Iranian fighter-bombers also attacked a headquarters
of the National Liberation Army, an Iraqi-based dissident movement
seeking to topple the Tehran regime, in the northern Diyala region,
``destroying all their targets.''
   Iran's air force has been badly depleted by combat losses and a
chronic shortage of spare parts.
   Outnumbered by around 8-to-1 by Iraq's powerful air force, it
has not raided Baghdad since early 1986. But in recent months it
has become increasingly aggressive.
   IRNA said the Iranian air raids ``completely caught the enemy by
surprise.''
   It said the warplanes destroyed Iraqi military basses in
Baghdad, ``killing or wounding dozens of soldiers.''
   IRNA quoted Iran's air force commander, Brig. Gen. Mansour
Sattari, as saying the bombing raids were ``unique and very
valuable militarily.'' He did not elaborate.
   Half of Tehran's 6 million people have fled the capital since
Feb. 29. Both sides have fired nearly 300 missiles into each
other's cities, killing hundreds on both sides.
</TEXT>
