<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Marshal,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>County Presses Charges Against Marshal Who Faked His Own Abduction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLUE MOUNTAIN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charges of trespassing and
disturbing the peace have been filed against an officer who
authorities say admitted he faked his own abduction in hopes of
gaining the attention of his estranged wife.
   District Attorney Joe Gay filed the charges Wednesday in Tippah
County Circuit Court against former Blue Mountain town marshal Gary
Stokes. If convicted, Stokes could face up to a year in prison and
$1,000 in fines.
   Stokes, the only lawman in the town of 870, was fired Tuesday by
the Board of Aldermen.
   About 200 law officers and volunteers searched for Stokes after
his patrol car and gun were found outside a store where he
reportedly had gone to investigate a burglary last week.
   Stokes reappeared early the next day in Myrtle, about 20 miles
southeast of here, saying he had escaped from his captors. But
relatives later said Stokes told them he'd staged the abduction to
gain the attention of his estranged wife.
   State Highway Patrol investigators said Stokes spent the night
following his disappearance in an abandoned house and then hiked
through the woods to Myrtle.
