<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0929EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Ethiopia-Relief     04-07 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ethiopia-Relief,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Condemn Ethiopian Order to Expel Relief Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Ethiopian rebel group charged today
that the Ethiopian government was trying to starve people by
ordering foreign relief workers to leave the war-torn and
drought-plagued regions of Eritrea and Tigre.
   ``The Eritrean People's Liberation Front calls on all charitable
organizations and those cooperating with them to oppose the
dergue's (Ethiopian leadership's) inhuman step and to help the
starving people in any way possible,'' the rebels' clandestine
radio station said in a broadcast monitored in Nairobi.
   Ethiopia's central government Wednesday told international
relief agencies to recall all their foreign workers in Eritrea and
Tigre ``to avoid personnel security risks'' from rebels.
   The government asked donors and the relief agencies to turn over
their operations to the Relief and Rehabilitation Commission, the
government agency responsible for drought and famine relief.
   The rebel radio said the order was intended ``to starve the
people of Eritrea and Tigre and cow them into submission.
   ``For this purpose, the dergue intends to put the charitable
organizations' food, vehicles and other services to military use,''
the broadcast said.
   Eritrean rebels have been fighting for 27 years against the
central government in Ethiopia. It is Africa's longest civil war.
   In neighboring Tigre, another separatist group, the Tigre
People's Liberation Front, has been fighting for 14 years.
   The fighting has disrupted relief efforts in both regions, where
crop failures threaten 3.5 million people with starvation. Overall,
nearly 7 million Ethiopians are facing famine without outside help.
   There are about 60 non-governmental relief organizations working
in Ethiopia, but only a few operate in Eritrea and Tigre.
</TEXT>
