<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SoldierofFortune     04-07 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soldier of Fortune,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Convicted Of Charges Related To `Soldier of Fortune' Murder
Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Tennessee man who offered no defense
on charges of directing an attempted contract murder that began
with a Soldier of Fortune magazine advertisement was quickly
convicted by a federal court jury.
   Jurors deliberated for about 1{ hours Wednesday before reaching
the verdict against Richard Michael Savage.
   ``The evidence was overwhelming,'' U.S. District Judge James
DeAnda told the jury after it convicted Savage on all seven counts
in a federal indictment.
   Savage, 39, was accused of arranging attempts on the life of
Colorado businessman Dana Free, including the Oct. 12, 1985,
grenade bombing of a Houston-area home.
   Free escaped that attack and two previous attempts in Atlanta to
bomb his car.
   The trial began Monday and prosecutors rested their case
Wednesday. Defense attorneys did not call any witnesses.
   Court-appointed defense attorney Michael Brown said he chose not
to present testimony because of Savage's prior criminal convictions
and a similar trial he faces in Georgia.
   Brown said he plans to challenge one of the counts against
Savage because he believes it charges him twice for the same
offense.
   DeAnda set sentencing for May 20. Assistant U.S. Attorney Gary
Cobe said Savage could receive as much as 40 years in prison and
fines totaling $1.75 million.
   Savage was indicted in 1986 on federal charges he accepted
$20,000 from a Colorado woman, Alice V. Brado, to arrange the death
of Free, and later carried out attempts to have Free killed. Ms.
Brado claimed Free absconded with her $300,000 life savings.
   She found Savage through a ``Gun for Hire'' an ad in Soldier of
Fortune, according to the indictment.
   Ms. Brado pleaded guilty and died while serving a five-year
prison term in Kentucky.
   Three other people named in the indictment have pleaded guilty,
and testified that Savage directed the operation from Knoxville,
Tenn.
   Savage is serving a 40-year Florida state prison term for
arranging the beating death of the former assistant city manager of
West Palm Beach, Fla., in an attack arranged through a Soldier of
Fortune advertisement. He also has been sentenced to 25 years in a
federal prison for an Arkansas conviction for attempted
murder-for-hire and threatening a witness.
   Savage's trial was moved from Houston, due to publicity from an
unrelated civil suit in which a jury in Houston found
Colorado-based Soldier of Fortune negligent and awarded $9.4
million to the family of a woman killed in a contract arranged
through an advertisement in the magazine.
</TEXT>
