<DOCNO> AP880407-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0945EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpeedLimit-Fatalities     04-07 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Speed Limit-Fatalities,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rise In Fatalities Linked To Higher Speed Limit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 65 mph speed limit appears to be
partially to blame for a nearly 50 percent increase in traffic
deaths on rural interstates in New Mexico, the first state to raise
its limit a year ago, an official says.
   Ninety-five accidents resulting in 110 deaths were reported on
rural stretches of interstate highways in New Mexico between April
2, 1987, the day the law went into effect, and March 31.
   Howard Graff, chief planner of the New Mexico Traffic Safety
Bureau, said 64 crashes resulting in 74 deaths were reported for
the corresponding period the previous year.
   ``My opinion is that it looks like (the new limit) has had an
effect,'' Graff said Wednesday. ``Rural interstates are supposed to
be the safest of roads, with wider shoulders, medians and all
that.''
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration released
figures last summer indicating traffic fatalities increased
nationwide about 50 percent within three months of the new speed
limit taking effect. States were allowed to boost speed limits to
65 only on interstate highways outside urban areas.
   Graff said traffic deaths in New Mexico more than doubled in the
first three months after the increase, but stabilized during the
winter.
   Al Lauersdorf, a highway safety specialist for the National
Safety Council in Chicago, said it is too early to detect a trend
nationally.
   ``My own personal observation is that there are some places
where you can do 65 and no one passes you with the exception of the
occasional leadfoot, and there are others where, if you go 65,
everyone's going by you,'' he said. ``It just doesn't seem to be
consistent in any way.''
</TEXT>
