<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 5thLd-Writethru a0525 04-07 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0525,0850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede HAWWARA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Settlers Call for Revenge at Funeral for Teen-age Settler</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY8</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with funeral, quotes from Shamir, Arabs
wounded. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARNEI SHOMRON, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Jewish
settlers, some shouting ``Revenge! Revenge!'' attended the funeral
today for an Israeli girl stoned to death by Arab villagers.
Earlier, settlers attacked Arab cars and homes.
   Under heavy army guard, settlers carrying Israeli flags strung
with black ribbons buried 15-year-old Tirza Porat, who was killed
Wednesday during a clash between settlers and Arab villagers in the
West Bank town of Beita.
   ``Near the fresh grave of Tirza Porat, God will avenge her
blood. The heart of all the people boils over,'' Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir told about 9,000 mourners.
   ``Every killing strengthens and unites the Israeli people, links
it more to this land, deepens its roots here. The rioters and
instigators will not achieve a thing. They are leading their people
to tragedy,'' he said.
   Shamir was interrupted by cries of ``Revenge!'' and ``Expel the
Arabs!'' Many in the crowd carried M-16 rifles or pistols.
   The body, wrapped in a black tarpaulin bearing a white Star of
David, was carried in a 25-minute procession from the Elon Moreh
settlement, where the girl had lived, through the heart of the Arab
city of Nablus and past several Arab villages, to the Jewish
cemetery in Karnei Shomron.
   Tirza was the first Israeli civilian to die in four months of
unrest in the territories occupied by Israel since the 1967 Middle
East war. According to U.N. figures, 140 Arabs have died, and one
Israeli soldier has been killed.
   Israeli troops shot and wounded two Arabs today during clashes
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Hospital officials said Fathi
Mahmoud Sirhan, 20, of the Beach refugee camp in Gaza was wounded
in the chest and another 18-year-old Arab from the West Bank's
Qabatieh was shot in the abdomen.
   The army announced it had destroyed four Arab homes in Beita
belonging to villagers suspected of attacking the settlers.
   Thirteen Israelis were injured in the incident Wednesday.
According to army accounts, it began after Arabs stoned a group of
teen-agers on a hike. Israeli guards accompanying the hikers fired
on the stone-throwers, killing two Palestinians and wounding two,
the army said.
   Arab witnesses said the clash was provoked by Israelis. They
said the guards fired without provocation on Arab villagers and
that the villagers then charged the Israelis.
   Justice Minister Avraham Sharir proposed demolishing houses in
Beita and expelling hundreds of villagers allegedly involved in the
violence.
   Rabbi Eliezer Waldman, a Parliament member from the West Bank's
Kiryat Arba settlement, echoed the call.
   ``With an Arab village in which a pogrom on Israeli children
takes place, there's nothing else to propose but to destroy all of
the village, to wipe it out from the land of Israel,'' he told
Israel's armed forces radio.
   Throughout the night and into this morning, settlers attacked
Arab homes and cars, despite appeals by Defense Minister Yitzhak
Rabin and Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, armed forces chief of staff, not to
retaliate for the slaying.
   Some called for Beita residents to be expelled to Lebanon and
for authorization allowing soldiers to shoot anyone throwing stones.
   Raja Salem, who had a swollen lip and a cut on his face, told a
reporter he was beaten up by settlers in the Arab village of
Hawwara, near Beita.
   ``Every house on the main road is in danger of attack now. They
want to retaliate. They want to kill us,'' he said.
   Aly Ahmed, 57, another resident, said ``everyone has clubs and
stones but that is not enough to face guns. Settlers using guns
come to humiliate us, but if we fight them, they will kill us.''
   The Maariv daily reported that dozens of villagers identified as
attackers by the Israeli teen-agers were detained Wednesday night.
It said they included a woman and her daughter suspected of killing
the girl to avenge the death of their cousin, who was killed during
the clash.
   Army spokesmen declined comment on the report.
   The army announced it was extending the closure of Arab schools
until May 8. The 850 Arab schools and five universities attended by
300,000 students have been closed since Feb. 4.
   Rabin, speaking on armed forces radio, said that Arabs
responsible for the attack had been arrested and would be punished.
He didn't say how many were arrested, and he noted that some Arabs
had tried to protect the Jewish teen-agers.
   Dozens of settlers held a vigil Wednesday near Beita and
announced they would build a settlement at the site of the clash.
   Leading right-wing politicians such as former Defense Minister
Ariel Sharon went today to Elon Moreh. About 100 men and women
gathered at the Porat home. Many of the men held M-16 rifles in
their laps as they waited for the funeral to begin. Some wept.
</TEXT>
