<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Cuomo 1stLd-Writethru a0431 04-07 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuomo, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0431,550</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 7th graf to CORRECT that Jackson finished second in
Illinois.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, in an interview
published today, was sharply critical of Democratic presidential
contender Albert Gore Jr. for his attacks on rivals Michael Dukakis
and Jesse Jackson.
   ``It does not work, and it's terribly dangerous,'' Cuomo said of
the negative campaigning.
   The New York governor told The Washington Post in a telephone
interview that he is unlikely to make an endorsement before his
state's primary on April 19.
   ``The closer you get to primary day, the less reason'' there is
to announce support for one of the candidates, Cuomo said, adding
that he would prefer to remain neutral until after the final
primaries.
   ``That's the time for leadership in this process,'' he said.
   New York, already important by virtue of the 255 delegates at
stake in its primary, takes on an added significance because of the
seesaw race being run by Jackson and Dukakis.
   The two have remained close in the national delegate count.
Jackson finished a strong second in the Illinois primary and had a
major win in the Michigan caucuses; Dukakis came back with
victories in the Connecticut primary, the Colorado caucuses and the
Wisconsin primary.
   Cuomo said he expects the contest between Dukakis and Jackson
``will be very close here.''
   Noting that Jackson had garnered 26 percent of the New York vote
in 1984, Cuomo told the Post: ``You've got to give him 10 points
more than that this year. I'd say, 35 to 40 percent is his base.''
   The governor said his call to hold down negative campaigning was
``intended for all Democrats and specifically for Al Gore.''
   Gore has said both Jackson and Dukakis lack experience in
international issues, and has been particularly critical of Jackson.
   ``It does not work, and it's terribly dangerous and
counterproductive in a primary where one of you will be the
nominee,'' Cuomo told the Post. ``You should not spend a lot of
time criticizing your opponents, especially if you have not
established your own identity in this state.''
   Another politician who has been vocal in his criticism of
Jackson has been New York Mayor Edward Koch. Cuomo said there was
little he could do to get Koch to heed his call to tone it down.
   ``The mayor has already ignored it and will continue to. I have
no hopes of conversion, short of his being struck in the tush by a
bolt of lightning ... and I have no command over the lightning,''
he said.
   Cuomo said he expected about 10 percent of the Jewish vote to go
to Jackson, despite the furor in 1984 over Jackson's reference to
New York as ``Hymietown.''
   ``Most of them (Jewish leaders Gore addressed last week) agreed
with him that Jackson should be defeated, but then the question
comes: Are you, Mr. Gore, the way to do it? The sophisticated ones,
who read the polls, may decide the best way to do it is with
Dukakis.''
   Cuomo said he expected black voters in New York, as they have
elsewhere, to ``go overwhelmingly for Jackson.''
</TEXT>
