<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1018EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PolygamistTrial     04-07 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polygamist Trial,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conspiracy Charge Dropped Against Three As Trial Begins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors and defense attorneys say the
trial of a polygamist leader and three others charged in the
bombing of a Mormon chapel and a 13-day standoff with police will
proceed much more quickly because of the dismissal of a conspiracy
count.
   ``It relieves the government of proving a real complex count and
makes the issues in the case much clearer,'' Fred Metos, attorney
for defendant John Timothy Singer, said Wednesday.
   A pool of 170 potential jurors reported Wednesday to the
courtroom of U.S. District Judge Bruce S. Jenkins, where they
received a 20-page questionnaire and heard the charges.
   The federal charges now include bombing, destruction of the
Kamas Stake Center with an explosive, use of a bomb, attempting to
kill federal agents, assault on federal officers, possession of a
bomb, possession of a sawed-off shotgun and two counts of use of a
firearm.
   Vickie Singer is charged with all eight counts; polygamist
leader Addam Swapp faces all but the shotgun-possession charge;
Jonathan Swapp, who had not been charged with conspiracy, and John
Timothy Singer face the firearms, assault and attempted murder
counts. Jonathan Swapp is Addam Swapp's brother, and John Timothy
Singer is Vickie Singer's son.
   Associate Utah Attorney General Paul Warner said Wednesday that
state prosecutors would wait until after the federal trial to file
homicide charges in the death of corrections Lt. Fred House, killed
during the shootout that ended the siege at the defendants' farm.
   Swapp, 27, appeared in court Wednesday in a buckskin coat
emblazoned with a Mormon pioneer flag. His mother-in-law, Mrs.
Singer, 44, was dressed all in white, including a white bow in her
hip-length hair.
   ``It is turning into a nightmare,'' Metos said.
   ``I've done nothing but criminal law for 10 years, and I never
saw defendants do anything like that to draw attention to
themselves,'' he added.
   Although Jenkins granted the prosecution motion to strike the
conspiracy count, he denied requests from all four defendants to
separate their trials, U.S. Attorney Brent Ward said.
   The judge did not rule on a motion by Swapp that his trial
should be moved out of Utah because of the predominance of the
Mormon Church, which abandoned polygamy in 1890. Jenkins has said
he would rule on the issue during jury selection.
   Swapp has said he was chosen by God to gather the American
Indians for the second coming of Christ.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
