<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Violence     04-07 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Violence,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rival Shiite Factions Battle for Third Day, 18 Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDMOND SHEDID</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABATIYEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shiite Moslem militias fighting for
control of south Lebanon battled today with rocket-propelled
grenades and automatic weapons. Police said 18 people were killed
and 27 were wounded.
   It was the third straight day of violence between the
Syrian-backed Amal militia and the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, believed
to be the umbrella organization for groups holding foreign hostages
in Lebanon.
   Thirty people have been killed and 61 wounded since Tuesday.
   A police spokesman said Justice Minister Nabih Berri's Amal
fighters, backed by armored personnel carriers, were advancing
slowly on Ghaziyeh, a key Hezbollah stronghold six miles south of
Sidon.
   Sidon is the provincial capital of south Lebanon.
   ``If Amal controls Ghaziyeh, then Hezbollah's remaining
strongholds will also fall eventually,'' the spokesman said. He
spoke on condition of anonymity in keeping with police regulations.
   The official said Amal had seized 10 major towns and villages
and that Hezbollah still held four hamlets in addition to Ghaziyeh.
   He said Amal seized Nabatiyeh, a market town 18 miles southeast
of Sidon, in a ``sweeping attack'' before dawn.
   ``Rescue teams are searching the rubble of devastated houses for
bodies,'' the spokesman said.
   Six Hezbollah fighters, their hands raised, walked out of a
gutted house to surrender to Amal after the fall of Nabtiyeh. It
has a population of 50,000 people, most of them Shiites.
   The battle for the town lasted several hours as Hezbollah
fighters, holed up in a school belonging to the town's tiny
Christian community, traded rocket-propelled grenades and mortar
fire with the Amal militiamen.
   Tensions between Hezbollah and Amal have increased since Feb.17
when Amal blamed Hezbollah for the abduction in south Lebanon of
U.S. marine officer Col. William R. Higgins.
   Amal rounded up dozens of Hezbollah members it accused of
involvement in the kidnapping. Hezbollah has denied the Amal
allegations and accused the rival militia of ``harrassing the
believers by searching for an American spy.''
   The Organization of the Oppressed on Earth, an underground group
believed linked to Hezbollah, claimed responsibility for Higgins'
abduction.
   He is one of nine Americans missing after being kidnapped in
Lebanon. American journalist Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Asssociated Press, is the longest-held
foreign hostage. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
