<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Hijack 2ndLd-Writethru   04-07 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Hijack, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0564,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freed Passenger Says There Was No Time To Be Frightened</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with comments from Austrian
passenger. Pick up 5th pvs, `Twelve British...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Hijack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British passenger freed from a hijacked Kuwaiti
jet in Iran was quoted today as saying that two of the hijackers
offered her pillows and drinks and chatted with her daughters.
   An Austrian businessman also released said the seven gunmen were
brutal when they seized the plane but later treated the hostages
well.
   ``We didn't have time to be frightened, things happened so
fast,'' British passenger Jean Sefton was quoted as saying in an
interview with London's Daily Mail. She spoke by telephone from the
Hyatt Hotel in Mashhad, northeast Iran.
   The Foreign Office confirmed today that all 22 Britons on the
plane, which has hijacked Tuesday on a flight from Bangkok to
Kuwait, had been freed. The hijackers were still holding about 50
hostages, including three members of Kuwait's royal family.
   They are demanding Kuwait release 17 convicted pro-Iranian
extremists.
   Austrian Josef Degeorgi, 53, who manages IBM's office in Kuwait,
was freed early today with 31 other passengers and crew members. In
a telephone interview from Mashhad, Degeorgi said the hijackers
were armed with handguns and grenades. All wore masks.
   At the start of the hijack the crew members were forced to lie
on the floor with their hands behind their heads, and some
passengers were handcuffed, Degeorgi said.
   ``At this stage things were quite brutal,'' he said.
   ``But they told passengers repeatedly to be calm, not to worry.
They were really very friendly to us. Some passengers got excited
and needed oxygen. But they (the hijackers) kept reassuring us.''
   
   Twelve British men were among 32 people released earlier today
and had been taken to the Hyatt Hotel, where they were reported
``fit and well,'' the Foreign Office said.
   Irishman Kieran O'Kelly and his wife, Nisran, also were freed.
   Mrs. Sefton and her daughters Jane, 14, and Patricia, 12, were
among 10 British women freed by the hijackers on Wednesday and
later contacted by the Daily Mail in repeatedly interrupted
telephone calls.
   ``One minute I was asleep, the next I was being nudged in the
ribs by my husband and I saw one of the hijackers in the aisle,''
Mrs. Sefton was quoted as saying.
   ``The hijackers weren't always within my view but I saw them and
one said, `Don't worry. Keep quiet.' ... A couple of the hijackers
spoke English and asked if we wanted pillows and drinks and things.
They talked a bit to the children.''
   Relatives of the Britons hijacked on the Bangkok-to-Kuwait
flight were jubilant at the release of their loved ones.
   ``We are obviously very relieved,'' said Brian Stillwell,
businessman father of 23-year-old Scott Stillwell, who was among
those freed today.
   Speaking from his home at Ryde on the Isle of Wight off the
southern English coast, the elder Stillwell added: ``It was an ugly
situation.
   ``These hijackings often end peacefully but who can be sure? It
has been a bad time. We are very pleased at the news. Now we are
waiting for official confirmation, but that could take a long
time.''
   Scott Stillwell, a commercial photographer, had been returning
from a six-month holiday in the Far East with his 19-year-old
girlfriend Elaine McIntosh, who also comes from the Isle of Wight.
She was among the British women freed Wednesday.
   ``We felt so helpless,'' said Margaret Jones, mother of British
hostages Mark Appleby, 23, and Nicola Appleby, 25.
   ``We have just been waiting from one news bulletin to the next,
hoping and praying they would be released,'' Mrs. Jones said from
her home in the western English port city of Bristol.
   Mark Appleby, a graphics salesman, and Nicola Appleby, a travel
courier, had been vacationing in Thailand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
