<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, his bitter fight
for the Republican presidential nomination against Senate Minority
Leader Bob Dole behind him, says he wants Dole to help him win the
general election in the fall.
   The two men met privately Wednesday in the Capitol for the first
time since their angry face-off on the Senate floor last February.
Bush told reporters afterward that they had a ``good, friendly
discussion.''
   At an earlier session in the same building, Dole had lunch with
Pat Robertson, who is continuing a half-hearted campaign to be GOP
presidential nominee. They discussed ways to keep the former
television evangelist's supporters active in Republican politics.
   ``There's no question that we plan to support the Republican
nominee, and it looks as though it's going to be George Bush,''
Robertson said.
   Robertson said he wanted to be ``a rallying point for
conservatives'' at the GOP convention in New Orleans so he could
encourage his supporters to remain involved in Republican politics.
   ``I want to make sure that it's the type of platform that will
make them get in with both hands and both feet and go to work,'' he
said.
   Robertson told The New York Times he would not campaign in New
York before the April 19 primary. His Secret Service protection was
withdrawn at his request Wednesday.
   In an interview published in today's editions of the paper, he
said it would be ``more quixotic than it is realistic'' to continue
actively campaigning.
   A Robertson spokeswoman, Barbara Gattulo, said today he would
make ``two or three'' speeches a week supporting conservative
causes and candidates, and go to the Republican National Convention
``whether we add delegates before then or not.''
   ``He has made a committment to supporters and a number of
candidates in races around the counry at the local level,'' said
Gattulo. ``No matter how many delegates he takes (to the
convention), he will have a voice there. He is also laying the
foundation for years to come, as a conservative voice and for a
future campaign.''
   ``He has already talked about running in 1992,'' she said.
   Robertson had already laid off most of his campaign staff and
has made only a few campaign appearances recently, because he is
bumping up against federal campaign spending limits.
   After his talk with Dole, Bush told reporters that he wanted the
Kansan to work on his behalf ``as much as he possibly has time to
give. A lot of it's here and a lot of it I hope will be around the
country.''
   ``We're ready to go to work,'' Dole said.
   Asked whether the two men had buried the hatchet, Dole said, ``I
don't have a hatchet. I'm a nice fellow.''
   Bush said their conversation focused on ``how to beat
Democrats.''
   Dole spokesman Walt Riker said later that the men talked about
``keeping the Republican nomination interesting until the
convention'' in August and ``ways to get the issues out there.''
   During a Senate vote last Feb. 4, Dole walked up to Bush and
accused him of condoning a campaign attack that amounted to
``groveling in the mud.''
   The face-off was sparked by a written statement made by a Bush
campaign aide implying that Dole accepted favors from the wealthy.
It also said three federal agencies were examining a defunct blind
trust once held by his wife, Elizabeth H. Dole.
   Dole dropped out of the race and endorsed Bush last month.
</TEXT>
