<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Soviet-AfghanExcerpts     04-07 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Soviet-Afghan Excerpts,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Excerpts From Gorbachev-Najib Statement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Soviet-Afghan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from the joint statement issued
Thursday by Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Afghan leader
Najib after their meeting in the Soviet city of Tashkent. The
excerpts were carried in English by the Soviet news agency Tass.
   As a result of the meeting, Gorbachev and Najib arrived at a
common view on the following:
   _The Soviet Union and the republic of Afghanistan will act in
accordance with the statements published on Feb. 8, 1988. These
statements imparted a new impulse to the process of the political
settlement of the most complex regional conflict and made it
possible to place negotiations on the plane of a practical solution.
   _The general secretary of the Communist Party Central Committee
and the president of Afghanistan believe that the last obstacles to
concluding the agreements have now been removed, thanks to
constructive cooperation of all who are involved in the settlement,
and favor their immediate signing.
   Both sides duly assess the role of the U.N. secretary-general
and his personal representative, Diego Cordovez.
   The Afghan president welcomes the readiness of the Soviet Union
and the United States to act as guarantors of the Geneva accords.
   _The Soviet Union and Afghanistan reaffirm that in the event of
the conclusion within the shortest period of the said agreements,
the Afghanistan-USSR understanding that the Soviet troops will be
withdrawn within the period fixed by these agreements, starting
from May 15, 1988, will remain in force.
   _The policy of national reconciliation makes it possible to
settle the situation around Afghanistan, end the war and
fratricide, establish peace throughout the country's territory and
form a coalition government with the participation of all forces
representing Afghan society, including those who are currently
opposed to one another.
   _The final status of their country among other states will be
determined by the Afghans themselves and nobody but them. The
Soviet Union reaffirms its support for President Najib's statement
on Afghanistan as an independent, non-aligned and neutral state.
   It proceeds from the premise that the territory of that country
or any of its part will never be used for purposes hostile to its
neighbors with regard to which Afghanistan will continue a policy
of good-neighborly relations and cooperation.
   This equally applies to the Soviet Union, the People's Republic
of China, the republic of India, the Islamic republic of Pakistan
and the Islamic republic of Iran. The Soviet side backs the Afghan
president's statement to the effect that Afghanistan's internal
structure will rest on a multi-party system in the political field
and on a multi-sectoral basis in the economic sphere.
   _It is of key importance for implementing the policy of national
reconciliation to create satisfactory conditions for the return of
Afghan refugees ... and grant them rights on an equal basis with
all citizens of the country. The Soviet Union will extend
assistance to Afghanistan in creating such conditions.
   _The Soviet Union, relying on relations of traditional and
historical friendship, expresses the readiness to cooperate with
Afghanistan at a high level ... to restore the economy and
facilitate the economic and social development of ... Afghanistan.
   _The general secretary and the president call on other states to
contribute to establishing peace and national reconciliation in
Afghanistan and respect the Geneva accords. This would set a good
and encouraging example for resolving other regional conflicts.
</TEXT>
