<2ND_LINE>PM-Stocks-Collar, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0487,0682</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYSE Limit on Program Trading Triggered For First Time</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with late-morning Dow average
today and to include Japanese, British stock activity. Picks up 3rd
graf pvs, `Although the ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jump in the Dow Jones industrial average
tested the New York Stock Exchange voluntary limit on computerized
program trading for the first time, but Wall Street experts differ
on whether the restriction matters.
   Traders said a cheer erupted on the Big Board's vast floor when
the widely-followed average careened past 50 points at about 3:20
p.m Wednesday, automatically placing the ``collar'' on so-called
index arbitrage trading for the rest of the day. The Dow average
closed at 2,061.67, up 64.16 points.
   The momentum of that rally helped inspire strong buying in Tokyo
today that pushed prices past their pre-crash levels. On the Tokyo
Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues,
which gained 195.82 points Wednesday, gained another 258.05 today,
reaching 26,769.22.
   In London, the London Financial Times 100-share index was up
about 22 points to the 1767 level by late afternoon.
   But as of late morning in New York, however, the momentum
stalled and the Dow Jones average was off about two points to the
2,059 level.
   Although the average had flirted with a 50-point daily up or
down limit at least four times since the restriction was announced
Feb. 4, Wednesday marked the first time the threshold was breached.
   The collar is part of an effort to suppress wild price swings in
the aftermath of the Oct. 19 market crash and restore investor
confidence. Some traders said that without the limit, the Dow
average might have risen as much as 100 points Wednesday, but
others said it was impossible to know.
   ``There was a lot of program trading when the Dow was up between
35 and 49 points,'' said Philip C. Puccio, manager of institutional
trading at Dillon Read & Co. ``It went from 40 to 49 within five
minutes.''
   Several other influences boosted stocks, notably a stronger
dollar and lessening fears of higher interest rates. But many
brokers said program trading played at least a partial role in the
Dow's sudden surge.
   Program trading refers to a sophisticated form of arbitrage, the
simultaneous purchase and sale of similar goods in different
markets in order to profit from price disparities.
   Using computers that instantly place massive orders, program
traders buy stocks in New York and sell corresponding stock-index
futures in Chicago, or vice versa.
   Many brokers have blamed the technique for injecting enormous
volatility _ as well as crushing trading volume _ into the stock
market without regard for underlying stock values. Some studies
have suggested program trading was an important element in the
October crash.
   NYSE spokesman Richard Torrenzano said Wednesday after the
50-point collar was triggered that ``it's not the solution but it's
clearly a first step in controlling what we call intra-day
volatility.''
   Asked how far the Dow average would have moved without the
limit, Torrenzano said, ``If you talked to 10 people you'd get 10
different answers. I have no idea.''
   Robert Gordon, president of Twenty-First Securities Corp., which
utilizies program trading, said he believed the technique wasn't an
element in the Dow's rise Wednesday, largely because the price
disparities between stocks and stock-index futures weren't
profitable enough for widespread arbitrage.
   ``It's sort of a non-event,'' he said. ``Program trading wasn't
fueling the up move. I don't think there was any particular rhyme
or reason to it.''
   Others said the reaching of the limit caused the Dow to retreat
several points before it began moving up again, but at a slower
pace that reflected the absence of program trading's influence.
   ``Without the restriction, I think you would have seen it up 100
points today,'' Puccio said. ``I think the limit is good because it
gives people a little pause to reflect rather than buying with
abandon.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
