<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Presser     04-07 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presser,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Restates Claims That FBI Approved Scheme</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A memo to former FBI Director William Webster
shows he knew as early as 1983 that Teamsters President Jackie
Presser was authorized to take part in ``illegal activities,''
Pressers' attorneys say.
   The memo to Webster was among documents filed in federal court
Wednesday by Presser's lawyers in an effort to show that Presser
had government permission to allow so-called ``ghost employees'' on
the payroll of Teamster Local 507 in Cleveland.
   Presser's lawyers claim the FBI authorized him to keep the
no-show employees, who reputedly had underworld ties, as a way of
gathering information about the mob. Presser has previously
produced the statements of two FBI agents to support his claim of
authorization.
   The government claims Presser; his lawyer, John R. Climaco of
Cleveland; and three FBI agents concocted the authorization defense
in 1985 to protectPresser from indictment.
   Presser, secretary-treasurer of Local 507, and two other union
officials, Anthony Hughes and Harold Friedman, are charged with
racketeering in the alleged $700,000 payroll padding scheme. Their
trial is set for July 12.
   In the memo to Webster, assistant FBI director Oliver Revell
recommended ``that authorization for Jackie Presser to participate
in illegal activities be elevated from the field to FBI HQ
(headquarters).''
   Memos filed Wednesday were intended to rebut a Justice
Department claim that the government did not know about the
authorization until 1985, when Climaco told department officials
about it.
   ``How can the government now claim that it first learned about
authorization on June 11, 1985, and how can it now claim that it
was concocted at or around that time when the director of the FBI
knew about it at least two years prior?'' Climaco said in court
papers with the Revell memo.
   Presser's lawyers say they are having problems obtaining
documents from the government to prepare their defense and have
asked for a hearing on their motion to dismiss the case.
   Wednesday's brief was a response to a brief filed in March by
prosecutors opposing Presser's attempts to have the case dismissed.
</TEXT>
