<1ST_LINE>u a PM-RapeRecant-Dotson 1stLd-Writethru a0527 04-07 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rape Recant-Dotson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0527,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thompson: Tests Shed No New Light on Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Thompson's statement today. No
Pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Genetic tests at a British university
failed to shed any new light on whether Gary Dotson committed a
rape that his accuser later said never happened, Gov. James R.
Thompson said today.
   Dr. Alec Jeffreys, the scientist who conducted the tests, said
the evidence ``was too degraded for analysis'' with the
sophisticated genetic test, the governor said in a written
statement.
   Jeffreys suggested that an alternative test might be able to
analyze the evidence, and Thompson said he would consider that
recommendation.
   The test focused on an article of clothing worn by Cathleen
Crowell Webb at the time Dotson allegedly attacked her.
   Dotson was freed from prison in 1985 after serving six years
when Mrs. Webb recanted the testimony she gave at his trial.
   Earlier this week, Thompson received the results of a
sophisticated genetic test used to compare Mrs. Webb's
semen-stained panties with a semen specimen from Dotson.
   The test was prepared by Jeffreys, a professor at the University
of Leicester, England.
   The test analyzes DNA, genetic building blocks unique to each
person. The test has several drawbacks, including the possiblity of
an inconclusive finding because of the age of the evidence.
   Thompson commuted Dotson's 25- to 50-year sentence to the six
years Dotson had already served after three days of televised
hearings in May of 1985 before the Illinois Prisoner Review Board.
   Dotson, 30, has had brushes with the law since his 1985 release
and says he is an alcoholic. He has been arrested more than a
half-dozen times for violent incidents and traffic violations.
   He is being held without bond in the Joliet Correctional Center
on a parole violation. Under the good-behavior terms of his
``last-chance'' release, Dotson could be forced to serve out the
sentence imposed in the rape case.
</TEXT>
