<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1233EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Alligators     04-07 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alligators,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Plans to Breed Alligators in Spain for Meat & Skin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Danish group plans to set up
Europe's first alligator farm in southern Spain to produce skins
and meat for export, the project organizer said Thursday.
   ``The baby alligators would come from the United States and be
bred at the farm in Spain, but it would take three to four years
before production and export of the reptiles' skin and meat could
begin,'' said Leif Skovgaard in a telephone interview with The
Associated Press.
   Skovgaard, a chartered accountant who is organizing the project
for a group of seven Danish investors, said 10,000-12,000
alligators would be bred yearly at a farm near the town of San
Roque.
   European Alligator Institue, as the project is called, seeks
financial support from the local and state governments in Spain as
well as the European Economic Community.
   The farm, which the group hopes to open by the beginning of
1989, would employ about 100 people, Skovgaard said.
   ``As alligators are dangerous at any age, our personnel will be
specially trained to cope with them so they don't lose fingers,''
he added.
   The project envisions a nature park where visitors can observe
the 9- to 15-foot-long animals in an outdoor environment.
   Skovgaard said he did not anticipate protests from animal
protection or environmentalist groups.
   The group contemplates inviting a representative of the World
Wildlife Fund to sit on the new company's board of directors, he
said.
   The United States banned hunting alligators because the species
was disappearing, but it was lifted recently after the animals made
a comeback.
</TEXT>
