<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spelunkers     04-07 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spelunkers,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rescuers Find Stranded Spelunkers Alive & Well</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARREDONDO, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine spelunkers were found safe and
sound Thursday after being stranded for four days inside a huge
cave that was threatened by rain-swollen underground rivers, a
rescue official said.
   Rescuers emerged from the cave with seven of the cave explorers
just before 7 a.m., said Joaquin Isla, a government Civil Defense
spokesman.
   Two other men decided to continue their trek through the
18-mile-long cave known as Cueto-Coventosa, Spain's second-largest
and a favorite of national and international spelunkers, he said.
   ``Everything went fine until we ran into the swollen waters of a
lake on our way towards the Coventosa exit,'' one of the men
rescued told Spanish National Radio shortly after emerging from the
cave.
   Isla said doctors declared the seven men who emerged from the
cave in good condition, but advised them to eat and get some sleep.
He said the men had been near to using up their food supplies.
   More than 100 cave explorers took part in the search that began
Monday when explorers, who were aged between 18 and 30, failed to
emerge as planned after entering the cave Friday.
   The cave is on the outskirts of Arredondo, 23 miles east of the
northern port of Santander.
</TEXT>
