<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Boland 1stLd-Writethru a0577 04-07 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0577,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Democrat Will Retire After 18 House Terms</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Leads with three grafs with statement as read by Boland,
picks up graf 4, ``Speculation ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Edward P. Boland, author of the
amendments which barred U.S. aid to the Contras in Nicaragua,
announced today that he will retire after 36 years in Congress.
   ``I've decided to call it a day,'' the 76-year-old Democrfat
said at a news conference at Our Lady of Hope School, surrounded by
supporters in the Irish neighborhood where he was born and raised.
   ``The parades are all over. The give and take of the campaign
trail no longer beckons and the time has come when the bell tolls
on a career that has been for me an exhilarating and fulfilling
experience,'' he said.
   Speculation that he might retire led three Democrats _
Springfield Mayor Richard Neal, former Mayor Theodore Dimauro and
state Rep. Kenneth M. Lemanski of Chicopee _ to announce they were
interested in the seat, provided they didn't have to oppose the
incumbent in a primary.
   Boland did not endorse anyone to succeed him.
   The Reagan administration's frustration with the Boland
Amendments inspired the diverion of profits from arms sales to
support the Contras. That operation became a focus of the
Iran-Contra investigation and the recent indictment of former
Marine Lt. Col. Oliver North and others.
   The reserved Boland came to Washington with the man who would
later become the speaker of the House, Thomas P. ``Tip'' O'Neill,
in 1952. For more than 20 years, the two friends roomed together in
an arrangement they described as a real-life ``Odd Couple'' with
Boland, the neat and tidy half of the pair.
   Many expected him to follow O'Neill into retirement in 1986, but
some believed that Boland stayed, in part, in the hopes of taking
over the chairmanship of the House Appropriations Committee.
   Boland is the No. 2 Democrat on the powerful panel and would be
in line for the chairmanship if Jamie L. Whitten of Mississippi
retired. Whitten, who is a year older than Boland, has already
announced plans to run for re-election.
   The son of Irish immigrants who settled in Springfield's Hungry
Hill district, Boland was elected to the Massachusetts House of
Representatives at age 22 and never lost an election in a
half-century in politics.
   Boland served as chairman of the House Intelligence Committee
from 1977 to 1985.
   He remained a bachelor until 1973, when he married Mary Egan,
then the 35-year-old president of the Springfield City Council.
They have four children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880407-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghan-Insurgents     04-07 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Insurgents,0752</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Forming Afghan Counter-Regime</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCHEHEREZADE FARAMARZI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of Afghanistan's fractious
Moslem guerrillas are forming their own regime to challenge the
communist government from ``liberated'' areas when Soviet military
forces are gone.
   The alliance of seven parties, three moderate and four
fundamentalist, has been meeting almost daily to preserve unity
while they lay the groundwork for their own government. ``There is
hope that it will work,'' a moderate leader said.
   ``No doubt, when the Russians leave Afghanistan, Najib's regime
will collapse,'' said Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, head of the alliance.
``To avoid anarchy and possible armed clashes to seize power, it's
necessary that all parties agree to a temporary government.''
   Soviet forces entered Afghanistan in December 1979 and an
estimated 115,000 soldiers now are helping fight the insurgency,
which began after a Communist coup in April 1978.
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Afghan leader Najib issued a joint
statement Thursday saying all obstacles had been cleared in
negotiations to end the war and the Soviets hope to start pulling
their troops out next month.
   In Geneva, the U.N. mediator indicated major differences remain
but Pakistan, where 3.5 million Afghan refugees have taken refuge,
said an agreement was ready for signing.
   The guerrilla alliance has agreed to hold elections among
fighters in Afghanistan and refugees in Pakistan for a council that
would vote on establishing of an interim Moslem government.
   Leaders of the seven groups have named Ahmad Shah as president
and Zabihullah Mojaddedi as his deputy to lead a 21-member Cabinet,
in which each party is to have at least two members.
   A leadership council of the seven guerrilla leaders would
function as the head of state and supervise Ahmad Shah's
government, which would operate from a ``defended'' area beyond the
reach of the Communist government's forces.
   Mohammad Nabi Mohammadi, leader of the moderate Harkat Islami
Party, named five guerrilla-controlled areas: Kunar, Noorestan,
Pakitia, Panjshir and Hazarejat.
   Sebghatullah Mojaddedi, leader of the moderate Afghan National
Liberation Front, said: ``If we come under pressure in one place,
we will move to another.''
   Agreement also has been reached on having a judiciary committee
to settle disputes among the parties.
   ``We will work hard for the liberation of Afghanistank, but the
devil ... may influence some people and encourage disputes,''
Mojaddedi said.
   ``We hope our brothers will understand that, except for unity,
solidarity and compromise, there is no other way to reach our pure
goals. For the freedom of Afghanistan and in order to create true
Islam in Afghanistan, we must put aside all these disputes. There
is hope that it will work.''
   Not all rebel leaders are equally keen on forming an interim
government inside Afghanistan. Ahmad Gailani of the moderate
National Islamic Front of Afghanistan fears it could cut the nation
in half.
   ``If there are two governments in Afghanistan, there is the
danger of partition into north and south or east and west, as with
North and South Korea, or East and West Germany,'' he said.
   Gailani prefers a transitional government in exile until the
Communist regime can be overthrown.
   Yunis Khalis of the hardline Hezb-i-Islami faction expects
outside interference. ``Colonialist countries, the superpowers _
East or West, American or Russian _ have joined hands to prevent
the creation of a total Islamic government in Afghanistan,'' he
said.
   Khalis said Iran, where Shiite Moslems dominate, is urging
Shiite guerrillas to reject a Sunni Moslem government in
Afghanistan, where Sunnis are in the majority.
   ``Therefore, we cannot for certain bring about an Islamic
government in the present circumstances,'' he said. ``This is why
we declare we will not abandon our jihad (holy war).''
   Deep-seated frictions persist. One source Hekmatyar, who is
unpopular even in the hardline camp but recently replaced Khalis as
head of the alliance.
   ``He is not the leader but only head of the alliance. Every
party is independent,'' Mojaddedi said. ``Of course we have had our
complaints. The brothers have warned him that, now that he has
become the head, it does not mean he has all the authority in his
hand to do whatever he likes.''
   Hekmatyar's men have been accused of harassing guerrillas of
other parties, journalists and relief workers traveling to
Afghanistan.
   His party, also called Hezb-i-Islami, has been blamed for the
killing of a British cameraman last year. Hekmatyar has denied it.
</TEXT>
