<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CremationCase     04-07 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cremation Case,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Widow `Not a Cold-Blooded Killer'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUINCY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although police don't consider her a
``cold-blooded killer,'' a woman charged with concealing the
shotgun slaying of her husband last November also is suspected of
shooting him.
   Aida Chapman, 28, was arrested Monday at a relative's home in
Rock Island, where she has lived since moving in mid-December from
the Quincy-area home she shared with her husband and two children,
said Jon McCoy, chief deputy for the Adams County Sheriff's
Department.
   Mrs. Chapman was charged with concealing the death of her
husband, Donald Chapman, 27, whose cremated remains were discovered
March 15 in woods near the Chapman's home, McCoy said.
   No charges have been filed in Chapman's slaying.
   ``We will prove that she killed her husband,'' McCoy said. ``But
there are varying degrees of homicides. Some are lawful and some
are not.
   ``This was not a murder. She is not a cold-blooded killer.''
   McCoy said there was a history of violence between the Chapmans
and that he believes the shooting occurred as Mrs. Chapman as
defended herself.
   McCoy said Mrs. Chapman reported her husband missing Dec. 3
under pressure from relatives who didn't believe her claim that
he'd run out. Chapman was unemployed at the time.
   Mrs. Chapman was released from the Rock Island County Jail after
posting $3,000 bail on the concealment charge. She waived
arraignment and a date for her preliminary hearing in Adams County
Circuit Court has not been set, McCoy said.
   If convicted of the felony, Mrs. Chapman could face two to five
years in prison and a $10,000 fine.
</TEXT>
