<HEAD>Man Convicted of Murder in Robbery Victim's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was convicted of murder after the man he
assaulted nearly five years ago died.
   The jury convicted Christopher Bush, 30, of first-degree murder
Wednesday after deliberating one day in suburban Oakland County
Circuit Court. The victim, Jeffrey Dudley, 24, died last summer.
   Assistant Prosecutor John Slevin argued during trial that
Dudley's health deteriorated steadily after the 1983 attack in
which he was beaten, shot in the heart and dumped in a sewer.
   Bush is serving a prison sentence for robbery and assault.
   Because of the attack, Dudley wore a pacemaker and had undergone
surgery eight times. Doctors had testified the attack caused
permanent heart damage.
   Dudley collapsed June 28 after trying to stop a shoving match
between two players at a basketball game in Detroit. Bush's lawyer,
Otis Underwood argued the fall may have caused his death.
</TEXT>
