<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SportAid     04-07 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sport Aid,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Registration Opens for Second Sport Aid Global Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Global registration began Thursday for a second
Sport Aid ``Race Against Time,'' the six-mile street jog by nearly
20 million people in 1986 that raised $35 million for starving
Africans.
   Organizers are hoping to involve all 218 countries and inhabited
territories in the Sept. 11 extravaganza, compared with 89 nations
last time. Major charities and sports federations in 85 countries
have already joined the Sport Aid '88 campaign.
   ``We're trying to build on that new constituency of
compassion,'' said an organizer, Simon Dring. ``All we can do is to
create a forum for this to happen and say to the world, `Please
join us.'''
   The United States is expected to contribute more this year,
Dring said. Sport Aid was a flop in America in 1986 because it
coincided with a nationwide ``Hands Across America'' campaign to
raise funds for the poor and homeless.
   ``America is America,'' Dring said in an interview. ``It lives
within itself so adequately, it's very difficult sometimes to
involve them in events of this nature.
   ``We're presently in discussions with the American Red Cross and
with a number of major sponsors in America and we believe this year
America will run,'' he said.
   The first person to register for this year's run was Omar
Khalifa, a Sudanese athlete who dramatized the plight of Africa's
famine victims when he carried a burning charcoal ember in an
Olympic torch to 14 countries to launch the May 25, 1986, event.
   Each runner will be given an individual number tag, starting
with Khalifa's No. 1, which he donned during a news conference at
Sport Aid's headquarters in London.
   ``It will give every single individual a common sense of
identity,'' said another organizer, Chris Long.
   The race will start on Sept. 11 when a boy and a girl from each
participating country or territory runs through the streets of New
York to the steps of the United Nations to give the signal for the
worldwide series of raod races to begin.
   Money raised from sponsors of runners and from ticket sales to
the races will go to needy children in mainly undeveloped countries.
   One-fifth of the money raised in developed countries will be put
aside for disadvantaged and disabled children in those countries.
The rest will be split between the United Nations' Children's Fund
and the Red Cross.
   The events will be televised live to an audience of more than
750 million people.
   In 1986, young and old crowded the streets and sidewalks of 279
cities from London to Ouagadougou and from Brisbane to Budapest for
the global race.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
