<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RangeFire-Beer     04-07 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Range Fire-Beer,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beer Truck Welcome In `Dry' Texas County</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's against the law to sell beer or any
other kind of alcoholic drink in Shackelford County, but a beer
truck was welcomed Thursday.
   The Adolph Coors Co. delivered 44,000 pounds of feed grain
pellets made from malt leftovers, a brewing byproduct, for cattle
left without grass because of last month's huge range fire.
   ``I'm sure it (the truck) will turn some heads in Shackelford
County, but there's no beer in there,'' said Bob Livingston,
legislative affairs manager for Coors in Austin.
   County Extension Agent Lawrence Winkler and County Judge Marie
Smith said they didn't know how many head of cattle remained.
Winkler said the majority have been moved out to other pastures.
   The high protein feed supplement should feed the remaining
cattle for four days, Livingston said.
   Officials say the delivery was one of the largest donations to
ranchers since the fire that began March 10 burned more than
300,000 acres in five counties.
   The grain pellets were donated by a Coors division, Coors
Biotech, said Dusty Garrison of state Rep. Rick Perry's office. He
said he understood that Coors employees heard of the fire and began
making arrangements for the donation.
   But while the dry county got help from the big beer company,
beer trucks do go the county, the judge said. ``The two counties to
the east and west of us are all wet.''
</TEXT>
