<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HowitzerPlea     04-07 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Howitzer Plea,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Howitzer Joy Ride Brings Guilty Plea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civilian accused of taking a self-propelled
howitzer for a joy ride with an Army private has pleaded guilty to
a federal misdemeanor charge in exchange for dismissal of a felony
charge.
   Roberto Torres, 26, and Pvt. Norman Clair, 19, took the tracked,
armored Army artillery piece from Fort Carson on Nov. 11 and drove
it up Interstate 25 to Denver, trailed by a parade of police cars.
When the howitzer ran out of gasoline, police arrested the men.
   Clair was sentenced earlier to 15 months in prison on military
charges.
   Torres faces a maximum of one year in prison and a $100,000 fine
as a result of his plea Wednesday to a charge of stealing personal
property valued at $200 or less. He also may be required to pay
restitution of $1,000 for minor damage to the howitzer and to
fences that were broken at Fort Carson.
   The charge dropped was stealing the artillery piece. Assistant
U.S. Attorney Fred Stephens said the 10-year sentence under that
charge was too stiff for what amounted to a joyride.
   U.S. District Judge Jim Carrigan accepted the plea bargain after
making sure Torres had chosen a different mode of transportation to
court.
   ``Yes, we came here together in my car,'' defense attorney
Robert Erler said. ``It gets better gas mileage than the vehicle he
chose for his previous trip.''
   Clair, an ammunition handler, said he got the idea of taking the
howitzer as a means of getting out of the Army after Torrez told
him he was declared schizophrenic and given an honorable discharge
and benefits after stealing a jeep in 1979.
   Torres is on a military disability pension after having been
discharged from the Army for psychiatric problems.
</TEXT>
