<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ChandlerProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0516 04-07 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chandler Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0516,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chandler Apologizes for Racial Remark</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Lexington, KY.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Chandler's news conference today.
NOTE language in 6th graf, `You know ...' CORRECTS in 14th graf,
`Chandler, 89, that Robinson signed with Dodgers in 1946, not 1947.
Also moved on sports wire. No Pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VERSAILLES, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. A.B. ``Happy'' Chandler today
released a statement apologizing for a racial remark he made at a
University of Kentucky Board of Trustees meeting.
   Chandler said Gov. Wallace Wilkinson, who appointed him to a
voting position on the UK board earlier this year, called him today
and ``took me to the woodshed'' for the remark.
   Wilkinson suggested that he apologize but did not request that
he resign from the board, Chandler said.
   ``If he did, I'd resign,'' Chandler said.
   Chandler used the racial epithet Tuesday during a committee's
discussion of the university's 1985 decision to dispose of its
investments in South Africa.
   ``You know Zimbabwe's all nigger now. There aren't any whites,''
he said. About seven of the 20 board members were present.
   Chandler said today at a news conference at his home here he
stands on his record of helping blacks and other minorities
throughout his lifetime of public service as governor, U.S. senator
and commissioner of baseball.
   ``I didn't intend to be offensive to anybody,'' said Chandler.
   In an interview Wednesday with the Lexington Herald-Leader,
Chandler said students who protested the racial slur were ``trying
to make a mountain out of a molehill.''
   ``I don't think I should be censured for this,'' Chandler told
the newspaper. ``I don't think I deserve any harsh treatment.''
   The Student Government Association on Wednesday night approved a
resolution calling for Chandler's resignation from the board.
Earlier, about 40 students marched on the university's
administration building to meet with President David Roselle. Some
carried placards with slogans like ``Hopefully Happy is Sad.''
   Tae Dorham, a member of the American Association of University
Students, said the group demanded an apology from Chandler, and if
that wasn't accomplished, his resignation.
   ``Let's see how far they (students) can go,'' Chandler said in a
telephone interview from his home. ``My whole record, I think, is
good enough to overcome this.''
   Chandler, 89, was commissioner of baseball from 1945-51 and
takes credit for opening the door for Jackie Robinson to become the
first black to play major-league baseball when Robinson signed with
the Brooklyn Dodgers in 1946.
   During a second term as governor, he won praise for his
endorsement of racial integration of schools.
   Roselle told the students that the ``university completely and
totally repudiates'' Chandler's statement. ``It's completely
contrary ... to what we want to have be the belief of the
University of Kentucky,'' he said.
   The university's only black trustee, Edythe Jones Hayes, said
she would ask the board to issue a statement ``to be sure the
public knows this is not representative of the feelings of the
board.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
