<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Israel-TearGas     04-07 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Tear Gas,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0630 to recast headline</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Doctors Fear Tear Gas Could Cause Deaths in Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two doctors say U.S.-made tear gas used by
Israel to curb Arab protests may be causing deaths and injuries to
civilians, but further studies are needed to determine the extent
of the problem.
   ``Adequate research just has not been done,'' said Dr. Howard
Hu, an epidemiologist at the Harvard University School of Public
Health.
   Hu and Dr. Jonathan Fine are associated with Physicians for
Human Rights, a Boston-based group which is concerned that the
Israelis may be misusing tear gas, a chemical agent that overcomes
its victims by causing severe irritation to the eyes, skin and
respiratory tract.
   If tear gas is handled properly, the effects are not
long-lasting, but it can kill people if it is fired in high doses
into enclosed areas.
   ``It would not surprise me if there were deaths of infants or
the infirm'' from too much exposure to tear gas in Israel, Fine
said. ``We believe it is important to do planned studies on this.''
   The American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee, a lobbying
group, claims that more than 30 people have died in Israel and in
the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip from exposure to tear
gas, which also has caused injuries and miscarriages.
   Yossi Gal, a spokesman at the Israeli Embassy, said those
figures are wildly inflated. The Israelis have found only one
probable death attributable to tear gas, he said.
   But the committee has asked TransTechnology Corp., a tear gas
manufacturer in Sherman Oaks, Calif., to halt shipments to Israel
until it determines the substance is being properly handled.
   Israel has bought 120,000 tear gas grenades or projectiles from
U.S. companies under the U.S. government's military sales credit
program since the Arab disturbances began in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip four months ago.
   Burl Alison, a vice president at TransTechnology, said the
company is ``redoubling'' its effort to ensure the material is
being used correctly after the committee ``presented what looked
like evidence that it is being misused.''
   Two types of tear gas _ code-named CN and CS by the U.S. Army _
are made at the company's Federal Laboratories in Saltsburg, Pa.
   ``We are writing to the prime minister (of Israel) to try to get
some attention to the proper use of the product,'' Mrs. Alison said.
   The company also has offered to send staff to train the Israeli
military on how to use the substance, but the Israeli government
has not responded, she said.
   There have been reports from Israel that tear gas was fired into
Al Aqsa mosque in Jerusalem in January, and a canister landed in
Ramallah Hospital in March. It has also been dropped by helicopter
into refugee camps, witnesses say.
   But Gal said it is not the government's policy to fire tear gas
into closed spaces, although some might drift into confined areas.
``It's mostly used outdoors,'' he said.
   Mrs. Alison said tear gas is a safe, effective way to control
crowds if directions are followed, and TransTechnology has no plans
to stop selling to Israel.
   ``Even if it is misused, you would see much more grief and many
more fatalities and injuries if it weren't available,'' she said.
   Each batch of tear gas sold to Israel must be licensed under the
Arms Export Control Act, which requires recipients to live up to
U.S. human rights standards. In 1985, the United States refused to
sell tear gas to Korean police because of that country's poor human
rights performance.
   A State Department official, speaking on condition he not be
named, defended the Israelis' use of tear gas, and said the U.S.
government has not investigated any reports of misuse.
   ``We think maintaining order should be in the most humane way
possible,'' the official said. ``One of those ways is tear gas.''
   Fine of the human rights group said the long-term effects of
tear gas have been ``understudied and underreported.'' He added:
``I wouldn't belittle the problem.''
   Since disturbances began in the occupied territories four months
ago, at least 138 Arabs, one Israeli soldier and one Israeli
civilian have been killed.
</TEXT>
