<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SuedSpouse     04-07 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sued Spouse,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules Woman Must Divorce Spouse To Sue Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman trying to collect $100,000 from
her husband for a broken foot must divorce him if she wants to
proceed with the suit, the Third District Court of Appeal has ruled.
   Florida law prohibits spouses from suing each other, the court
ruled.
   The dilemma is part of Shoemaker vs. Shoemaker, a case in which
Aleta Shoemaker of Key West slipped and fell while trying to help
her then ex-husband, Michael, tidy up his house.
   After the May 23, 1985, injury, Michael moved into Aleta's
apartment to care for her.
   ``He had to,'' she said in her disposition. ``I couldn't help
myself. I had no one to help me.''
   A few months later, while her merchant marine husband was back
at sea, Aleta sued him. ``I felt he owed me,'' she said.
   But when Michael returned, they re-married.
   The suit hasn't soured the second marriage, Aleta said. ``He
feels responsible and he doesn't like to discuss it.''
</TEXT>
