<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MarineHearings Bjt   04-07 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marine Hearings, Bjt,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women Investigated in Lesbianism Probe at Marine Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARRIS ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chants of women recruits jogging
in the warm April sun drift through the open windows of the Law
Center at the Marine Corps Recruit Depot.
   Inside, Marine officers are continuing an investigation of
lesbianism, which has already led to charges against several former
drill instructors and at least one officer.
   Five women Marines have been charged with various counts
including committing indecent acts. Two other women who were due to
go before administrative hearing boards are seeking discharges.
   Each year, 20,000 recruits graduate from the 11-week basic
training program at Parris Island. One of the four recruit
battalions is made up of women and Parris Island is the only base
that provides basic training for the 10,060 women in the Corps.
   At least 10 women are under investigation and the probe by the
Naval Investigative Service is likely to expand, according to a
Marine who said she's a target and who has leaked word of the
investigation in letters to a number of news organizations.
   ``Every base I've been on has had one of these so-called witch
hunts,'' said the woman.
   ``One of the reasons I went to the press is to show there's an
injustice being done,'' said the woman, who spoke on the condition
her name not be used. ``If they're going to conduct these
investigations they need to do it on the male side of the house as
well.''
   The woman denies she is homosexual and has not been formally
charged.
   During the last three federal fiscal years, 90 women and 219 men
have been dismissed for homosexuality, according to the Department
of Defense. More than 40 percent of those discharged were women,
who represent only about 5 percent of the Corps' strength.
   Department of Defense figures also show that, during the
three-year period, 662 cases of homosexuality among Marines were
investigated by the Naval Investigative Services and about a third
of the investigations involved women.
   There's no clear reason for the disparity and the matter has
never been studied, said Corps spokeswoman Joanne Schilling in
Washington. She denied that special attention was being paid to
lesbians.
   ``A commanding officer has the responsibility if someone in
their command has indicated a reason to believe there's a violation
of the UCMJ (Uniform Code of Military Justice) to check it out,''
she said.
   The investigation at Parris Island ``is not a regular occurrence
but it's not an unprecedented thing,'' said Maj. Robert McLean, a
spokesman for the base.
   Records of such cases are kept only about two years, but McLean
said he understood that there was a similar hearing involving women
Marines three or four years ago.
   He said the base doesn't make unsolicited announcements of such
hearings but will answer media inquiries.
   The current proceedings are Article 32 hearings, which are
similar to civilian grand jury hearings. They are, in effect, an
open investigation in which defendants have certain rights and
defense and prosecution witnesses can be called.
   The investigating officer then makes a non-binding
recommendation to the Marine's commanding officer. The
recommendation may be that the charges go to a court-martial, that
the Marine go before an administrative discharge board or the
charges be dismissed.
   In an administrative discharge board, a board of Marines
determines whether the defendant has the potential for further
service. A court-martial could lead to a prison sentence.
   In addition to the counts of indecent acts, the defendants face
various charges including dereliction of duty, sodomy, conspiracy
to obstruct justice and assault.
   ``Not all the charges are related to homosexuality,'' McLean
said. ``In a larger sense, we are talking about breaches of good
order and discipline.''
   He said the Corps cannot tolerate homosexuality because
``homosexuality is contrary to good order and discipline, not
because there is a statement being made about lifestyles.
   ``Recruit training must be conducted with the highest standards
of order and discipline,'' he added. ``The overwhelming majority of
those who serve perform faultlessly.''
</TEXT>
