<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TV-MonitorNews     04-07 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV-Monitor News,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christian Science Monitor Launching TV Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Christian Science Monitor announced Thursday
it is launching a nightly half-hour news program, ``Monitor
Newsworld,'' in September.
   The show will originate from Boston with satellite linkups to
international bureaus. Former NBC correspondent John Hart will
anchor. Commentator Hodding Carter, a former spokesman for the U.S.
State Department, will be the program's special Washington
correspondent.
   The Christian Science Monitor already has a syndicated TV news
analysis show, ``The Christian Science Monitor Reports,'' and a
radio show.
   No distribution agreement has been reached for the new show, but
it will either by syndicated or on a national cable network, the
Monitor said in a statement.
   When Hart announced three weeks ago that he was leaving NBC
after 13 years, he insisted he had no plans. He said Thursday he
decided to join the new Monitor show because of a ``coherence of
purpose _ to give a balanced account of human life.''
   On Wednesday, USA Today officially unveiled plans for its
nightly television news show, ``USA Today: The Television Show,''
which will also premiere in September. That show will be syndicated
and has been sold in more than 100 markets.
</TEXT>
