<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1355EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OakdaleCenter     04-07 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oakdale Center,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Shortage Stops Reconstruction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKDALE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reconstruction has been stopped at the
Federal Detention Center, which was heavily damaged by rioting
Cuban detainees last November, while the Bureau of Prisons waits
for Congress to reallocate funds to finish the job.
   The bureau's administrative division issued a temporary work
stoppage order a week after workers began rebuilding the $17
million facility.
   ``We're waiting for Congress to reprogram the money to go ahead
with reconstruction,'' said Kathy Morse, a bureau spokeswoman in
Washington, D.C. ``We've got the money, but it has not been
appropriated to use for this purpose.''
   She said no problem was anticipated in securing the approval.
   BOP is trying to transfer funds from other projects to rebuild
both the Oakdale center and Atlanta Federal Penitentiary, she said
Wednesady.
   Cuban detainees, protesting possible deportation, rioted and
burned the two facilities late last year.
   Contracts were signed March 25 to rebuild the Oakdale center,
and BOP issued an order for work to begin March 28.
   The burned-out shells of 10 of the Oakdale detention center's 14
buildings have been demolished and are expected to be rebuilt. The
four other buildings, all dormitories, are being renovated.
   Oakdale city officials have predicted the rebuilding will employ
about 300 people in an area with 14.1 percent unemployment.
   More than 200 people were waiting to apply for construction jobs
the morning the Oakdale office of the Louisiana Job Service began
accepting applications.
</TEXT>
