<DOCNO> AP880407-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GoingHome     04-07 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Going Home,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine-Month-Old Recipient Of Multi-Organ Transplant To Leave
Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two months after being given a new liver, small
bowel, pancreas and a portion of stomach, 9-month-old Michael
Steward is ready to go home, his doctor says.
   The success of the transplant operation so far is ``absolutely
fantastic news'' that provides hope for other children suffering
from multiorgan failure, Dr. James Williams says.
   The boy, who is from Rockford, underwent a multiorgan transplant
operation at Chicago's Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical Center
in February.
   Michael, the youngest child to receive such a transplant, is
scheduled to be released from the hospital Saturday, Williams said
Wednesday.
   Only three other children are known to have had such
transplants. Two have died; the third still is hospitalized.
   Michael was born with a twisted intestine that turned gangrenous
and had to be removed a week later. That left him with an intestine
too small to absorb food. Intravenous feeding kept him alive but
destroyed his liver, necessitating the transplants.
   After the transplant surgery, Michael battled setbacks,
including holes in the donor small bowel, Williams said.
   ``There have been a couple of times in this course that I didn't
think he was going to survive,'' Williams said.
   He said it was possible the boy will be able to function
normally.
   ``I'm very encouraged by the progress that has been made so far,
but it's still an experiment and we're still in the middle of it,''
Williams said.
   Williams said the donor bowel has been maturing well and the
child now gets about two-thirds of his nutrition through it. He
gets the rest of his nourishment through intravenous feeding.
   The doctor said he expects the boy will be weaned entirely from
intravenous feeding within two weeks.
   The donor small intestine has not yet been connected to the
boy's stomach, so he will have to return to the hospital in about
two months to undergo an operation to connect it, Williams said.
   ``We can't say that we have the total solution to short gut
syndrome in children, but we are strongly encouraged that this
procedure can be a promising option for other children suffering
from similar problems,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880407-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Knights Bjt   04-07 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Knights, Bjt,0864</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ancient Religious Order Electing New Grand Master</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the Knights of Malta cast secret
ballots Friday for a new leader to carry on the Roman Catholic
order's 900-year-old tradition of chivalry, charity and nobility.
   Thirty-six electors will lock themselves in a villa on the
Aventine Hill on Friday to vote for a successor to Fra Angelo de
Mojana di Cologna. The order's grand master died Jan. 18 at the age
of 82 after 25 years as the knights' supreme leader.
   The 78th grand master will be chosen from among 22 of the
electors, including de Mojana's interim replacement, Fra Giancarlo
Pallavicini, a Hungarian-born American biochemist.
   A grand master carries the title of prince and is addressed as
``Your Most Eminent Highness.'' Equal in rank to a cardinal, he is
elected for life and is considered the highest-ranking layman in
the Roman Catholic church.
   To be eligible for the position, he must have attained the top
rank of ``Knight of Justice'' and followed vows of poverty,
chastity and obedience. He also must be able to prove 200 years of
nobility on the side of both parents.
   The result of the election will be announced only after the
decision is ratified by Pope John Paul II, possibly several days
after the vote.
   The Sovereign Military Order of the Hospital of St. John of
Jerusalem, of Rhodes and of Malta _ the group's full title _ was
founded during the crusades when it opened a hospice for pilgrims
in Jerusalem in the early 11th century.
   It has the status of an independent state and has diplomatic
relations with 50 nations.
   The order is not related to the Knights of Columbus, an American
Roman Catholic society for men founded in 1882 in New Haven, Conn.,
that also is involved in charity and social works.
   The Knights of Malta dedicate themselves to chivalry, charity
and nobility. Today the order has about 10,000 members, led by
Italy with 2,800 and followed closely by the United States with
2,500, said spokesman Monsignor Antonio Jannone said.
   Among its well-known members in the United States are New York
financier J. Peter Grace, attorney Edward Bennett Williams, former
Secretary of State Alexander Haig and the late CIA director William
Casey. Italian members include Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti,
President Francesco Cossiga and Fiat Chairman Giovanni Agnelli.
   Beyond the image of chivalry, pomp and noblesse oblige _
symbolized by their uniforms, cloaks, medals, plumed hats and
swords _ the knights are known for their dedication to the sick and
wounded.
   The order operates about 200 hospitals and first aid centers in
90 countries, especially in Third World nations and war zones.
   ``After centuries of fighting to protect our citizens and
territory, the order has returned to its original function: health
assistance, hospitals, fighting against hunger and misery,''
Jannone said in an interview.
   For centuries, membership in the order required proof of ``blue
blood,'' but some ranks including ``Knights and Dames of Grace and
Devotion'' are now accessible to those without noble ancestry.
About 60 percent of the order's members today do not come from
nobility, Jannone said.
   Since 1834 the order has been based in Rome, where it owns a
16th century palace on Via Condotti in the heart of the shopping
district and a four-acre villa on the Aventine Hill. The site is a
favorite spot for Romans and tourists, who can peek through a gate
keyhole down a cypress-lined path that frames the dome of St.
Peter's Basilica in the distance.
   The order took on its military-chivalric character to defend
pilgrims and the Christian kingdom against Moslem attacks. The
knights were forced out of the Holy Land at the end of the 13th
century, eventually settling in Rhodes, where they became a naval
power in the eastern Mediterranean.
   They were driven from Rhodes by the Ottoman Turks in the 16th
century and moved to Malta, which they turned into an island
fortress and a thriving center of Christianity and trade.
   The knights stayed in Malta until 1798, when the island was
captured by French Emperor Napoleon. Before settling in Rome, the
order temporarily came under control of Czar Paul I of Russia and
shuttled among St. Petersburg, Catania and Ferrara.
   Among their activities in the United States, the Knights of
Malta run free clinics at St. Vincent's Hospital in Los Angeles and
Providence Hospital in Oakland, Calif., and a family dispensary in
East Los Angeles. They also give financial aid to Fordham
University in New York, the Pearson Foundation and Project Hope.
   In recent years the order has been waging a legal battle against
some 22 groups in the United States that use similar names and
titles and demand high fees and contributions. The real knights say
they collect minimal dues but that members are expected to
contribute generously to the order's projects.
   The order has filed suits in U.S. courts against the ``false
groups,'' but all the cases have apparently been dropped, Jannone
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
