<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HaircutSuspension     04-07 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haircut Suspension,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mohawk Haircut Doesn't Make the Grade, Gets Sixth-Grader Suspended</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Clifta and Youngs are cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SACKETS HARBOR, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 11 year-old boy suspended from
school for refusing to tame his Mohawk haircut blamed school
officials Thursday for blowing the issue out of proportion.
   ``None of the kids make fun of me,'' said Matt Youngs, a
sixth-grader at Sackets Harbor Central School. ``A lot of them like
it and want one.''
   ``It's the teachers that don't like it,'' he said.
   William and Clifta Youngs don't like their son's haircut, but
they're willing to go to court to defend his right to keep it.
   School officials in this small town on Lake Ontario believe
Matt's haircut is disrupting classes. He was suspended for five
days this week after his parents refused to promise that he would
change it.
   Superintendent Alson B. Dougherty said he considers Matt's
haircut to be as disruptive as ``extremely short shorts'' or
``see-through blouses.''
   ``More time is spent talking about the hairdo than working on
the things they (students) should be working on,'' Dougherty said.
``We want a safe, predictable environment in the classroom.''
   ``I think what I'm doing is right,'' Matt said. ``I can wear my
hair any way I want. This is America.''
   Matt, reached at home Thursday, said that about three months ago
he and three buddies asked their parents to give them Mohawk
haircuts. Matt's mom did his.
   ``It's brush-cut on top, long in the back and shaved on the
sides,'' he said.
   The boys' parents received letters March 16 from Principal
Robert B. Wagoner Jr. saying their sons would be suspended if they
didn't change the styles. All but Matt's parents complied.
   ``Teachers do not want to take his class to assembly programs,
have guest speakers come in or go on field trips,'' Wagoner's
letter said. ``They are saying they would rather forego the
embarrassment to themselves and the school.''
   Under New York Department of Education regulations, principals
or superintendents have the authority to intervene in disruptive
manners of dress, said Elena Zongrone, a staff member with the
Educational Planning Department in Albany. Parents can appeal the
decision, which may ultimately be decided by the courts.
   School district attorney Lee Willbanks said the district would
decide by Monday whether to impose another suspension or possibly
expel Matt.
   Mrs. Youngs said she only requires that Matt wash his hair daily
and keep it neat.
   ``It's clean, it's neat, it's short,'' said Mrs. Youngs. ``I
don't feel there's anything wrong with it. If he wants it, he can
keep it.''
</TEXT>
