<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     04-07 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lester Maddox says he has a right to sell
his property for use as a tire store if he wants to, no matter what
his neighbors think.
   The former Georgia governor is to appear April 19 before the
Cobb County Board of Commissioners in an effort to have his
1.24-acre lot rezoned for sale to Firestone Tire & Rubber Co.,
which wants it for a store and car care center.
   But some neighbors in Maddox's densely developed neighborhood
south of Marietta and north of Atlanta don't like the idea.
   ``An automotive business is a noisy, disruptive type
establishment that doesn't belong in a residential neighborhood,''
said resident David Hong.
   Commercial development has boomed in the area around Maddox's
house in the 11 years that he and his wife, Virginia, have lived
there. Maddox said he wants to sell out because he is fed up with
congestion and traffic.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>YAZOO CITY, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country humorist Jerry Clower's
popularity is costing his hometown money and leaving passing
motorists with no direction.
   Six bare sign poles along Jerry Clower Boulevard attest to the
drawing power of the comic's name. Two years ago, Yazoo City named
the part of U.S. 49 in honor of Clower, ``The Mouth of the South.''
   Clower and Mayor Charles Fulgham theorize that out-of-towners
must have stolen the signs while passing through. But the
investigation, begun in January when the absence of some of the
signs was noticed, has hit only dead ends.
   ``I don't know who did it,'' Clower said recently. ``But it was
some good ol' boy passing through, I assume, and he was on his way
to Ohio and he thinks, `I'll hang this up in my house.'''
   Fulgham said the signs cost $40 apiece. The city only has nine
signs left out of the original 15 ``and we're keeping an eye on
them,'' the mayor said Thursday.
   City officials are offering a $200 reward for information
leading to the whereabouts of the signs, along with the arrest and
conviction of the souvenir seekers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Patrick Crecine formally assumed the
presidency of Georgia Tech, pledging to make the institution a
leader in developing new technology and in opening science to women
and blacks.
   In remarks prepared for his inauguration Thursday, Crecine said:
``My ambition for Georgia Tech is no less than to be the model of a
modern technological university. In so doing, we will help define
what is meant by any great university in the 21st century.''
   Crecine also vowed, ``Before my stewardship of Georgia Tech is
finished, Georgia Tech will be seen as the major source of women
and black Ph.D.s in engineering, science and the other technical
disciplines.''
   Crecine, 48, was named president last August, taking over from
Acting President Henry Bourne, who served after the death of Tech
President Joseph Pettit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FERNANDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two juveniles convicted of
trespassing at the Malibu home of actor Sean Penn and rock star
Madonna have been sentenced, but authorities are keeping mum about
the outcome.
   Penn and Madonna confronted three men when they returned home
shortly after midnight on Jan. 20, officials said. Penn subdued one
intruder after a struggle by hitting him on the head with a bottle
of salad dressing.
   Richard Barcelo, 20, of Chino, has pleaded innocent to
misdemeanor charges of prowling and assault. But the two juveniles,
who faced sentences ranging from confinement at the state youth
authority to probation, were never identified.
   Prosecutors refused to discuss the case after Wednesday's
sentencing, citing state law involving juveniles. ``They were
disposed of,'' said Andy Reynolds, a spokesman for the district
attorney's office.
</TEXT>
