<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1408EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan-Home 1stLd-Writethru a0448 04-07 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Home, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0448,660</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: First 12 grafs new, picking up 2nd graf pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House chief of staff Howard
Baker said today that President Reagan's arrangement for leasing a
$2.5 million Bel Air estate was ``beyond legitimate criticism'' and
that the first family ``may not like'' all the publicity about the
deal.
   The White House refused to say how much Reagan and his wife,
Nancy, will pay for the posh home where they will move when he
leaves office. Real estate sources, however, estimate the
fair-market value at $12,000 to $15,000 a month.
   Without providing any figures, the White House said the Reagans
will pay a fair-market rental.
   Baker, talking with reporters at the seaside hotel where he is
staying during Reagan's vacation, was asked if there was any
appearance of impropriety in the leasing deal.
   ``I don't think so,'' he replied.
   ``The White House, the president and the first lady went to
great lengths to make sure that this was an arms-length
transaction, that there was a full appraisal of the rental price of
this property and that all of the i's were dotted and the t's were
crossed, and the president and the first lady have handled this in
precisely the right way and really beyond legitimate criticism of
the transaction,'' Baker said.
   Asked if the Reagans were upset by publicity about the house, he
said, ``Oh, I don't think so. I think after eight years they've
come to understand that that occurs, and while they understand it,
they may not like it, but they are not angry about it.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater refused to say how much
the Reagans would pay under a three-year lease that took effect
March 1.
   ``There is no federal requirement to divulge the amount of the
lease rental,'' Fitzwater said Wednesday.
   Stephen Shapiro of the Los Angeles realty firm of Stan Herman &
Associates said the fair market value for a 6,500 square-foot home
in that neighborhood would be $15,000 a month. Realtor Jeff Hyland,
who lives in the neighborhood, estimated the cost at $12,000 a
month.
   The single-story, ranch-style home, with three bedrooms, six
baths and a heated swimming pool, is situated on 1\ acres in west
Los Angeles in one of the most expensive areas of the state.
   Located at 668 St. Cloud Road, the home is near the Kirkeby
estate where the television show Beverly Hillbillies was filmed.
   The Reagans' neighbors will include celebrities such as
Elizabeth Taylor, Zsa Zsa Gabor, Joan Rivers, Mac Davis, Burt
Bacharach and Robert Stack.
   Real estate agents say the value of the home has shot up since
it was purchased in 1986 for the Reagans by a consortium of about
20 people, who have incorporated as the Wall Management Services
Inc.
   Jeff Hyland of the Los Angeles firm of Alvarez, Hyland & Young
said the value of the land alone could be as much as $3 million now.
   The rental fee and the terms of the lease were negotiated by
representatives of the Reagans and the owners, based on fair-market
rental estimates from two independent appraisers, Fitzwater said.
   Prior to buying the property, the proposed owners obtained a
legal opinion from the Office of Government Ethics.
   The ethics office said ``any potential lease or sale of the
house to the president and Mrs. Reagan will comply with standards
of conduct regulations and conflict of interest statutes so long as
the president pays a fair market rental or purchase price for the
house,'' Fitzwater said.
   The Reagans' lease gives them the option to renew the agreement
or purchase the house, Fitzwater said. No purchase price terms are
set in the lease, he added.
   The spokesman said the lease allows the Reagans ``to make
further decisions about the home once the president is out of
office and has exact knowledge of the assets and income in his
blind trust.''
   The house is expected to be ready for occupancy in late 1988,
before Reagan moves out of the White House next Jan. 20.
</TEXT>
