<DOCNO> AP880407-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Prize     04-07 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Prize,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prize Awarded to AIDS, Smallpox Researchers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American and a Frenchman whose independent
studies led to the discovery of the AIDS virus shared the Japan
Prize in preventive medicine Thursday.
   The Science and Technology Foundation of Japan awarded another
prize in the same category to U.S., Japanese and Australian
scientists credited with eradicating smallpox from the earth.
   French scientist Georges Vendryes, who pioneered development of
the fast-breeder type nuclear reactor, won the Japan Prize for
energy technology.
   Robert C. Gallo of the U.S. National Institutes of Health and
Luc Montagnier of France's Pasteur institute shared a $200,000
prize for their work on AIDS.
   Working separately, Gallo and Montagnier both discovered the
deadly virus and helped develop blood tests to detect infection.
   ``There would be no mistake in thinking that the methodology has
been established by the two doctors for the control of an
infectious disease which has become a major problem of the 20th
Century,'' the prize committee said.
   ``In parts of the world (AIDS) is akin to genocide,'' Gallo said
in accepting the prize at the National Theater. ``It is global, and
mostly, it destroys the young.''
   Donald A. Henderson of the United States, Isao Arita of Japan
and Frank Fenner of Australia shared $200,000 for their work on
smallpox. The World Health Organization declared the disease
eradicated in 1980, three years after the last patient was reported
in Somalia.
   Vendryes was awarded $400,000.
   The Japan Prize, awarded in two categories each year since 1985,
rewards scientific and technological achievements that contribute
to world peace and prosperity. Previous prizes have gone to five
Americans, an Indian and an Israeli.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
