<1ST_LINE>r a BC-AIDS-Stats     04-07 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AIDS-Stats,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Statistics On U.S. AIDS Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the latest statistics on acquired immune
deficiency syndrome in the United States, as reported this week by
the national Centers for Disease Control:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Number of Cases</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Total cases reported since June 1981: 58,270.
   Cases, year to date: 7,870.
   Total deaths: 32,545, or 56 percent of all cases.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Transmission Categories</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Homosexual or bisexual males: 36,605, or 63 percent.
   Intravenous drug abusers: 10,370, or 18 percent.
   Homosexual male and drug abusers: 4,267, or 7 percent.
   Heterosexual cases: 2,333, or 4 percent.
   Transfusion or blood cases: 1,523, or 3 percent.
   Hemophilia patients: 624, or 1 percent
   Undetermined transmission cause: 1,839, or 3 percent
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Age and Race</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Childhood cases (under age 13): 919, or 2 percent.
   Cases among whites: 34,560, or 59 percent.
   Cases among blacks: 14,992, or 26 percent.
   Cases among Hispanics: 8,191, or 14 percent.
   Cases among other: 527, or 1 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: These statistics are through April 4 and have
been rounded to the nearest whole percent. Cumulative totals are
for AIDS cases reported since June 1981, and include 75 cases
subsequently found to have occurred prior to that date. The
``other'' classsification under Age and Race includes Asians,
American Indians and native Alaskans.
</TEXT>
