<DOCNO> AP880407-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1432EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GreenRiver     04-07 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Green River,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two More Victims Added To Green River Serial-Killer List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two names have been added to the official list of
victims of the Green River serial-killer, police said.
   The latest identified victim in the nation's largest unsolved
serial-murder case is Tammie Charlene Liles, 16, of Snohomish,
whose skeletal remains were found in Tualatin, Ore. The bodies of
Ms. Liles and an unidentified female were dumped in a wooded area
near the grounds of the Tualatin Country Club, said Bob Evans,
commander of the King County Police Green River task force.
   The unidentified remains also were added to the list Thursday.
   The official tally of Green River victims stands at 39, and nine
other missing women are believed to be victims.
   The case takes its name from the river south of Seattle where
the bodies of the first five victims were found in 1982. Many of
the victims have had histories of prostitution, and many were known
to frequent the Sea-Tac strip near Seattle-Tacoma International
Airport.
   Ms. Liles, who was believed to be working as a prostitute,
disappeared in June 1983, Evans said.
   She was identified last month when her family contacted the task
force to report her missing, Evans said. She was identified March 8
through dental records by the King County medical examiner's office.
   Elliott Woodall, the spokesman for the Snohomish County
sheriff's office, said last month that Ms. Liles was reported as a
runaway in April 1983. The sheriff's office followed up the report
several months later, he said, and the family said Ms. Liles was
living in Tacoma and planning to get married.
   ``We cleared her from runaway status (in May 1984) based on that
information,'' Woodall said.
   Evans said police now believe the family was misinformed.
   Two other victims on the official list also were found in
Oregon. Those bodies were found in June 1985 in Washington County,
four miles from the site of the Liles body.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
