<1ST_LINE>u p BC-SimonText 2Takes   04-07 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Simon Text, 2 Takes,600-1200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon's Statement As He Suspends His Presidential Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of Sen. Paul Simon's
statement Thursday as he suspended his campaign for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
   I am today suspending my campaign for the presidency.
   I'm grateful to all who have campaigned with me and for me.
   And I leave the field of active campaigning with no regrets for
having made the race.
   No regrets, first, because it has been an exhilarating
experience to get to know our nation better, both our difficulties
and our potential.
   I understand more fully the plight of native Americans in South
Dakota, the nuclear energy in New Hampshire and New York, the
similarities and difficulties that farmers in Iowa and Wisconsin
share with their Illinois counterparts, the isolation of a small
city in Wyoming in winter, the disfigurement oil rigs could cause
to the magnificent coastline of California, the sadness of
unemployment in Starr County, Texas, and the wasted humanity in too
much of our nation.
   But I've also come to know better a nation with potential, a
nation that is limited not by our talent and resources, but by our
dreams and our leadership.
   Where I have had the opportunity to reach people I have seen
them respond with a selflessness that must be tapped.
   Americans instinctively know that we are one nation, one family,
and when anyone in that family hurts, all of us eventually hurt.
   There really is a yearning across this land for leadership that
appeals to the noble in us rather than the greed in us.
   I wish I had been able to tap that yearning more effectively.
   But to the extent my supporters and I have been able to reach
out and talk about programs and a vision of a better nation, to
that extent we have helped to make possible the building of a
better nation.
   For that, I am grateful to far too many people to be
acknowledged here, but they include my wife Jeanne, a superb
campaigner; my daughter Sheila and her husband Perry Knop, who were
married Sept. 12, and have since been honeymooning in places like
Audubon, Iowa, and Berlin, N.H., and Sturgeon Bay, Wis., and my
son, Martin, my traveling companion, photographer and consultant.
   No candidate could have stronger family support.
   To the staff of my campaign, who worked long hours for limited
pay, to our chairman Chuck Manatt, and the countless volunteers,
more volunteers than any other campaign, who are unbelievable in
their efforts; to those who raised money against great odds, to a
host of others I should be acknowledging my gratitude.
   And to the people of Illinois who have been both supportive and
understanding, my full efforts will now be devoted to being your
senator, and I shall be a better senator because of this rich
experience.
   The Polish writer, Kazimierz Brandys, tells a story of two who
were approached during a period of ferment in Poland and asked to
protest the illegal arrest and imprisonment of a leading
intellectual.
   One refused to sign and said, ``I can't. I have a son.''
   The other immediately took out his pen and said, ``I have to
sign because I have a son.''
   Both acts are understandable.
   But the legacy of honor that one leaves is vastly different than
the other.
   I entered this race beause I have a daughter and a son.
   I entered this race because I have had the good fortune to
understand the vast difference in the lives of millions of people
action by government can make.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
