<DOCNO> AP880407-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1420EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-SimonText 1stadd   04-07 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Simon Text, 1st add,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHN: can make.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   School officials at Hamilton High School in Milwaukee, Wis., who
knew I helped create the law requiring that those with disabilities
be given a chance by our public schools, arranged for a chorus of
retarded young people to sing for me.
   They recited the preamble to the Constitution in unison, and
then sang, ``This is My Country.''
   I glanced at the reporters covering the event, and noted the
moist eyes.
   We all had them.
   Without that change in the law, probably half of those young
people would be in institutions today.
   Government is not the enemy.
   Government is simply a tool that can be used wisely or unwisely.
   In passing that law, we used it wisely, compassionately.
   ``To form a more perfect union,'' these students recited from
the Constitution, a goal partially achieved but in large measure
still unattained.
   We can do better, my friends.
   I entered this race because I want this generation to give the
coming generations a sound economy, not an uncontrollable debt.
   I entered this race because I see a nation indifferent to the
wasted lives of far too many; children in schools where fear
dominates rather than learning; older citizens and their families
financially devastated by long-term care needs; hard-working
farmers devastated by short-sighted government policies; people
eager to work who cannot find a job, lose pride in themselves and
their families and their nation; and communities gripped by the
terror of crime.
   I entered this race because I know that the president of the
United States can lead our nation and other nations away from the
arms race.
   The blight of the arms race, and unemployment, and crime, and
inadequate health care, and educational shortcomings are not the
results of God, but the result of insensitive leadership _ chosen
by a people who sometimes are not as caring nor as careful as they
might be.
   I know we can do better.
   You know we can do better.
   I want leadership that will provide that.
   After the last primary on June 7, I will meet with my delegates
to determine what course should be followed.
   In a year that has already seen many surprises, no one knows
what twists and turns may develop between now and then.
   There will be many encounters with fate before the contest is
ultimately decided in a wide-open convention.
   For that reason, while I am ceasing all campaigning, I will make
no decision formally withdrawing as a candidate until after June 7,
though I have no illusions that the nomination will come my way.
   But I want my delegates to have a voice in this nation's future.
   We will weigh the options then.
   I want to be in a position to do everything I can to help unify
the party, and, ultimately, the nation.
   I'm grateful to those who've contributed to the nation's
dialogue who have withdrawn _ Joe Biden, Dick Gephardt, Gary Hart
and Bruce Babbitt.
   And I'm appreciative of the efforts already made and still to be
made by Jesse Jackson, Mike Dukakis, and Al Gore.
   All three have been working hard, discussing and refining the
issues, sharpening our knowledge and challenging our conscience.
   Delegates to the convention probably will select one of these
three who have come to know this nation well.
   To those who have already asked the inevitable question, ``Will
you run in 1992?'' I have two responses.
   First, I expect to campaign for a Democratic president for
re-election in 1992.
   Second, running for president is a little like taking an
ice-cold shower. It's a great one-time experience but I have no
yearning for a repeat performance.
   But we have a great nation, and all of us working together can
make it a better nation.
   Thank you.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End Simon Text _ 2 Takes</HEAD>
