<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--NukeTest     04-07 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Nuke Test,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Test of Year at Nevada Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERCURY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear weapons test with an explosive
force of less than 20,000 tons of TNT was detonated Thursday at the
Nevada Test Site.
   It was the second announced U.S. test of 1988. The Soviet Union
announced its third test of the year Easter Sunday.
   Energy Department spokesman Jim Boyer said the test, code-named
Abilene, was detonated in a shaft 800 feet beneath the surface of
Yucca Flat, 75 miles northwest of Las Vegas.
   Boyer said he felt no ground motion at a control point a few
miles from ground zero.
   The test is in the lower range of those conducted at the desert
site. All tests are announced as having an explosive range of less
than 20 kilotons or 20 to 150 kilotons. Larger tests, which
sometimes shake high-rise buildings in Las Vegas, are normally
announced in advance.
   A subsidence was reported 15 minutes after the 10:15 a.m. test.
DOE officials say that is a good sign because it means the ground
has settled over the weapon chamber.
</TEXT>
