<1ST_LINE>r i AM-DutchKidnap     04-07 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dutch Kidnap,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Confessed Kidnapper Leads Police To Grave Of Murdered Tycoon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAARLEM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police found the body of a kidnapped
Dutch tycoon buried in a forest after his abductor admitted
murdering his captive seven months ago and led authorities to the
grave, officials said Thursday.
   The discovery Wednesday night of the body of grocery baron
Gerrit Jan Heijn ended the nation's longest kidnap case. Heijn's
body was dug up near the northeastern village of Renkum, said Theo
Bot, a spokesman for the prosecutor's office.
   An unemployed architect admitted kidnapping Heijn, 56, on Sept.
9, 1987, and shooting him to death a few hours later, Bot said.
   Most of the ransom of 8 million guilders (about $4.3 million)
and 1,200 diamonds paid by Heijn's family was found in the
suspect's home, along with the gun used to kill Heijn, Bot said.
   The case became known as the ``Heijn Affair'' and, despite a
news blackout, dominated headlines throughout the nation. It is the
first modern Dutch kidnapping case in which a prominent victim was
killed.
   In line with police procedure, authorities refused to identify
the suspect except by his initials, P.E. They said he lived in the
village of Landsmeer, a few miles north of Amsterdam and about 75
miles from where Heijn was buried.
   The 45-year-old architect was arrested early Wednesday at home,
police said.
   Bot said police also took into custody the man's wife and his
three children, aged 17 to 25, but he said it was unclear if they
had any role in the crime.
   Heijn was kidnapped at gunpoint Sept. 9 as he left his home for
a dentist's appointment. He was vice-chairman of the family-run
Ahold grocery concern, which operates the nation's largest
supermarket chain, Albert Heijn.
   Ahold also owns the Giant Food and Bi-Lo stores in the United
States.
   The suspect told police he waited for Heijn outside the family
villa in the affluent Bloemendaal suburb, drove Heijn to the forest
in a stolen car and shot the executive in the head, Bot said.
   The suspect told interrogators he then cut off one of Heijn's
little fingers and buried him later that day, Bot said.
   Police spokeswoman Anne Geelof said in an interview with Dutch
television that police picked up the suspect's trail after the
discovery of a 250-guilder note from the ransom payment early this
year at a Landsmeer bank.
   The banknote was traced back to a supermarket in northern
Amsterdam, which was then put under police surveillance, Geelof
said.
   Several weeks after the first banknote surfaced, another
250-guilder note was spent at the supermarket by one of those now
under arrest, according to Geelof.
   The suspect's house was then put under police surveillance.
   The Amsterdam newspaper Het Parool said the suspect had been
living on welfare after several small businesses he started failed.
   Ahold communicated with the abductors through a series of coded
advertisements in Dutch newspapers, and the ransom was paid on Nov.
27.
   In early October, Heijn's little finger was mailed to Ahold.
   Justice Minister Frits Korthals Altes said in December that
Heijn was presumed dead.
   There was no indication that Heijn knew the suspect, police said.
</TEXT>
