<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis     04-07 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Talks to Cuomo: No Endorsement Yet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis said he talked
Thursday with New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, whose elusive endorsement
he described as ``relevant'' to New York primary voters despite
Cuomo's opinion otherwise.
   Dukakis, who has been courting a Cuomo endorsement for months,
said his discussion with Cuomo was ``a very pleasant conversation.''
   ``I'm sure we will be speaking frequently,'' Dukakis said.
   Asked if he felt a Cuomo endorsement would still be helpful with
less than two weeks to go before the New York primary, Dukakis
said, ``Sure it's relevant. People in New York and across this
country care very deeply about what Gov. Cuomo thinks and what
other governors think. As I said the other day, that is a decision
that he has to make. I respect it.''
   Cuomo, who appears to be leaning toward no endorsement, said
Thursday his opinion means less and less as the primary approaches.
``Who cares what ... Mario Cuomo says?'' he told reporters in
Albany.
   Dukakis said Sen. Paul Simon's decision to put his presidential
campaign on hold brings heightened attention to the trio of
Democratic hopefuls remaining.
   ``As I said to somebody the other day,'' Dukakis said with a
smile, ``it suddenly struck me Tuesday night that this was all
getting kind of serious.''
   The governor told a Statehouse news conference that Simon's
decision Thursday ``means that those of us who continue to be
strong contenders are going to be looked at, observed, and listened
to even more carefully and more intensively.''
   ``So it's for me, I think, another step in the road, and I hope
a good step in the sense that I've got an opportunity now to take
my case to the people of New York and ask them to make some choices
among the three candidates that now remain.''
   Asked about Simon's refusal to release his 170 delegates,
Dukakis said, ``It is his decision really as to what happens now
with respect to his delegates. Obviously, I want every delegate I
can get.''
</TEXT>
