<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz     04-07 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz,0743</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Says Hussein Possible Negotiating Partner for Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz said
Thursday that King Hussein of Jordan is a possible partner for
peace talks and that Israel should take its cue from him.
   Shultz, who is nearing the end of an arduous Middle East peace
shuttle, returned from Saudi Arabia for more talks with the king
and lauded Hussein's ``constructive'' approach to the U.S. peace
plan for the second day in a row.
   Indirectly applying pressure on Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir, Shultz said ``the message of that to Israel is here is a
possible Arab partner in negotiations.''
   But Shultz, who returns home Friday, acknowledged ``it remains
to be seen whether that can evolve'' into peace talks.
   Shamir remains opposed to an international peace conference,
which Hussein has demanded as a precondition to negotiations.
   Shultz said he was able to put ``a little life'' into his peace
plan since starting out in Jerusalem. But he said, ``I don't want
to exaggerate the progress that has been made.''
   The U.S. initiative calls for negotiations in two stages. The
first would seek to establish some self-rule for Palestinians who
live in the Israeli occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. The second
would deal with the settlement of the 40-year Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Four months of anti-occupation rioting in the occupied lands
have left more than 140 Palestinians and two Israelis dead. Israel
seized the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip from Egypt in
the 1967 Middle East War.
   Shultz spoke to reporters in al-Bareeda after an audience with
Saudi King Fahd in a palace about 300 miles north of the capital,
Riyadh.
   He said the king encouraged him to pursue Arab-Israeli
negotiations. ``I found a great measure of support and
encouragement,'' Shultz said.
   On another subject, Shultz said the United States was nearing an
agreement with the Soviet Union on Afghanistan that would permit
both sides to keep arming rival factions.
   ``Its an end-game situation,'' Shultz said, but he declined to
verify reports that a deal had already been struck. ``We are in
very active touch,'' he said.
   Shultz said he took up with the Saudis their purchase of
ballistic missiles from China, which has alarmed U.S. officials as
possibly sparking an escalation of missile arsenals throughout the
region.
   The rockets, delivered surreptitiously, can strike Israel or
Iran and range even beyond.
   Another U.S. official, briefing reporters aboard Shultz's flight
to Amman, said the Saudis gave assurances that the missiles were
non-nuclear: ``Non-today, non-tomorrow, non-forever.''
   He declined to say whether the Saudis gave the United States
permission to inspect the sites. Another U.S. official said Israel
gave Washington assurances it would not launch a pre-emptive strike
against the missiles.
   The purchase angered a group of 30 senators who have threatened
to try to block further arms sales to Saudi Arabia. The Reagan
administration apparently intends to go ahead with its plan to
provide new equipment for U.S.-built AWACS radar planes.
   ``That's obviously got great value,'' the U.S. official said,
defending the deal.
   In contrast to Arab-Israeli efforts, Shultz evidently has made
headway with Syria over a new constitution for Lebanon.
   He said he had ``quite constructive discussions'' with President
Hafez Assad in Damascus on Tuesday. The Syrians evidently are
prepared to help devise new constitutional guidelines that would
rearrange the division of power among Lebanon's warring factions.
   Describing the plight of the country, the U.S. official
traveling with Shultz recalled that ``people said a year ago, two
years ago, this is anarchy, total anarchy. Two years later, it's
worse.''
   Shultz's kind words for Hussein contrasted with his cool
approach to Shamir. On Wednesday, he urged Shamir to regard
negotiations with his neighbors as the most fundamental element in
Israel's security.
   In an interview with Israel television, Shultz lauded Hussein as
``a man of peace'' and said the questions he posed about the U.S.
plan showed he was engaged in the U.S. effort.
   Sizing up his five-day visit, Shultz said ``I think it's been
worthwhile and we've made a little progress here and there. But it
comes very hard and slow and I don't want to exaggerate the
progress that has been made. But it is important to keep at it.''
</TEXT>
