<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1528EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-JFKStatue Bjt   04-07 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-JFK Statue, Bjt,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg Unveils Model of JFK Memorial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A statue showing John F. Kennedy in mid-stride was
unveiled Thursday as the winner of a competition to select an
official memorial to the late president in his home state.
   His daughter, Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, unveiled a
three-foot plaster model of the bronze planned for the front lawn
of the Statehouse.
   The finished bronze sculpture that will be the state's official
memorial to Kennedy is scheduled to be unveiled May 29, 1989, which
would have been his 72nd birthday.
   It will stand a short distance from a statue of Henry Cabot
Lodge, the Republican whose son Kennedy defeated in 1952 in the
U.S. Senate campaign that launched his national career.
   ``There are many memorials to my father in this country and
around the world,'' Ms. Schlossberg said. ``But of all of them,
this one in the state he loved means the most.''
   The winning design in a year-long competition was executed by
artist Isabel McIlvain of Concord. It shows Kennedy in what members
of the selection commission called a classic pose _ mid-stride,
eyes forward, elbows bent with his left hand tucked into his suit
pocket.
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis strode into the ceremony a few minutes
late to speak about how Kennedy inspired his own entrance into
politics and, ultimately, his bid this year for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
   Echoing some of the things critics have said about himself,
Dukakis said of Kennedy: ``People said he was too young, he
couldn't carry the South, he had a religious burden.''
   Longtime Kennedy aide Dave Powers, a member of the committee
that selected the winning scupture, told stories about the 1960
Kennedy campaign during which the Massachusetts senator startled
some visitors with his voice exercises, designed to prevent him
from losing his voice at a critical time.
   Powers said the sculpture reminded him of what E.B. White once
wrote of Kennedy: ``He never feared the weather. ... Instead he
challenged the wind, to change its direction and to cause it to
blow more kindly and more softly over the world and its people.''
   Another commitee member, Paula Kozol, said she liked Ms.
McIlvain's design because ``there's steadiness, a composure
reflected there.''
   A fund drive to raise $150,000 to build the eight-foot bronze
statue began officially Thursday when state Senate President
William Bulger of Boston gave the memorial organizers a check for
$1,000 from his own campaign fund.
   House Speaker George Keverian, the original mover behind the
Kennedy memorial commission, said he was proud that none of the
money needed to execute the bronze would come from the public
treasury.
   Bulger, a frequent jokester, added that with the state's current
tight fiscal situation and Dukakis' presidential aspirations, the
private fund-raiser was a particularly good idea. ``We want to keep
the economic miracle alive in Massachusetts at least until
November,'' Bulger said.
   For three months, five small clay models of the proposed statues
have been on display at the John F. Kennedy Library in Boston's
Dorchester section.
   The other four finalists were by Frederick Hart of Markham, Va.;
Penelope Jencks of Newton; Norman Legassie of Old Lyme, Conn., and
Robert White of New York. Each artist received $4,000 to make the
models.
   McIlvain, who attended the ceremony, said she looked forward to
executing the bronze. ``I'm delighted to be doing this,'' she said.
</TEXT>
