<HEAD>Cuomo Refuses To Get Behind Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo refused again
Thursday to endorse any of the Democratic candidates for president
and implied that he might not back anyone until the primaries are
over in June.
   ``Who cares what ... Mario Cuomo says?'' the governor told
reporters.
   Cuomo also said he had told candidate Albert Gore Jr. that his
attacks on Jesse Jackson and Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
would be ``ineffective'' leading up to New York's April 19 primary.
   Cuomo said he talked to Gore Thursday morning and told the
senator that his criticism of Jackson and Dukakis ``wasn't helping
him.''
   Cuomo said his no-more-attacks message had also been passed
along to the Jackson and Dukakis camps.
   During a lengthy news conference, Cuomo again refused to endorse
any of the Democratic candidates and said ``every day this (an
endorsement) means less because we're getting closer to the
primary.''
   Many New York voters agree. Lee Miringoff, head of the Marist
College Institute for Public Opinion, said a new poll to be
released Friday found that more than 40 percent of likely New York
Democratic primary voters said it made ``no difference'' to them
whether Cuomo endorsed someone.
   Cuomo said he was thinking of not backing any of the candidates
until the primary season ended June 7. As he has in the past, Cuomo
said ``the candidate with a plurality at the end of the process
should be the candidate'' of the party.
   Cuomo said party leaders should rally around the leader at that
point and find enough votes to give him the nomination.
   To help with that process, it might be best to remain neutral
through the primaries, said Cuomo.
   ``You're already committed and for the rest of this thing you're
committed,'' he said of making an endorsement. ``When they look at
the whole scene at the end ... maybe at that point there should be
some force.''
   Cuomo again refused to rule out accepting a draft for the
nomination himself if there was a deadlocked convention.
