<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1646EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bennett-ToughKids     04-07 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bennett-Tough Kids,0757</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bennett Says Government Should Pay Parochial Schools To Teach
Tough Kids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   NEW YORK (AP) U.S. Education Secretary William Bennett called on
Catholic schools Thursday to enroll the ``worst 5 or 10 percent''
of public school students and ask state or local government to help
pay for teaching them.
   His proposal, made in an address to the National Catholic
Education Association's 85th annual convention here, was greeted
warmly by Catholic educators but was challenged as unconstitutional
by several leading public education groups.
   Bennett dubbed his proposal ``Project Voluntas,'' Latin for good
will.
   Parochial schools already have done an exemplary job teaching
minority students, who make up 22 percent of their 2.5 million
total enrollment, he told the gathering. But he said Catholic
educators have not been effective in telling outsiders how much
better they've done with difficult students compared with many
public schools.
   ``The challenge is simple,'' said Bennett, a parochial school
product himself. ``Show educators around this country what works.''
   ``Seek out the poor, the disadvantaged, the disruptive, the
dropout, and take them in, educate them, and then ask society for
fair recompense for your efforts,'' Bennett said.
   He said Catholic schools should ask state or local governments
for ``half the price, or two-thirds of the price, or something like
that,'' of whatever it would have cost to teach such students in
public school.
   Governments ``would, I believe, be receptive to constitutionally
sound efforts to pay for the education of such students.''
   But if government can't or won't, Bennett said, ``business and
others in the private sector would surely want to support such a
worthwhile endeavor.''
   ``I think there's a good deal of possibility for it,'' said the
Rev. John Pollard, director of education for the Archdiocese of
Chicago which enrolls 180,000 kindergarten through 12th-grade
students.
   ``We do not subscribe to the absolute separation of church and
state that others who oppose us do. The so-called wall of
separation is not in the (U.S.) Constitution,'' he said.
   But ``Project Voluntas'' was condemned by Gary Marx, associate
executive director of the American Association of School
Administrators: ``Every thoughtful American should be appalled by
the secretary's remarks. He constantly hits people in the public
schools below the belt and they are the ones who are working
hardest to deal with the problems of at-risk youth.''
   Thomas Shannon, executive director of the National School Boards
Association, called Bennett's proposal ``a welcome challenge to
Catholic schools,'' but questioned its constitutionality.
   ``If the Catholic schools are going to do what they are supposed
to do, that is, teach Catholic beliefs in an integrated way
throughout the curriculum, it would be unconstitutional on its
face'' to support such schools with public funds, Shannon said.
   Bennett's proposal is the latest of several he has advanced,
largely unsuccessfully, aimed at expanding educational options
including the private school sector. His ideas have included
tuition tax credits and tuition vouchers that would offer tax
breaks or direct assistance to parents of private school children.
   But with prospects bleak for tax credits or vouchers, Bennett
urged Catholic schools to take the initiative and prove that they
deserve community support.
   Roxanne Bradshaw, secretary-treasurer of the National Education
Association, the nation's largest teacher union, dismissed
Bennett's idea as ``a back-door approach to finance private
schools.''
   ``On the one hand, he's saying that money is irrelevant to a
quality education. On the other hand, he's saying the Catholic
schools need more money to educate at-risk children. Which is it,
Secretary Bennett? Does money matter, or doesn't it?'' she said.
   But Bennett said Catholic schools ``have often done more with
less.''
   Citing studies by University of Chicago sociologist James
Coleman, Bennett said the dropout rate among parochial high school
sophomores nationwide is just 3 percent, compared with 14 percent
in public schools.
   Median tuition at Catholic elementary schools is about $700, and
$1,500 for high schools, compared with an average of about $4,500 a
year to educate a child in public school, said Bennett.
   Still, he said, more than 4,000 parochial schools have closed in
the last 20 years, and part of the blame is with Catholic schools
themselves for being reticent in proclaiming their excellence.
   ``I believe that it is in your interest to take up this
challenge,'' Bennett said. ``It is also in society's interest.
Catholic schools shouldn't be closing. And disadvantaged children
should be getting a good education.''
</TEXT>
