<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Postal-Privatization     04-07 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Postal-Privatization,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Budget Director, Postal Workers Clash on Privatization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal budget director James C. Miller III
pushed the idea of turning over the Postal Service to private
companies Thursday, as about 100 picketing postal workers accused
him of trying to destroy the U.S. mail.
   New Postmaster General Anthony M. Frank, appearing at the same
meeting, opposed the privatization idea and called for greater
discretion for the service to manage its finances and set rates.
Picketers said they had no dispute with Frank.
   Miller and Frank appeared at a seminar sponsored by the Cato
Institute, a conservative policy research organization.
   ``There is no good reason why (the Postal Service) should remain
part of the U.S. government, and no good reason why it should enjoy
a monopoly over the delivery of letter mail,'' Miller said.
   He accused the service of wanting to be a government-protected
monopoly when it comes to letter mail and a federal agency when it
comes to federal subsidies and other benefits.
   Miller denied allegations from the postal unions and others that
his Office of Management and Budget has tried to intrude into
management of the Postal Service, which is an independent
government agency.
   He said his problem is not with the 800,000 postal workers but
with the system which he said is ``not working particularly well
right now.''
   ``If given the opportunity to compete, I'm sure the Postal
Service, including its employees, would do very well indeed,'' he
said.
   ``Miller, Miller, he's a jerk; privatization just won't work,''
chanted members of the American Postal Workers Union, who
obstructed the front door of the hotel where the seminar was held
until police arrived and ordered them to the sides.
   Moe Biller, president of the 365,000-member union, called
Miller's proposal ``cockeyed'' and said it would cause chaos with
the mail and increase costs to the public.
   ``No responsible businessman has advocated privatization,''
Biller said.
   Wearing a sign accusing Miller of betraying postal reform,
Biller stood at the doorway of the seminar room for a few minutes
before the budget director arrived. Biller later followed Miller
into the hotel and shook his hand, saying he wanted to debate him.
   Frank, who took over the Postal Service March 1, said it should
not be operated for profit.
   ``It should be the most efficient, reliable, convenient public
service in the country,'' he said.
   Frank said he senses even among advocates of privatization a
desire to effect only gradual changes.
   ``I sense a desire to go slowly, a recognition that the mail
system, like Humpty Dumpty, once broken, couldn't be put back
together again,'' he said.
   He said that if privatization means eliminating the letter-mail
monopoly, skimming off the profitable segments of the postal
business or busting the postal unions, he opposes it.
   But the postmaster general said he was willing to explore the
idea of privatization that would promote efficiency through more
sharing of the workload with major mailers and more contracting of
non-critical postal services.
</TEXT>
