<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Election     04-07 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Election,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amid Missile Attacks, Iran Ready For Parliamentary Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Under the threat of Iraqi missiles and air
raids, Iranians vote Friday for a new parliament that will be a key
factor in determining the course of the Islamic revolution.
   The election of a new 270-seat Majlis, or parliament, will be
vital in determining who will hold power in Iran after the
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini dies. He is 87 and reported in poor
health.
   The vote is seen as a test of strength between fundamentalists
who support an Islamic-style capitalism and radicals who favor a
socialist-style economy.
   Iranian leaders fear that Iraq will blitz Tehran and other major
cities with a barrage of missiles to disrupt the elections, and
they have urged Iran's more than 20 million voters to turn out in a
massive show of defiance.
   ``The people will attend the election with God's help, even if
they are under missile attack. I will vote under any
circumstances,'' Khomeni said last week.
   He added, ``The people must beware and choose candidates among
... those loyal to Islam. They must choose their deputies from
among those who have suffered from poverty and are real Moslems,
not those who obey America's Islam.''
   About 1,400 candidates, approved by provincial and city
governors controlled by Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi,
will be running.
   Tha's about 400 more than ran in the last election in 1984.
There will be 30 female candidates. It's the first time women have
run for Iran's parliament.
   It is the third parliamentary poll since Khomeini's 1979 Islamic
revolution toppled the late Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi.
   Iranian leaders have said the election will be a crucial test
for the Islamic form of democracy, and the campaigning has shown
sharp differences between rival factions over the future course of
domestic policy.
   The 7{-year-old Iran-Iraq war, the country's most pressing
problem, has not figured in the campaigning. Khomeini, Iran's
undisputed patriarch, has decreed that the war will not end until
his adversary, Iraq's President Saddam Hussein, has been toppled.
   The conservatives essentially identify with the religious
fundamentalists, who base their concept on a narrow interpretation
of the teachings of the Koran, Islam's holy book, which protects
private property and free enterprise.
   Their protagonists, seeking tighter state control, are likely to
garner widespread support from the increasingly discontented poor
who have to cope with runaway inflation and a flourishing black
market.
   Cigarettes cost $10 a pack, red meat is about $16 a pound, and
eggs are $8.50 a dozen.
   House Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani, one of Khomeini's closest
aides and considered a pragmatist on most issues, is expected to be
reelected along with most of the leading figures in the hierachy.
   But the hardliners, such as Prime Minister Hussein Musavi, are
expected to make some gains, a development that could have
far-reaching effects on the shape of the revolution in the
post-Khomeini era.
   None of the candidates is running on party tickets. The last
formal party, the Islamic Republic Party, which Iran's clerics used
to gain power in the early days of the revolution, was disbanded by
Khomeini last June because it was torn by factionalism.
   The candidates will represent various shades of Islamic and
revolutionary thinking.
   The results may not be known for 10 days, and the new parliament
may not sit until June while a new cabinet is screened and nominees
scrutinized by the deputies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
