<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France     04-07 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine Candidates In Presidential Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Constitutional Council on Thursday published
its list of candidates for the April 24 presidential elections: one
woman and eight men including President Francois Mitterrand who
leads all public opinion polls.
   The nine candidates each fulfilled the requirement of obtaining
the signatures of at least 500 elected officials and payment of a
$1,750 fee.
   French elections are run in two rounds. If no candidate wins an
absolute majority in the April 24 first round, as expected, a
run-off will be held on May 8.
   There is little doubt that the 71-year-old Mitterrand, seeking a
second seven-year term, will win the largest number of first-round
votes. Polls show him with about 38 percent. The real race is for
the second runoff spot, a battle between conservative Premier
Jacques Chirac and former center-right premier Raymond Barre.
   Polls indicate that Mitterrand would easily defeat either
Chirac, 55, or Barre, 63, in the second round. Many voters say,
however, that they are undecided.
   Chirac, who trailed Barre in the early stages of the campaign,
since has overtaken him and now is shown in the polls winning about
24 percent of the vote and Barre about 15 percent.
   Farther back is Jean-Marie Le Pen, 59, leader of the extreme
right National Front, with about 10 percent, depending on the poll.
   Others in the race are Andre Lajoinie, 58, official candidate of
the Communist Party, at about 6 percent, and Pierre Juquin, 58, a
former Communist Party Poliburo member now leading a splinter
reform movement, who has about 3 percent in the polls.
   Also on the list are the ecologist candidate, Antoine Waechter,
39, with about 2{ percent, Arlette Laguiller, 48, head of the
Trotskyist Worker Struggle movement, 1 percent, and Pierre Boussel,
67, leader of the new extreme left Movement for a Party of Workers,
who hasn't turned up in any polls.
   Mitterrand was elected May 10, 1981, defeating incumbent
President Valery Giscard d'Estaing.
   Mitterrand's popularity, which fell to as low as 27 percent at
midterm, has soared in the two years since he no longer has had
direct control over the government.
   The two leading conservatives, Chirac and Barre, have agreed not
to attack one another so as not to split the right, and to support
the top conservative vote-getter in the second round.
   Mitterrand, who has abandoned most of his Socialist rhetoric and
taken pains to distance himself from the party he founded and led
for many years, has moved toward the center. That has turned the
campaign debate largely into a contest of personalities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
