<DOCNO> AP880407-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1618EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Lebanon     04-07 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Lebanon,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Writes Letter to President of Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has sent a letter
to President Amin Gemayel of Lebanon, expressing concern about the
continuing conflict in the war-torn country, an administration
source said Thursday.
   This official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that he
had not seen the letter, but ``I would characterize it as
underscoring the mutual interests that the United States and
Lebanon have in building peace in the region.''
   White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk declined to discuss
Reagan's letter to Gemayel, saying: ``We do not comment on any
private presidential communication'' to another head of state.
   April Glaspie, the U.S. ambassador-designate to Iraq, conducted
a shuttle mission between Syria and Lebanon last month in an effort
to mediate a compromise over conflicting power-sharing demands.
   In Washington, a State Department official, also speaking on
condition of anonymity, said the United States was ``serving as a
postman between Assad and Gemayel,'' who have not spoken to each
other in over a year.
   Syria, which maintains about 25,000 troops in eastern Lebanon
and in Beirut, is seeking an arrangement that would grant the
country's Moslem majority more power in government. Gemayel, who
heads Lebanon's Christian community, has rejected Syria's
interference.
   The United States has been concerned that unless some agreement
is worked out, this summer's elections would result in serious
factional violence.
   U.S. officials have rejected speculation that the State
Department's mediation is designed to score points with Syria in
return for its help with gaining the release of American hostages
held in Syrian-controlled parts of Lebanon.
</TEXT>
