<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WhizKid     04-07 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whiz Kid,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Solves State's Financial Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINERAL WELLS, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sixth-grader has done in a few
months what critics say state leaders have been unable to do for
years: solve West Virginia's financial problems.
   Keeling Fife Jr. did it as a school social studies project.
   Fife, who became concerned last fall when he heard news stories
about the state's growing financial woes, said his solution
involves changing the ``gross state product'' by increasing the
percentage of workers employed in industry.
   His project won the Wood County Social Studies Fair and is
entered in the May 20 state contest. Fife was last year's state
fair winner.
   ``West Virginia is in a desperate time, and it will take
patience and tough decisions to bring the state back to prosperous
times,'' the 11-year-old said.
   He suggests building hydroelectric dams, training workers in
high-technology fields and lowering the costs of natural resources
for in-state users.
   By 1990, Fife said, the northeastern United States won't have
enough electric power, and hydroelectric plants on West Virginia's
rivers easily could generate power and help the state.
   West Virginia also needs technically literate workers to attract
industries to the state, he said.
   Included in Fife's research, along with newspaper accounts of
the state's indebtedness and legislative performance, are responses
from area legislators and an interview with state Auditor Glen
Gainer.
   ``Sometimes I wonder if we shouldn't turn the Legislature over
to the sixth-graders of the state,'' said Fife's father, Keeling
Fife Sr.
   The younger Fife, however, has no intention of becoming a
legislator. He says he prefers collecting baseball cards, playing
baseball and taking piano lessons.
   He doesn't limit his problem-solving to social issues. He also
was a winner in this year's county science fair with a project on
lasers and was a regional math field day winner.
</TEXT>
