<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1925EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SoybeanOutlook     04-07 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soybean Outlook,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Soybean Producers Facing Heavy Competition From Abroad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World demand for high-protein, oil-rich
soybeans has led other producing countries into a fierce
competition with American farmers, an Agriculture Department report
said Thursday.
   Soybeans have the potential to supplement diets of low-income
people in the Third World, where it will be important to gain
consumer acceptance for soybeans and soy-fortified foods, said Gary
Vocke, an agriculture and trade analyst in the department's
Economic Research Service.
   ``A historical view shows that U.S. dominance of world soybean
trade, founded on U.S. research and development in the 1940s and
1950s, declined in the 1980s as South American countries, spurred
by high prices, developed large-scale production and processing
facilities,'' he said.
   Brazil and Argentina have been the main U.S. competitors in the
international soybean market.
   Vocke added: ``Their success, mainly in temperate areas, has not
been duplicated in tropical areas elsewhere in the Third World.''
   The major factors behind the increased demand for soybeans in
the Third World are rising incomes and population growth, Vocke
said. As families have more to spend, their demand increases for
meat and other food products such as margarine and cooking oil.
   ``Fierce export competition with the South Americans for these
markets, as well as the developed country market, will likely
continue,'' Vocke said. ``The expansion of large-scale soybean
production in South America will continue as long as soybean prices
are high enough for Brazilian farmers to profitably open new lands
for soybeans.''
   Further encouragement would be in the Brazilian government's
willingness to develop the rural transportation system connecting
the new lands to ocean ports, he said.
   ``If the price of soybeans is high relative to other crops,
farmers in Brazil, Argentina and elsewhere will find it profitable
to switch even more of their existing cropland to soybeans,'' Vocke
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
