<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Robertson     04-07 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Still Seeks Delegates Despite Reduced Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHESAPEAKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson is pursuing delegates to
the Republican National Convention even though he has given up a
serious contest for the GOP presidential nomination, Robertson
campaign officials said Thursday.
   Robertson has decided not to campaign in the New York primary,
dismissed his Secret Service protection this week and has scaled
back his public appearances, said Barbara Gattullo, a spokeswoman
for Americans for Robertson.
   ``We did not mean to set off any alarm bells by this,'' she said.
   She later said, ``We are going to the convention whether we add
delegates or not.''
   The Secret Service agents are no longer needed because ``we are
traveling about two to three days a week instead of the seven days
a week we were prior to Super Tuesday,'' she said.
   Since his poor showing in the March 8 primaries, Robertson has
cut his staff from 200 to about 50, reduced his campaigning to
those states that choose delegates by caucus rather than primary,
and turned his attention from 1988 to 1992.
   Ms. Gattullo said Robertson had two rallies scheduled in
Virginia Thursday night and Friday and would fly to Georgia on
Saturday for campaign stops over the weekend. She said he would
also make campaign appearances in California and Ohio.
   ``We are absolutely in this through the convention,'' she said.
   Robertson has estimated he will go to the New Orleans convention
in August with 150 delegates. So far, he has 17.
   Since his campaign was derailed during the early March
primaries, when he failed to win any state including his native
Virginia, Robertson has shifted his emphasis from an attempt to
broaden his base of support beyond the religious right to targeting
delegates chosen by caucus.
   With those delegates, he said he will be able to bring a
``strong conservative message'' to the convention. That message
would include the adoption of a national platform that supports
prayer in school, the strengthening of the American family, and
opposition to abortion.
</TEXT>
