<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StudentProtest     04-07 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Student Protest,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protest Over Alleged Racism Ends Peacefully</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen black students were cited for
trespassing and released after an all-day sit-in to protest alleged
racism at the University of California-Berkeley.
   The peaceful protest by about 50 members of the African Students
Association ended Wednesday when campus police cited 18 students
who refused to leave the campus housing office at the close of the
work day.
   ``This protest is the culmination of a lot of different things
that have gone unresolved at the university,'' said ASA President
Michael Stoll.
   The protest focused on charges by freshman Traci Morris, who
claims she's been harassed by three white male dorm-mates who
allegedly damaged her bicycle. Morris also said she had suffered a
year of racial slurs and jokes.
   ``They say things like, `Only 27 percent of you pass anyway, why
study?''' Morris said, referring to a 1987 study which indicated
that 27 percent of black students at the university graduate.
   The protesters demanded the three men be expelled and that
Morris be refunded her housing expenses for the school year.
   University spokesman Ray Colvig said the white students will be
disciplined.
   ``The Office of Student Conduct did a rapid and thorough
investigation and has drawn up a proposed settlement,'' he said.
The agreement involves payment by the men for the damage to the
bicycle, moving the students to other dorms and requiring them to
perform some community service.
   ``I don't know about anything else, all I did was hang her bike
in the shower because she's my friend,'' said Tony Sanchez,
identified as one of the students. He called the incident a
practical joke.
   Freshman Jeffrey Wisher, also named by the ASA, admitted he hung
Morris' bike in the shower a second time. ``But it was only the
bike, it has nothing to do with racism,'' he said.
</TEXT>
