<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FCC-Indecency     04-07 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC-Indecency,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Dismisses Five Indecency Complaints Against Broadcasters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Please note that grafs 11 and 12, ``Another complaint ...
double entendre,'' contain material that may be offensive to some
readers''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission on
Thursday dismissed five indecency complaints, including one against
a television station that aired a sex-education program for
teen-agers and another against a radio station that apparantly
aired a reading of James Joyce's ``Ulysses.''
   In four of the cases, the FCC said the material involved did not
violate the agency's decency standards. It said thre fifth case did
not contain sufficient information to determine the context of the
material aired.
   A complaint filed against KING-TV, Seattle, cited a program
called ``Teen Sex, What About the Kids?'' which included what the
FCC described as ``frank discussions of sexual topics, the use of
sex organ models and the simulated demonstration of various birth
control devices.''
   In a letter to the Seattle couple who complained, the FCC said
that while the program contained references to sexual and excretory
organs and activities, the references ``in context, were not
`vulgar,' `lewd' or `shocking.' Nor were they made in a pandering
or titillating manner.''
   The FCC judges material to be indecent if it ``depicts or
describes, in terms patently offensive as measured by contemporary
community standards for the broadcast medium, sexual or excretory
organs or activities.'' The agency also says it will examine the
context of the material.
   The FCC has said indecent material may be broadcast between
midnight and 6 a.m. because there is little risk children would be
in the audience then.
   Obscene material, however, cannot be aired at any time. Such
material is defined as appealing to the prurient interest and
lacking serious artistic, literary, political or scientific value.
   Broadcasters are challenging the FCC's year-old decency
standards in court, charging the guidelines are vague. They say the
commission has refused to identify specific material that would be
deemed indecent under the standards.
   The FCC has said broadcasters should be guided by the decisions
the agency makes in the cases that come before it.
   A complaint against WBAI-FM, a Pacifica Foundation station in
New York City, described portions of an unidentified program that
the FCC said appeared to be a reading from the ``Penelope'' chapter
of ``Ulysses.''
   Assuming the program was a reading from the classic work, the
FCC said, ``we would not expect that the commission would find such
(sexual and excretory) references, dispersed as they would have
been throughout the three-hour reading of this work of literature,
to be patently offensive.''
   Another complaint the FCC dismissed had been filed by the mayor
of North Charleston, S.C., John E. Bourne Jr., against WTMA-AM,
Charleston, S.C., for airing a political advertisement opposing his
proposal to put a clock on the City Hall. Toward the end of the ad,
someone shouts ``clocksucker.''
   The FCC also found the song ``I Want to Kiss Her, But ...,''
aired by WTRG-FM, Rocky Mount, N.C., was not indecent, despite its
use of double entendre.
   ``The lyrics at issue here are not such that they are capable of
only one, sexual meaning. Rather, the lyrics are capable of two
meanings _ one innocent, one sexual,'' the FCC said.
   The commission ruled last April in a case involving New York
disc jockey Howard Stern that double entendre and innuendo could be
deemed indecent when they were mingled with explicit references
that made the material capable of only a sexually explicit meaning.
   The Public Broadcasting Service's series ``Heimat,'' about the
life of three German families from the end of World War I to the
1960s, was the target of another complaint because of scenes
containing sexual activity.
   The FCC said the complaint, filed against WCET-TV, Cincinnati,
did not contain sufficient information to determine the context of
the material.
   Ron Wilson, a WCET executive, said the series that aired on
about 70 PBS stations last October and November contained some
nudity, but he said it was relevant to the story line and the
characters.
   ``Without those scenes a large part of the content would not
have made sense,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
