<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MIARemains     04-07 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MIA Remains,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Remains Of 27 Possible Americans Arrive From Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-seven sets of remains believed to be
those of Americans killed in the Vietnam War arrived here Thursday
for identification.
   A military honor guard carried each of the flag-draped
containers from an Air Force cargo plane at Hickam Air Force Base.
Following military honors, the remains were taken to the Army's
Central Identification Laboratory.
   Military officials said that after positive identification is
made and the families are notified, the names will be released.
   The Vietnamese provided a list of names for at least half the 27
remains, according to Lt. Col. Paul Mather, head of the U.S.
casualty team which received the remains in Hanoi earlier this week.
   It was the largest transfer of remains since the last American
forces withdrew from South Vietnam in 1973.
   U.S. officials list 1,767 Americans as missing in action in the
Vietnam War. Vietnam so far has returned 152 remains that the Army
laboratory has confirmed as those of Americans missing in action.
