<DOCNO> AP880407-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1957EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HiroshimaVisions     04-07 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hiroshima Visions,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>For Artists, Horrors of Hiroshima Live On</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world changed for the Marukis when they left
their small plot of land near Tokyo for Hiroshima three days after
it was destroyed by an atomic bomb.
   For millions born after 1945, the devastation of Hiroshima is
history. For Iri and Toshi Maruki, it was a revelation that led to
the creation of murals depcting the horrors of war.
   The two are subjects of the film ``Hellfire: A Journey from
Hiroshima,'' produced by filmmaker John Junkerman and nominated for
a 1988 Academy Award as best documentary feature.
   Maruki, born in Hiroshima 86 years ago, and his wife, 76, went
to Hiroshima on Aug. 9, 1945, the same day an atomic bomb was
dropped on Nagasaki, to check on family members.
   He had lost his father, uncle, two nieces and numerous friends
in the inferno, which killed an estimated 130,000 people.
   Both say the death and destruction left by the bomb remains a
living memory.
   ``How can we forget?'' Maruki said. ``The horror is always in
our mind. The stench of death was in our nostrils for three or four
weeks.''
   He and Mrs. Maruki were interviewed Thursday at the
Massachusetts College of Art, which is displaying some of their
works _ powerful ink canvases including some of the ``Hiroshima
Panels,'' ``Auschwitz,'' and ``The Battle of Okinawa.'' The two are
scheduled to receive honorary doctorates from the college.
   Titled ``Surviving Visions,'' it is the first Maruki exhibition
in the United States since 1970.
   The artists, who spent a month in the devastated city, describe
this work as ``a procession of ghosts, with hands held before them
... (who) pushed on, dragging their burned bodies, falling and
piling into one another, groaning and dying.
   ``One lone child slept innocently, with unburned skin,'' they
write in a an exhibit catalog. ``Perhaps it survived, sheltered by
its mother's breast.''
   One of the ``Hiroshima Panels,'' ``Ghosts,'' completed in 1950,
depicts some of the dead and dying, naked, their bodies charred,
their faces anguished.
   ``Death of American Prisoners of War'' is a 1971 canvas
depicting a tragedy that was taboo in Japan for decades, the
massacre of 23 U.S. POWs by enraged survivors of the bombing.
   ``We trembled as we painted the death of the American prisoners
of war,'' Mrs. Maruki wrote.
   The victims' manacled corpses are intertwined with erotic nude
figures of their wives and lovers back home. A dark, menacing mass
of enraged Japanese crowds the periphery of the drawings.
   ``Auschwitz'' resulted from a trip to the former death camp in
Poland, where 3 million Jews and other inmates were gassed or
starved to death by the Nazis. Completed in 1977, the work's eight
somber panels pay tribute to Holocaust victims and survivors.
   The Marukis said their art educates generations born too late to
experience the horrors of World War II.
   ``The kids don't know because they're not taught in school,''
said Mrs. Maruki, suggesting that Japan still was reluctant to come
to grips with a painful period in its history. ``I suspect that the
Ministry of Education is somehow maneuvering not to teach (this)
modern history to children.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880407-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1958EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Alzheimer'sDisease     04-07 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alzheimer's Disease,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers Confirm Early Brain Sign of Alzheimer's Disease</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to fix typo in slug.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SPEER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists have confirmed the presence of
an abnormal protein in normal-looking brain cells in Alzheimer's
disease patients, adding evidence that it may be an early
contributor to the disease.
   Further study may lead to a way of battling the memory-decaying
condition before its effects are irreversible, they said Thursday.
   ``You can imagine how exciting it would be if we had a way of
intervening before there has been much irreversible damage,''
Antonio Damasio, head of the neurology department at the University
of Iowa, said at a news conference.
   There is no known treatment or cure for Alzheimer's disease,
which the scientist said affects nearly 3 million Americans and is
the single most common cause of mental decline in older people.
   The results of Damasio's study, done in collaboration with
Bradley Hyman and Gary W. Van Hoesen of the University of Iowa and
brain chemists at the Albert Einstein College of Medicine in New
York City, were to be published Friday in Annals of Neurology, the
journal of the American Neurological Association.
   Alzheimer's is centered in cells which transmit signals to and
from the memory center in the brain, Damasio said.
   He compared the disease's action to a computer with faulty input
and output lines. That limits the functioning of the computer
``while not doing too much damage to the computer itself,'' Damasio
said.
   The study, done by autopsies on the brains of Alzheimer's
patients, shows that the disease is very specific in the brain
cells it attacks, Damasio said.
   The protein confirmed by the study was previously idenfified and
named A68, by Dr. Peter Davies at Albert Einstein.
   ``It looks like the disease knows its way and is very choosey,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
