<DOCNO> AP880407-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1752EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Home 1stLd-Writethru a0706 04-07 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Home, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0706,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baker Says Reagans May Not Like Publicity About Estate Leasing</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf pvs, bgng: Moreover, it, to put the number of
buyers at 18-20; INSERTS three grafs after 14th graf pvs, It said,
to UPDATE with comments from ethics official; SUBS last graf to
include name of real estate company</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House chief of staff Howard
Baker on Thursday defended the propriety of President Reagan's
secret leasing arrangement for a $2.5 million estate and said the
first family ``may not like'' all the publicity about the deal.
   The White House refuses to say how much Reagan and his wife,
Nancy, are paying for the three-bedroom, six bath home in the
exclusive Bel Air section of Los Angeles that has a heated swimming
pool and three-car garage.
   Real estate sources estimate the monthly rent at $12,000 to
$15,000, based on fair-market value.
   Moreover, it is unclear why the Reagans are leasing the home
instead of buying it outright. Also unknown are the identities of
the 18-20 people who formed a consortium specifically to buy it for
the Reagans.
   The Reagans are planning to move into the home, at 668 St. Cloud
Road, after he leaves office next Jan. 20.
   The 1\-acre property, in the poshest area of Bel Air, touches
the Kirkeby estate where the ``Beverly Hillbillies'' television
series was filmed and is located near the homes of Elizabeth
Taylor, Zsa Zsa Gabor and other celebrities, as well as some of the
Reagan's closest friends.
   Baker rejected the notion that there was any impropriety in the
deal.
   Responding to reporters' questions at the seaside hotel where he
is staying during Reagan's vacation, Baker said, ``The White House,
the president and the first lady went to great lengths to make sure
that this was an arms-length transaction, that there was a full
appraisal of the rental price of this property and that all of the
i's were dotted and the t's were crossed.''
   Baker said, ``The president and the first lady have handled this
in precisely the right way and really beyond legitimate criticism
of the transaction.''
   Asked if the Reagans were upset by publicity about the house, he
said, ``Oh, I don't think so. I think after eight years they've
come to understand that that occurs, and while they understand it,
they may not like it, but they are not angry about it.''
   A White House statement released Wednesday said the Reagans'
three-year lease took effect March 1, and contained an option to
renew or purchase. No purchase price was specified in the lease,
the White House said.
   Before buying the property, the prospective owners sought an
opinion from the Office of Government Ethics on the propriety of
leasing or selling the property to the Reagans.
   The opinion said the Reagans would comply with standards of
conduct regulations and conflict-of-interest statutes if they paid
a fair-market rental or purchase price for the house, the White
House said.
   It said the lease terms were negotiated by representatives of
the owners and the Reagans, based on fair-market value rental
estimates from two independent appraisers.
   In Washington, Donald Campbell, deputy director of the Office of
Government Ethics, confirmed that lawyers representing the
consortium approached the agency in July 1986 and ``we did make an
analysis of it'' and provide an informal opinion letter.
   Eighteen people were listed in the consortium, all but one
described by the lawyers as friends of the Reagans for a number of
years, Campbell said.
   Presidents are not required to adhere to the standards or to
federal conflict-of-interest criminal laws, but traditionally have
committed themselves to doing so.
   The property was purchased in August 1986 by the consortium,
which has incorporated itself as Wall Management Services Inc.
   Realtor Jeff Hyland of the Los Angeles firm of Alvarez, Hyland &
Young said that with rising prices since the purchase, the land
alone now is worth $3 million.
   ``They got a great buy,'' he said. ``The bought it for land
value. As far as I'm concerned, they got the house for free.''
   Realtor John Aaroe of the Jon Douglas Co. said the house, built
in 1954, still has the original kitchen and bathrooms and needs
updating and renovations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
