<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Simon 2ndLd-Writethru a0753 04-07 0820</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Simon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0753,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Suspends Campaign But Holds Delegates</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Moves up grafs 15-18 pvs to grafs 9-12 to raise Simon comment
on delegates</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois Sen. Paul Simon suspended his stalled
presidential campaign Thursday but held onto his 170 delegates in
hopes of influencing the choice of a nominee at the Democratic
national convention in July. Jesse Jackson immediately blasted
Simon for keeping the delegates, saying many of them were
rightfully his.
   ``In a year that has already seen many surprises, no one knows
what twists and turns may develop between now and then,'' Simon
told a news conference. ``There will be many encounters with fate
before the contest is ultimately decided in a wide-open
convention.''
   In a quasi-withdrawal, Simon said he would no longer actively
campaign for the nomination but said he technically would remain a
candidate even though he conceded he has ``no illusions that the
nomination will come my way.''
   ``I want to have an impact on who the party nominates,'' Simon
said. ``I want to have an impact on the whole process there (at the
Atlanta convention), and on where we go.''
   Jackson, however, said Simon's move was a less-than-honorable
one, and that he ought to release his delegates.
   ``If one is not in the race one ought to indicate a form of
honorable withdrawal at which time whoever got second place in that
state will get those delegates. That's what Mr. Gephardt did. It
was the honorable and the fair thing to do,'' Jackson said in New
York.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt dropped out of the Democratic race last
month.
   ``I would hope that in time Mr. Simon likewise _ now that he has
made the decision to leave the race _ will leave so honorably, and
hide behind no technicalities to block those as my delegates which
in fact belong to me,'' Jackson said.
   Simon's decision to nominally remain a candidate and retain his
delegates means he holds onto 47 at-large delegates won in the
Illinois primary. Had he formally withdrawn from the race, those
delegates would have gone automatically to Jackson, who finished
second in Illinois.
   Asked whether his move could be seen as an effort to deprive
Jackson of support, Simon said, ``I am sure it is not perceived by
Jesse Jackson as a stop-Jackson effort.'' He said he had spoken to
Jackson and the other two remaining Democratic candidates _
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Sen. Albert Gore Jr. _ about
his plans.
   Simon said he would keep a lock on the 170 delegates he has won
and an aide said he hoped to perhaps attract a few more by the time
the party's last primaries end on June 7. At that point, Simon
said, he will meet with the delegates and decide what to do next.
   ``I owe something to those delegates,'' he said. A total of
2,082 delegates is needed to nominate a candidate.
   Simon showed early strength in the Democratic campaign,
finishing a close second in Iowa's first-in-the-nation caucuses.
But he dropped to third in New Hampshire and failed to rebound as
the primary season wore on, except for a lone win in his home
state. His bid bottomed out Tuesday in Wisconsin, where he finished
last with just 5 percent of the vote.
   He blamed his campaign's precipitous decline on a failure to
effectively communicate his message of traditional Democratic party
values, and on a lack of money, but said he did not see his failure
as a rejection of those values.
   ``I do belive we have to have a government that cares, and the
American people believe that, too _ that I know,'' he said to the
cheers of supporters who packed a Senate hearing room where he made
his announcement.
   ``I really believe the American people are ready for a candidate
who says let's put unemployed people to work, let's have quality
schools for this nation,'' he said.
   But Simon said he still is concerned, as he said at the outset
of his campaign a year ago, that the Democratic Party could
``become a clone'' of the Republican Party by forgetting its past.
   ``We can't build the kind of nation we want if we simply pander
to the wishes of the rich and powerful,'' he said.
   Simon, 59, stayed true to his liberal background during the
campaign. With his trademark bow-tie and claim to the plain-spoken
legacy of Harry Truman, he said often that voters were ``ready for
something other than the slick, packaged product.''
   He proposed long-term health care for the elderly, a public
works program for the unemployed and new education initiatives, and
promised that as president he would balance the budget in three
years. But critics questioned how he could reconcile promises to
set up expensive new programs while also claiming to be a fiscal
conservative who would balance the budget.
</TEXT>
