<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon     04-07 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslem Factions Battle, 39 Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDMOND SHEDID</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABATIYEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighting raged for the third day in a
showdown for dominance in south Lebanon between Shiite Moslem
militias allied with Syria and Iran. Police said 39 people were
killed and 96 wounded.
   Casualties for the three days stood at 51 dead and 130 wounded,
according to police figures
   The battle is between Justice Minister Nabih Berri's mainstream
militia Amal, supported by Syria, and Hezbollah, or Party of God,
which is loyal to Iran.
   It continued despite repeated cease-fire appeals from the
highest Shiite clerics. That may indicate Syria wants to crus
Iran's challenge to its role as the main power broker in Lebanon,
where the Syrians have 25,000 troops.
   A police spokesman said Amal units with armored personnel
carriers advanced about noon into the coastal town of Ghaziyeh, a
key Hezbollah stronghold.
   By nightfall, Amal recaptured the village after ``ferocious
house-to-house fighting,'' police reported. They said most of the
day's casualties occurred in Ghaziyeh, five miles south of Sidon,
the provincial capital of south Lebanon.
   Amal said its fighters had captured and disarmed several
Hezbollah militiamen.
   ``With the recapture of Ghaziyeh, Amal has established
undisputed control over the whole of south Lebanon as well as the
main coastal highway,'' which links the predominantly Shiite south
to the rest of Lebanon, the communique said.
   Trouble between Amal and Hezbollah began Feb. 17, when Lt. Col.
William R. Higgins, the U.S. Marine who commands U.N. truce
observers, was kidnapped near Tyre and Amal rounded up dozens of
Hezbollah members it accused of involvement.
   Shiite militants loyal to Iran are believed to hold most of the
22 foreign hostages in Lebanon, who include nine Americans. Held
longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of
The Associated Press, kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   The police spokesman said Amal had seized 11 towns and villages,
and Hezbollah fighters remain entrenched in three hamlets in
addition to Ghaziyeh.
   Hezbollah issued a statement in Sidon accused Amal of stopping a
convoy of international and Lebanese Red Cross vehicles that
carried three wounded Hezbollahis from south Lebanon for treatment
in Beirut.
   ``The assailants forced all Red Cross personnel out of the
ambulances and then raked the vehicles with gunfire, killing the
three wounded men on their stretchers,'' the statement said.
   Amal denied involvement in the attack, whichoccurred after
nightfall near the village of Aaqbiyeh, 12 miles south of Sidon.
   Police confirmed the attack without reporting the politics of
the assailants or victims. They said no Red Cross personnel were
hurt.
   The attack by Amal on Ghaziyeh ``obviously aims at stripping
Hezbollah in south Lebanon of its main supply line,'' said the
police spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing
regulations.
   The road to south Lebanon has been blocked at Ghaziyeh since
Wednesday, when Hezbollah fighters overran an Amal checkpoint in
the town.
   The spokesman said Hezbollah's 40 fighters in the village of
Kfar Roumman surrendered to Amal a few hours after Amal seized the
adjacent town of Nabatiyeh in a ``sweeping attack.'' Nabatiyeh, 18
miles southeast of Sidon, is a mainly Shiite town of 50,000.
   An Associated Press reporter saw six Hezbollah fighters, their
hands up, emerging from a gutted house in Nabatiyeh's old sector
and surrendering to Amal militiamen.
   Fighting for Nabatiyeh was fierce. The two sides traded
rocket-propelled grenades and mortar rounds until Hezbollah's last
stronghold at the town's Christian school fell to Aamal attackers.
   The school, occupied by Hezbollah when the confrontation broke
out Tuesday, was devastated with its walls peppered with shell
holes, blown-out windows and fire-blackened wooden desks.
</TEXT>
