<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MingoIndictments 1stLd-Writethru a0465 04-07 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mingo Indictments, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0465,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Indicts 16 Political Figures</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with another state senator indicted.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special grand jury investigating
political corruption indicted 16 Mingo County political figures
Thursday, including two state senators, three former House of
Delegates members, the county prosecutor and Williamson's mayor.
   Also indicted were two county commissioners, a current and
former magistrate, one former and two current county school board
members, and the former county and circuit clerks, a spokesman in
the circuit clerk's office said.
   State Sen. Truman Chafin, a one-time Democratic candidate for
governor, was indicted on a felony count of bribery for allegedly
accepting money when he was a county commissioner as part of a
scheme to sell the sheriff's job for $100,000. Chafin was indicted
separately from the other 15.
   All others were charged in a 10-count indictment with various
violations of state election laws, as well as with a felony count
of conspiracy. The indictment alleges that they ``associated
together with Johnie M. Owens and others to improperly affect and
influence the free election system and the law enforcement system
of Mingo County.
   Sen. John Pat Fanning, also a Democrat, was indicted on two
counts of bribery, one count of conspiracy and one count of filing
false accounts _ all felonies _ and one count each of making
political contributions exceeding the state limits and failing to
report political expenditures, both misdemeanors.
   Chafin and Fanning both were reported to be out of their offices
late Thursday afternoon and were unavailable for comment.
   Also named as defendants are Mingo County Prosecutor W. Thomas
Ward, county school board members Paul Sizemore and Robert
Simpkins, former Delegates James B. Simpkins, Irvine K.O. Damron,
and R. Doyle Van Meter II, County Commissioners Ronnie Rumora and
Steve Adkins, former Mingo County Magistrate Joey Kohari,
Magistrate Bill Webb, former Circuit Clerk Robert J. ``Jack'' Webb,
former County Clerk Hugh Wellman, Williamson Mayor Sam Kapourales,
and Larry Hamrick, a former school board member and former director
of the county's anti-poverty agency.
   Also indicted Thursday was Goodwill Motors Inc., a used car
dealership at Delbarton owned by former county commissioner and
county Democratic Chairman Stewart Justice. Justice was not named
in the indictment.
   Arraignment for all defendants is scheduled Wednesday in Mingo
County Circuit Court.
   All charges pertain to the 1984 election, except for two counts
that involve the 1986 election.
   Last week, grand jurors heard testimony from candidates in the
1984 and 1986 primary elections, including Fanning, Damron, James
B. Simpkins and Van Meter.
   Also appearing before the grand jury were United Mine Workers
Local 1440 President Bill Davis and Wally Warden, editor of the
Williamson Daily News.
   The newspaper has extensively covered the state and federal
probes in Mingo County, and Warden provided jurors with background
on the makeup of campaign slates in past elections and with
information on precincts that have been the site of voting
irregularities.
   Davis reportedly was questioned about campaign contributions and
financial support from COMPAC, the UMW's political action committee.
   The grand jury has indicted several current and former Mingo
County officials, including Sheriff Charles ``Eddie'' Hilbert, in
connection with the sale of the sheriff's office in 1982 for
$100,000.
   Owens and Runyon have pleaded guilty in that matter and will be
sentenced April 18, the same day Hilbert is scheduled to enter a
plea as part of an agreement with prosecutors. Adkins is awaiting
trial.
</TEXT>
