<HEAD>Jackson Organizers Concerned Over Comments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's campaign organizers in Georgia
expressed concern Thursday over comments by some of the state's top
Democrats that Jackson cannot win the presidency.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, Gov. Joe Frank Harris, and Georgia House Speaker
Tom Murphy, all Democrats, recently said they do not believe
Jackson, if nominated by their party at the national convention
here in July, can win the election in November.
   ``Yes, it does concern me _ it concerns me that politicians of
whatever race automatically discount the electability and the
credibility of other political candidates,'' said Decatur Mayor
Mike Mears, co-chairman of Jackson's Georgia campaign.
   Jackson's other co-chairman, state Sen. Eugene Walker, said
party leaders had assured him that Jackson's Super Tuesday showing
would be properly reflected in the allocation of at-large delegate
slots to be filled in May.
   But, Walker added, ``we're providing the commensurate work and
diligence to ensure that we get those things.''
   Jackson led the field in Georgia's March 8 Super Tuesday
primary, capturing 40 percent of the vote and 36 of the 77
delegates at stake.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Koch Fears He Won't Be A Delegate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch said Thursday he may not be
a delegate to the Democratic National Convention because he favors
New York Gov. Mario Cuomo for president.
   Koch said he would like to be an uncommitted delegate so he
could work to draft Cuomo, who is not running for the nomination.
   However, he said, 15 percent of the voters in the April 19
primary must cast ballots for ``uncommitted'' to empower the state
Democratic committee to send uncommitted delegates _ such as Koch _
to the convention.
   The mayor has balked at backing one of the candidates, even
though his commitment would end after the first ballot.
   ``I'm not going to endorse before the convention because I still
want Cuomo,'' he told reporters. ``I think it would be unfair for
me to endorse someone other than Mario Cuomo ... and then desert
them at the convention.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Dukakis' Comment Sounds A Lot Like Koch's Remark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Worcester Telegram says Michael
Dukakis is using a line about charisma and competence that sounds a
lot like one used a decade ago by Edward I. Koch.
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor running for the Democratic
presidential campaign, has responded recently to comments that he
is on the dull and boring side by saying that ``after eight years
of charisma, maybe it's time for a little competence.''
   The Telegram said Thursday that in 1977, when Koch was running
for mayor of New York City, he asked: ``After eight years of
charisma and four years of the clubhouse, why not try competence?''
_ a reference to the terms of Mayors John Lindsay and Abe Beame.
   But Koch apparently is not disturbed by Dukakis' failure to
attribute the quote, the newspaper said, and it quoted Koch aide
Larry Simonberg as saying, ``We're not charging for the slogan''
and adding ``it doesn't bother him the least. He's aware of it.''
   Mark Gearan, spokesman for the Dukakis campaign, agreed the
quote was similar to the one used by Koch but he said there was no
deliberate attempt to steal it. ``I think by any measure it was
total happenstance,'' he said.
  
</TEXT>
