<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1843EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0693 04-07 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0693,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Accord Appears to Meet U.S. Terms, Officials Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS lede, grafs 6-8 pvs, bgng: State Department, and 14-18,
bgng: The Shultz, to CLARIFY U.S. proposal; ADDS 5 new grafs with
Byrd, Humphrey comments; single name Najib correct in 4th graf</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet-Afghan agreement under which the
Red Army may start pulling out of Afghanistan by May 15 appears to
meet U.S. conditions on continuing aid to the warring parties,
administration sources said Thursday.
   President Reagan was described by his chief of staff, Howard
Baker, as ``cautiously optimistic.'' But Reagan still ``wants to
see the fine print,'' Baker told reporters in California, where
Reagan is vacationing.
   ``We think an agreement now is clearly within reach,'' said one
administration source in Washington who closely monitors Afghan
developments.
   Administration officials interpreted a statement issued by
Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and his Afghan ally Najib as
``an indication that they have agreed to our conditions, but we
want to know that authoritatively,'' said the source, who spoke on
condition of annoymity.
   The administration is waiting to hear from the Soviets on a
proposal advanced by Secretary of State George P. Shultz on March
31. He said the United States _ under what is being called a
``gentlemen's agreement'' _ would continue its estimated $600
million a year in covert aid to the Afghan guerrillas as long as
Moscow was aiding the Kabul regime.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Thursday that
the United States has not budged from the Shultz formula, which
embodies what diplomats call ``positive symmetry.''
   She said the Soviets had rejected a proposal involving
``negative symmetry,'' in which the two sides would end aid shortly
after an agreement was signed.
   ``Our position is clear,'' Mrs. Oakley said. ``Such an agreement
must be a comprehensive settlement that provides for the prompt
withdrawal of all Soviet troops, an independent non-aligned
Afghanistan, self-determination for the Afghan people and the
return of the refugees in safety and honor.''
   Two other administration sources involved with Afghanistan, also
speaking on condition of anonymity, said the next step would be to
seek agreement at the United Nations-brokered talks in Geneva on
formation of an interim Afghan government during the Soviet
withdrawal.
   ``The parties are going to work very hard on the interim
government,'' said one official. ``It is the next item on the
agenda. But it is not clear whether it will be part of the
agreement.''
   The Gorbachev-Najib communique, issued after a surprise meeting
between the two in the Soviet Central Asia city of Tashkent, said
``the last obstacles to concluding the agreements have now been
removed thanks to constructive cooperation of all who are involved
in the settlement and favor their immediate signing.''
   The declaration said the road was now clear for formation of a
coalition government including all political forces in Afghanistan,
``including those who are currently opposed to one another.''
   Many of the guerrillas balked at Najib's previous political
overtures, which he has billed as ``national reconciliation.''
   The administration has seesawed on the question of ending aid to
resistance. The State Department had been pushing for cessation of
aid to the guerrillas within 60 days of an agreement.
   But last December, Reagan said he would continue sending aid to
the Mujahedeen guerrillas until the last of the 115,000 Soviet
soldiers left Afghanistan.
   The Senate, acting on a resolution introduced by Majority Leader
Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., urged Reagan in a 77-0 vote to stick to his
guns, and at the beginning of March, the State Department made the
tougher line a formal U.S. position at the Geneva talks.
   The Soviets rejected that, and Shultz proposed ``negative
symmetry,'' or simultaneous cessation of aid, a softer line than
advanced by Reagan in December. But the Soviets rejected that too,
and Shultz proposed ``positive symmetry,'' which was closer to the
positions taken by Reagan last December and the Senate in February.
   Byrd applauded the latest turn of events.
   ``Secretary Shultz has kept me informed of the developments
during the last three weeks of negotiations. From our
conversations, I believe that my concerns have been met. I want to
give this agreement a chance,'' Byrd said in a statement issued by
his office.
   Another lawmaker who has vocally supported the guerrillas, Sen.
Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., was pessimistic about the chances of the
proposed agreement.
   ``If the option to resupply is not in writing, then the
government of Pakistan (which channels aid to the guerrillas) is
going to find itself in under tremendous domestic and international
pressure to pinch or sever the arms pipeline,'' Humphrey said in a
telephone interview.
   At the same time, the United States greatly increased its covert
arms shipments to the guerrillas, but curtailed shipments of
hand-held Stinger anti-aircraft missiles, according to
congressional sources who closely track the issue.
</TEXT>
