<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-DrugPriest     04-07 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Drug Priest,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italians Want to Try Priest on Drug Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Lorenzo Zorza, a Roman Catholic priest
wanted in New York on drug trafficking charges, should be tried in
Italy, the investigating judge said Thursday.
   A U.S. official said, however, that Zorza was expected to be
extradited.
   Zorza, 46, is an American citizen who lives in New York City and
was arrested by Italian drug police Wednesday in Bologna. He was
among 39 people charged in Manhattan last week with participating
in a large international heroin and smuggling ring with links to
the Sicilian Mafia.
   Zorza was arrested at the home of an art restorer identified by
police as Adria Gialdini. She and her husband, Vittorio Santunione,
were arrested on charges of aiding and abetting the fugitive and
possession of firearms.
   In announcing Zorza's arrest Wednesday, U.S. Attorney Rudolph
Giuliani said in New York: ``The Italian government will turn him
over to U.S. authorities, probably federal marshals, tomorrow.''
   The priest remained in Italian custody, however, and was brought
to Rome for interrogation by investigating magistrate Margherita
Gerunda, who issued the arrest warrant March 29.
   Asked about extradition, the judge replied: ``He was arrested on
a warrant issued by the Italian judicial authority. ... He is
expected to be tried in Italy. The main judicial authority is in
Italy.''
   Judge Gerunda added, however, that there ``might be some
political considerations, perhaps a temporary extradition,''
because Zorza is an American citizen.
   She said charges against Zorza in Italy include associating with
organized crime, criminal association for drug trafficking,
importation of drugs, counterfeiting and illegal exportation of art
works.
   An American official said privately that extradition is expected
``in due course'' but ``first you have to go through all the formal
procedures.''
</TEXT>
