<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BlackStudies     04-07 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black Studies,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scholars Convene For Conference on Black Studies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scholars from around the world gathered on
Thursday to discuss ways to foster black studies on college
campuses and to help the public understand the African perspective.
   The 12th Annual Conference of the National Council for Black
Studies, which runs through Saturday, will include workshops and
panel discussions on topics ranging from the needs of black
students at predominantly white schools to blacks and AIDS in
Philadelphia and the depiction of blacks in the media.
   In keeping with the theme ``The Struggle for Black Minds:
Operationalizing Afrocentricity,'' the 250 scholars attending the
conference will try to find ways to allow others to see the world
from an African perspective, according to Kariamu Welsh, assistant
professor of African Studies at Temple.
   The conference will allow scholars to develop support for
African studies and to examine ways to make the African perspective
relative to all fields, she said.
   Diane Abbott, the first black woman elected to Parliament in
Britain, was scheduled to deliver the keynote address Friday.
   The schedule also includes Doyin Abiola, managing director of
the Concord Publishing Group, who helped break barriers for female
journalists in Nigeria.
   In addition, the conference features Molefi Asante, professor
and chairman of the department of African-American studies at
Temple University. He has written 23 books, the latest being the
controversial ``The Afrocentric Idea,'' which tries to present
African history from an African rather than European perspective.
   The conference is sponsored by the African-American studies
departments of Temple, the University of Pennsylvania and
Pennsylvania State University.
</TEXT>
