<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CarltonShot     04-07 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlton Shot,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jazz Guitarist Changes Hospitals for Security</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jazz guitarist Larry Carlton, who was shot in
the neck at his home by two teen-agers, was moved to an undisclosed
hospital for security reasons Thursday as police puzzled over the
motive for the attack.
   The Grammy Award winner, wounded Wednesday as he arrived at his
Hollywood Hills home, was in stable condition in the new hospital,
said Detective Russ Kuster.
   ``We just suggested routine, everyday security procedures,''
Kuster said, explaining the move from St. Joseph Medical Center in
Burbank, where Carlton underwent four hours of surgery after the
attack.
   Carlton, 40, was conscious in the hospital and described his
attackers as two boys between the ages of 14 and 17 who had a
German shepherd puppy with them, Kuster said. Investigators haven't
been able to determine the motive, he said.
   The shooting took place at 3 p.m. Wednesday, as Carlton arrived
at his home in the exclusive Lake Hollywood area surrounding a
reservoir in the hills 10 miles northwest of downtown.
   ``He walked inside, left the door open,'' Kuster related. ``He
looked outside, saw a little dog and saw a gun pointed at him.''
   Carlton won a best pop instrumental performance Grammy this year
for his version of the Doobie Brothers' ``Minute By Minute,'' and
shared the same award in 1981 with pianist Mike Post for their work
on the ``Hill Street Blues'' theme.
   The musician toured with the Fifth Dimension vocal group during
the 1960s and was a member of the Jazz Crusaders during the early
1970s.
</TEXT>
