<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SkullsFound     04-07 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Skulls Found,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Get New Search Warrant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police returned with a new search
warrant Thursday to a house where skulls and bone fragments were
found after a man said he was tortured and sexually abused there
for four days last week.
   The owner of the house, flea market merchant Robert Berdella, is
jailed without bond on seven counts of forcible sodomy and one each
of felonious restraint and first-degree assault.
   The alleged offenses all involve a 22-year-old man who wore only
a dog collar when he escaped from Berdella's home by jumping from a
second-floor window on Saturday. Authorities who arrested Berdella,
39, said they found pictures of the man being tortured and abused,
and similar pictures of other young men, one of whom appeared to be
dead.
   Police have been looking for possible links between Berdella and
11 missing persons cases, including those of two young men with
whom he was reportedly seen.
   His arrest led to the discovery of two human skulls, one
apparently a relic, in the home, while another was unearthed from
the backyard, along with bone fragments. It has not yet been
determined if those fragments are human.
   Police said Thursday that an interview with a carpenter who had
helped build a deck at the back of the house led authorities to
believe they might find more skulls or skeletons under the deck.
   But they began their work Thursday by using power saws to cut
through planks of the front porch.
   ``We don't want to take a chance on overlooking anything,'' said
Meyer. ``We're not going to leave that stone unturned.''
   He also said the investigative team working on the case had been
increased from six detectives to 11 so police can follow up on
calls from people who claim to have known Berdella.
   Police are still trying to identify eight young men in hundreds
of bondage pictures found in Berdella's home.
</TEXT>
