<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hijack-Passengers     04-07 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijack-Passengers,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Passengers Say Hijackers `Quite Considerate'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britons freed from a hijacked Kuwaiti jumbo jet in
Iran said Thursday the seizure was frightening but the Arab gunmen
soon relaxed and became ``quite considerate.''
   The 22 Britons were among two groups of hostages freed by
hijackers who forced the Kuwait Airlines Boeing 747, which was en
route from Bangkok to Kuwait, to land early Tuesday at Mashhad in
northeastern Iran. The Foreign Office said all the freed Britons
were ``fit and well.''
   Several spoke to British Broadcasting Corp. radio from Iran
before leaving for home.
   Various reports put the number of hijackers at five to seven.
They demand the relase of 17 pro-Iranian extremists convicted and
imprisoned in Kuwait for bombing the U.S. and French embassies in
the Persian Gulf sheikdom in 1983.
   Susan Carew-Jones, an advertising executive from London, said
the hijacking began as passengers slept.
   ``Suddenly there was a lot of shouting and we saw the terrorists
with grenades and we were told to put our hands on our heads and
look down,'' she said. ``When you see people with grenades and guns
you have to fear for your life.''
   After 15 or 20 minutes the passengers were ``herded together in
one section of the plane'' and told to keep their hands on their
heads until the landing at Mashhad Airport, she said.
   ``Then they told us to relax and be calm, and they were fine,''
Mrs. Carew-Jones said. ``They were quite relaxed themselves by
then. Nobody panicked.''
   ``They were quite considerate,'' she said, allowing her to
change seats to sit with her husband David. They gave oxygen to
passengers who felt ill when the cabin grew stuffy, she added.
   Social worker Jerry Moore, also from London, said the hostages
were ``treated very well.''
   There was ``no violence, no aggression,'' he said. ``Obviously
we were very frightened and intimidated for the first two or three
hours, but once we landed things settled down.''
   An Austrian businessman among those released said the gunmen
were brutal when they seized the plane but later treated the
hostages well.
   Josef Degeorgi, 53, who manages the IBM office in Kuwait, said
all the hijackers wore masks and they spoke English to non-Arab
passengers.
   At the outset, crew members were forced to lie on the floor with
their hands behind their heads and some passengers were handcuffed,
Degeorgi said.
   ``At this stage things were quite brutal,'' he said, ``but they
told passengers repeatedly to be calm, not to worry. They were
really very friendly to us.''
   Degeorgi said the air conditioning system failed to work at
times and it became very hot inside the aircraft, but ``the
treatment was excellent otherwise, with plenty of food and water.''
</TEXT>
