<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 2116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-IraqBombs     04-07 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Iraq Bombs,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say 180 Tons of Cluster Bomb Components Shipped</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 180 tons of material, presumed to be
components for cluster bombs, were shipped from Italy to Iraq since
June, police said Thursday.
   Italian law forbids sale or supply of arms to Iraq or to Iran,
which have been at war in the Persian Gulf since September 1980.
Officials here said two men were arrested and a third was sought.
   The shipments were halted with the March 24 seizure at Rome's
Leonardo da Vinci airport of nearly 27 tons of bomb parts about to
be loaded on an Iraqi Airways jet bound for Baghdad, said officials
of the carabinieri, Italy's paramilitary police force.
   An added 33 tons of parts, waiting to be transported to the
airport and eventually to Iraq, also were seized recently in Italy,
the police said.
   Customs declarations were falsified to describe the components
as parts for furniture or spare parts for home appliances or
plumbing repair, the police said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   They said documents examined by police showed the Iraqi Ministry
of Planning ordered the shipments and the Iraqi government
provided, for export agents in Rome, a letter of credit for $8
million to cover dealings with Italian factories manufacturing the
parts.
   Cluster bombs, designed to spread shrapnel over a wide area, are
an effective anti-personnel weapon. Iraq has used such bombs to
break up mass Iranian ground assaults. Iran says Iraq dropped
cluster bombs in Kurdistan against villages which it says were also
hit by chemical bombs March 16-17.
   Police reported finding Iraqi government documents outlining
which components were needed for the cluster bombs.
   A police official said other bomb components, 16 tons in all,
were seized at 27 small factories that received the Iraqi orders. A
few factories are in the Milan area; others are in Tuscany.
   No one answered at the Iraqi Embassy in Rome when called for
comment.
   Police said Thursday the two men arrested were charged with
construction, export and illegal holding of war arms. Both worked
for an import-export firm in Rome that police said arranged the
bomb parts delivery.
   Officers identified them as Iraqi-born Ahmad Al Kodasi, 30, an
Italian citizen, and Hamoudi Jaffar Kasim, 21, of Baghdad.
   Police said they a third man sought is an Iraqi.
   They said no charges have been brought against factory officials.
   The parts ranged from metal tubes and cones, which the factories
described as plumbing pieces, to plastic connecting parts listed on
the inventory as table legs, police said.
   Several investigations are being carried out in Italy into the
alleged supply of weapons to Iran by Italian arms manufacturers.
</TEXT>
