<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 2234EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PublicHousing     04-07 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Public Housing,370</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at Midnight EDT - time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Up to $9.2 Billion Needed To Upgrade Existing Public Housing,
Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban
Development estimates it will cost up to $9.2 billion to make the
nation's existing public housing ``decent, safe and sanitary.''
   The estimate, in a report issued for publication Friday, is
based on inspection of 2,196 units and 3,120 buildings at public
housing projects across the country at the end of 1985. It took
more than two years and $5 million to compile and review the final
report which was ordered by Congress, HUD officials said.
   Since then, said HUD deputy assistant secretary C. Duncan
MacRae, $3.9 billion has been spent. He said another study to be
completed this summer will show how much needs to be spent each
year to keep public housing at mandatory HUD standards.
   The study released by HUD Secretary Samuel R. Pierce said repair
and renovation of existing units among the 1.3 million dwellings
nationwide will cost between $7.5 billion and $9.2 billion.
   ``HUD is committed to restoring the public housing stock to
decent, safe and sanitary conditions in every instance where that
housing is viable,'' Pierce said. The report indicates that only 5
percent to 10 percent of public housing is not viable and not worth
modernizing.
   HUD mandatory modernization standards include repairs and
changes to ``preserve public health and safety, ensure bulding
integrity, meet local code requirements and meet federal standards
for accessibliity for the handicapped as well as reduction of
hazards associated with lead-based paint,'' said a HUD statement
accompanying the study.
   Pierce said half the nation's public housing has been in service
for between 20 and 40 years.
   He said that after the backlog is met, additional funds will be
needed from federal, state and local governments.
   The 283-page report, ``Study of the Modernization Needs of the
Public and Indian Housing Stock,'' was based on data gathered by
Abt Associates of Cambridge, Mass.
   Its estimates cover 11,000 public housing projects, where
low-income families live, paying about 30 percent of their incomes
as rent. Individual housing authorities own the units, aided by
federal assistance and financing.
   Officials say 3 million Americans live in public housing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
