<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-US 1stLd-Writethru   04-07 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-US, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0726,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-South Korea Field Exercise Ends</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To CORRECT spelling of assistant secretary of state to Sigur,
sted Segur, sub 6th graf: U.S. Assistant ....; picks up 7th graf
pvs: Washington has ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and South Korea on
Thursday ended their annual military field training exercise
involving U.S. troops from the American continent and Pacific
areas, a military announcement said.
   The 10-day field exercise, which was held at various parts of
South Korea, was the highlight of Team Spirit 88 which involved
about 200,000 troops from the two countries.
   The announcement from the U.S.-South Korea Combined Forces
Command said that all deployed forces will return to their home
bases by early May.
   The command said Team Spirit, which was first held in 1976, was
designed to improve defensive readiness of South Korean and U.S.
forces through joint operations.
   Seoul has attached a special meaning to the joint exercise
because North Korea threatens to disrupt the Seoul Olympic Games.
Pyongyang has refused to take part in the Games unless its demand
to be made a cohost is met.
   U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Gaston Sigur said Tuesday
while on a visit here that the exercise was ``a valuable
demonstraton of our commitment to preserving peace ... and timely
in this year of the Seoul Olympics.''
   Washington has pledged to provide necessary security support to
prevent North Korea from disrupting the Games.
   Also on Thursday, the U.S. Air Force said it plans to introduce
at least 24 more F-16 fighters this year to improve combat
capability of its tactical fighter wing in South Korea.
   The U.S. Air Force said its 51st Tactical Fighter Wing here
would replace F-4E Phantom II fighters now in service with F-16
fighters this fall.
   U.S. officials said the introduction of F-16 Fighting Falcons
would help meet military threat from North Korea and the
modernization of the Soviet military in the region.
   Currently, 12 F-4E Phamtom fighters are assigned to two U.S. air
bases in South Korea each: the 36th Tactical Fighter Squadron in
Osan and the 497th Tactical Fighter Squadron in Taegu, they said.
   A U.S. Air Force statement said the 36th TFS will receive 24
F-16C and D models in October 1989 to improve and modernize its
combat capability and readiness.
   The 497th TFS in Taegu will be deactivated early next year in
line with budget cuts, with its 12 F-4E Phantom fighters to be
released for foreign sales, the statement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880407-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 2058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a BC-Theater     04-07 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Borderlines,' Two One-Act Plays by John Bishop, Open Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The men in ``Borderlines,'' the umbrella title
for two new one-act plays by John Bishop, sure have their problems.
   ``Right now I'm having trouble connecting to things,'' admits
Charles Graham, the protagonist in the evening's pretentious
curtain-raiser. It's called ``Borderline'' without the ``s,''
presumably to mark its anti-hero's precarious state of mind.
   Charles is a yuppyish marketing specialist who sells things like
shampoo and toothpaste, but his mind is not on his work. He worries
about his stale marriage, frets about the big basketball game he
blew in high school, commiserates and drinks with a crude
co-worker, sleeps with a young secretary and finally kills the
woman's jealous boyfriend.
   In between these episodes, a lecturer appears on stage to
outline Charles' violent family tree which she traces back several
centuries to the border wars between England and Scotland. His
ancestors made their way to America where they were involved in one
disastrous episode after another _ from Indian wars in Pennsylvania
to battles between cowboys and sheepmen in Arizona and fights over
land in Oklahoma.
   Bishop suggests that Charles' homicidal nature was preordained.
It's in man's genes and no amount of moping about and worrying is
going to change things.
   Much of the same anxiety pervades ``Keepin' An Eye On Louie,''
the second and much more successful half of the evening. This time,
the man at sea with himself is Dave, a policeman who keeps a New
York mobster named Louie under surveillance.
   Dave is just as miserable as Charles but in this play, the
dialogue crackles with blue-collar banter. There are a lot of jokes
about members of the mob with first names like Bananas or Tomatoes
or Philadelphia or Detroit.
   Also enlivening the proceedings is the appearance _ in drag _ of
Louie's recalcitrant son-in-law, who has decided to help the police
and identify members of the mob.
   Dave also can't communicate with his wife. The reason is never
made clear, although the playwright paints a picture of a man
closer to his job and his fellow police officers than the woman he
married. It's an unsatisfactory portrait.
   The cast is first-rate, particularly Cotter Smith as the
distraught executive in the first play and Bruce McCarty as the
unnerved policeman in the second. They bring a conviction to their
roles that is not supported by the writing.
   Despite those performances and Robert Bailey's fluid direction,
``Borderlines,'' which arrived Thursday at off-Broadway's Circle
Repertory Company, never becomes much more than two morose, murky
tales of male menopause.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880407-0236 </DOCNO>
