<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostage Freed, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0844,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Fatally Shoot Hostage Taker</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6 to UPDATE with description of scene from
photo, dropping attribution to newspaper report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos HX2, HX3, HX7</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police ended a three-hour siege Wednesday by
fatally shooting a suicidal 20-year-old man who had held his young
girlfriend hostage apparently with a fake gun, authorities said.
   Israel Ramos died Wednesday afternoon of a single gunshot wound
at York Hospital, where he had been taken for surgery, a hospital
spokeswoman said. The hostage, a 14-year-old runaway whose name was
withheld by authorities, was not injured.
   Ramos had held what appeared to be an automatic gun to the
girl's head, which was covered by a pillowcase.
   Authorities originally said that a police sharpshooter fired at
Ramos after the hostage taker said, ``I am now going to kill her.''
   But film shot by WGAL-TV in Lancaster showed Ramos was hit by a
bullet moments after he swore at police and said ``I'm coming out.''
   Both Ramos' hands were on a window ledge, no gun was apparent
and the girl was out of view. As soon as Ramos was shot in the
abdomen, the teen came to the window shouting for an ambulance.
   Police Chief William Hose, who was not present at the shooting,
said the initial accounts may have been wrong and that the incident
was being investigated. State police were called in to assist.
   The chief said a handgun and an Uzi-type rifle found in Ramos'
apartment appeared to be fakes.
   The sharpshooter's name was not released.
   During the siege, Ramos tossed radios, a stereo, pizza boxes and
shoes from the window as he swore at police and asked whether he
should beat his hostage.
   He refused to surrender despite pleas from his psychiatric
counselor, who had been treating Ramos for suicidal tendencies,
said police Lt. Dennis McMaster.
</TEXT>
