<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet-Afghan agreement under which the
Red Army may start pulling out of Afghanistan by May 15 appears to
meet U.S. conditions for ending aid to the warring parties,
administration sources said Thursday.
   President Reagan was described by his chief of staff, Howard
Baker, as ``cautiously optimistic.'' But Reagan still ``wants to
see the fine print,'' Baker told reporters in California, where
Reagan is vacationing.
   ``We think an agreement now is clearly within reach,'' said one
administration source in Washington who closely monitors Afghan
developments.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois Sen. Paul Simon suspended his stalled
presidential campaign Thursday but held onto his 170 delegates in
hopes of influencing the choice of a nominee at the Democratic
national convention in July. Jesse Jackson immediately blasted
Simon for keeping the delegates, saying most of them were
rightfully his.
   ``In a year that has already seen many surprises, no one knows
what twists and turns may develop between now and then,'' Simon
told a news conference. ``There will be many encounters with fate
before the contest is ultimately decided in a wide-open
convention.''
   In a quasi-withdrawal, Simon said he would no longer actively
campaign for the nomination but said he technically would remain a
candidate even though he conceded he has ``no illusions that the
nomination will come my way.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis phoned
twice. His wife, Kitty, called too. Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore
Jr.'s staff called as well, but Patricia Russell is clinging to her
neutrality.
   Mrs. Russell is a ``super delegate,'' one of the 645 party
officials who could tip the balance on the Democratic presidential
nominee at the national convention in Atlanta July 18-21.
   The candidates, realizing that the emergence of a clear-cut
delegate leader from the primary process is unlikely, are placing
greater emphasis on securing the support of the super delegates.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In dusty fields and stadiums across
Panama, civilians turn out by the hundreds for military training to
repel what the government says is an imminent U.S. invasion.
   ``We get political speeches, and sometimes we see patriotic
films,'' said Javier Ortega, a government housing ministry
employee. ``We do physical training and we have some weapons
instruction.''
   The volunteer units, called ``Dignity Battalions,'' formed, and
have grown, since the United States started announcing increases in
troop strength in the former Panama Canal Zone in mid-March.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARRIS ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chants of women recruits jogging
in the warm April sun drift through the open windows of the Law
Center at the Marine Corps Recruit Depot.
   Inside, Marine officers are continuing an investigation of
lesbianism, which has already led to charges against several former
drill instructors and at least one officer.
   Five women Marines have been charged with various counts
including committing indecent acts. Two other women who were due to
go before administrative hearing boards are seeking discharges.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Working indoors may be hazardous to your health
after all, suggests a study that says modern, energy efficient
buildings may significantly increase the risk of communicable
respiratory infections.
   The study examined the incidence of influenza and other
respiratory illnesses among about 400,000 trainees at four Army
training centers in the southeast and south-central United States
from October 1982 to September 1986. But the researchers said the
findings may apply to office buildings and other structures
designed for maximum energy efficiency.
   Researchers found that trainees housed in modern barracks were
about 50 percent more likely to contract a respiratory infection
during the seven-week basic training period than those who stayed
in older, more drafty buildings.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The beat of a different drummer that makes
some children extremely shy and others very outgoing may actually
be a biological rhythm set at birth and continued throughout life,
researchers say.
   In a study appearing Friday in the journal Science, three
researchers said they found that extremely inhibited children
actually experience an increased heartbeat, a dilation of the
pupils and a tensing of muscles when confronted by strangers or
other social stresses.
   ``It appears that a small percentage of children are born with a
biological disposition that would tend to make them shy, and this
is independent of what the parent has or has not done,'' said
Steven Reznick, a Yale University psychologist.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grade A eggs appear to be a main source of
salmonella infections that have sickened hundreds of people in the
Northeast in recent years, and the problem may be spreading, a
federal researcher said Thursday.
   Previous egg-related salmonella food poisoning has been limited
to eggs that were cracked, dirty or otherwise defective or
mishandled, said Dr. Michael E. St. Louis of the Centers for
Disease Control in Atlanta.
   The new findings implicate Grade A eggs, which have been
screened for defects and whose shells have been sanitized with
chemical disinfectant, St. Louis said in a telephone interview.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Day after day, a small, dapper man in a grey derby
has trudged up the federal courthouse steps weighed down with a
document-filled suitcase and the threat of a 10-year prison
sentence.
   Charles Merrill Mount, an art historian and portrait painter, is
charged with selling documents that belong to the Library of
Congress and National Archives. The government has portrayed him as
a thief, a Brooklyn native with an affected British accent who has
had previous scrapes with the law.
   But Mount's friends say he is genuine, a self-taught scholar and
Guggenheim Foundation fellow who wrote well-received artist
biographies and collected an impressive catalog of letters of the
famous, much of which he has donated to one institution he is
accused of looting.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the Knights of Malta cast secret
ballots Friday for a new leader to carry on the Roman Catholic
order's 900-year-old tradition of chivalry, charity and nobility.
   Thirty-six electors will lock themselves in a villa on the
Aventine Hill on Friday to vote for a successor to Fra Angelo de
Mojana di Cologna. The order's grand master died Jan. 18 at the age
of 82 after 25 years as the knights' supreme leader.
   The 78th grand master will be chosen from among 22 of the
electors, including de Mojana's interim replacement, Fra Giancarlo
Pallavicini, a Hungarian-born American biochemist.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
