<1ST_LINE>a a AM-CivilServant Adv15   04-07 1091</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Civil Servant, Adv 15,1124</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday AMs, April 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>Message from the Woods: The Story of Park Naturalist Glen Kaye</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Forget about the Internal Revenue Service
auditor who may be doublechecking your tax return. Forget the
unreceptive receptionists who pass your call around when you phone
some federal office with a simple question. Forget the fact that
everyone loves to kick bureaucrats, especially at tax time. Read
on. You may end up glad you're paying Glen Kaye's salary.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKY MOUNTAIN NATIONAL PARK, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Glen Kaye gets paid
federal tax dollars to serve the American people as chief
naturalist for Rocky Mountain National Park.
   He helps the 2.7 million citizen bosses who visit each year to
understand the 414 square miles of national patrimony located 75
miles northwest of Denver.
   It's Kaye's job to tell us what it all means: What are those
funny looking birds? Will this mushroom kill me if I eat it? What
time do the rangers turn off the waterfalls?
   His is a five-page, single-spaced job description. He supervises
two visitor centers, two museums, four amphitheaters, two
information booths, a 2,000-volume library and an outpouring of new
books and pamphlets; oversees six park employees, more than 30
seasonal workers and 50 volunteers, and administers an annual
budget of $400,000.
   He is park spokesman for good news, such as international
wilderness conferences, and bad news, such as people falling off
mountains.
   A 25-year veteran of the U.S. government, he earns $43,891
annually and lives with his wife, Harriet, a pianist and caterer,
and their two teen-age children, in a government-owned house five
minutes' walk from his office. His burning ambition is to return to
Hawaii, ideally as a park superintendent.
   Assigned for five years to Hawaii Volcanoes National Park, Kaye
says: ``I left my heart there. It's the first place on Earth that
really sang to me.''
   But the return will have to wait. In mid-May, Kaye begins work
as chief of interpretation for the park service's Southwest region.
He'll be based in Santa Fe, N.M., a beautiful place, even if not
his paradise.
   If Glen Kaye didn't exist, Woody Allen would invent him.
   At 46, he reports for work dressed like the Boy Scout he once
was, yet often spends his days immersed in cosmic dilemmas such as
the future of the ozone layer.
   He is an acrophobic who tries, and fails, to overcome his fear
of heights by climbing mountains.
   A painter of tropical scenes, a wearer of Hawaiian shirts, Kaye
lives in a landlocked alpine valley where winter lasts seven months.
   He describes himself as a diffident man, yet he boldly creates
five-year plans for his department. Tall and gangly, with a monk's
fringe of hair, he is a solitary outdoorsman but seizes every
opportunity to attend grand opera with crowds.
   Growing up in Medford, Ore., Kaye decided he wanted to spend his
adulthood in the outdoors. So, straight out of Oregon State
University in 1963, he joined the park service as a naturalist at
Crater Lake National Park.
   There weren't many interpreters back then.
   ``Rangers were hugging trees or working with three spine
sticklebacks (an ugly little fish). They weren't big on people or
communications skills.''
   Today hundreds of workers on the federal payroll do nothing but
explain the nation's parks to its people.
   ``What I try to do is get people to realize a park is not
protected by boundaries on paper and a handful of rangers,'' Kaye
said. ``But we can't go out and say, `YOU MUST SAVE THIS NATIONAL
PARK!'
   ``We must lay out information and let people make up their own
minds. In the long run, parks are protected by the peer attitudes
of society.''
   Kaye believes one of the best ways to educate Americans about
their natural treasures is through art. That notion, and an old log
cabin, inspired him to create Rocky Mountain National Park's
artist-in-residence program in 1984.
   The cabin, once owned by the late Kansas newspaper editor
William Allen White, has a breathtaking view of 14,255-foot Long's
Peak. Every summer Kaye selects ``creators and communicators'' to
spend from one to three weeks in the cabin, doing their own thing.
The park provides housing and firewood, guests provide groceries.
   ``Glen broke through the inertia of `This is the way we've
always done it' and came up with a great idea,'' said Bill Sontag,
chief of the park service's Rocky Mountain region interpretation
office in Denver.
   Sontag attributed the program's success to Kaye's enthusiasm _
he raised money for the restoration and contributed his own elbow
grease _ but added, ``There are quite a lot of those folks in
government.''
   Participating last summer were four journalists, three artists,
two composers, a photographer, a writer and an actor.
   ``Artists need time to goof around, and Glen understands that,''
said Paul Sullivan, a New York pianist and composer who stayed in
the cabin after he was commissioned to create a score for a park
service film.
   Sullivan taped wildlife, water and wind sounds to help him write
a piano composition. He also practiced daily on the piano Kaye
moved into the house for his tenure.
   ``The cabin was offered with no strings attached. The guy was
genuinely offering an experience to us to see what we would do with
it,'' Sullivan said. ``At first it seemed too good to be true, but
I learned that Glen Kaye is a truly gentle man who has a very
sincere respect for artists.''
   Sullivan plans to return to the park later this year to premier
his musical work.
   ``This is the best thing the United States has ever done for me
personally,'' the pianist said, speaking of the opportunity Kaye's
program presented. ``I feel I've been given a great gift.''
   Art, Kaye says, has helped change Americans' perception of their
land _ ``from fear and loathing of wilderness to embracing and
positively administering it.''
   Kaye writes magazine articles and a column in the local
newspaper. In one recent piece, he gently warned readers about
world overpopulation and dwindling natural resources, and cautioned
of a growing scarcity for future generations.
   He wished them freedom from the regimentation of overcrowding,
access to beauty in nature, clean air and water, and the
opportunity to achieve their potential.
   ``Above all,'' he concluded, ``I want them to know of their
history and their responsibility, for in their action is the future
of their lives.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, April 15</NOTE>
