<1ST_LINE>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv10   04-07 0809</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 10,0829</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 10 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Rural Bus Effort Being Cranked Up by Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sometimes its hard to get from Frogfuzz
Junction over to Blitz Center where the courthouse is. Or up to
Wrathgrape Falls where Aunt Sophie Lou has the family in for Sunday
dinner now and then.
   Most often rural people who are too poor or infirm to drive a
car have to find a friend or relative to take them around. You
don't trot or teeter down to the corner to catch a bus or train
because there aren't any.
   And sometimes people who live in the countryside, in the
thousands of small towns and hamlets that make up rural America,
simply stay home when they're lonely or really should see a doctor.
   Railroad whistle-stop passenger service, the ``local'' or milk
train of yesteryear, has long passed into history. Stagecoaches
mostly gave way to buses by World War I, and even the buses are now
becoming hard to find.
   ``Increasingly, if one lives in a rural community, efficient bus
service may be only a distant memory, nor may rail or air service
be available,'' says the Agriculture Department.
   That's why USDA's Office of Transportation and the Department of
Transportation's Urban Mass Transportation Administration are
joining with the United Bus Owners of America to discuss a solution
to rural transportation problems.
   Two regional meetings will be held this spring, in Annapolis,
Md., April 20-22, and in San Francisco, Calif., May 18-20. A
national conference will be held in August in Omaha, Neb.
   Ellen Stommes of USDA's Office of Transportation said the
government's major financial aid involves the ``Section 18'' funds
provided states by the Department of Transportation (DOT) under the
Urban Mass Transportation Act.
   The money has totaled around $75 million annually and is
apportioned to states under a formula to help improve passenger
transportation systems available to rural people.
   No increase in federal money is being talked about at this
point, Ms. Stommes said in an interview. Instead, she said, the
conferences will be focusing on ``coordinating the resources that
are out there and trying to bring together the private and public
sectors.''
   It's sort of a hodge-podge of programs right now.
   States are contributing to rural transportation programs, along
with the federal government. Local transportation providers, mostly
non-profit groups, often have authority to operated within a single
county or a certain multi-county region.
   To some extent, these contract with human services agencies to
provide specialized transportation, to health facilities, for
example. But in order to qualify for Section 18 funds, general
public transportation must also be provided.
   ``One of the things that we're trying to encourage ... is the
coordination of schedules between these providers and the intercity
carriers,'' Ms. Stommes said. ``That is not happening in a great
many places.''
   But there are exceptions, she said.
   For example, ``Greyound is establishing what they call their
rural connector program, in which local or non-profit providers are
feeding their passengers into the intercity network,'' Ms. Stommes
said.
   Improving rural transportation is not a new or novel idea. It
has been the goal of countless community efforts since Americans
started heading West. Any small-town Chamber of Commerce worth its
salt has had a plan, prospectus or lobbying effort on behalf of
gaining or keeping its railroad service, bus station or airport.
   Much work already has been done at the federal level. In the
Carter administration, a White House Rural Development Initiatives
project included ``ways to overcome isolation by improving
transportation in rural America.''
   The Farmers Home Administration of USDA in 1979 took the lead
with the National Council for the Transportation Disadvantaged in
turning out a handbook, Rural Rides, for starting and operating a
rural public transportation system.
   A point made by the 1979 handbook is the relatively scant amount
of federal money available for rural transportation: although
nearly 30 percent of the U.S. population lives in rural areas, only
about 1 percent of the federal money spent on public transportation
goes to rural needs.
   The handbook, although dated in many ways, sounded a call for
coordinating the fragmented transportation services that did exist
_ exactly what Ms. Stommes said is one of the priorities of the
1988 effort.
   ``Coordination is good for the taxpayers and contributors who
foot the ultimate bill because waste, inefficiency and duplication
of effort should be eliminated,'' the handbook said. ``And it's
good for everybody in the participating town, county or area
because the savings can be passed on to the public in the form of
increased transportation services.''
   For further information on the upcoming meetings about bus
service in rural areas, contact: Eileen Stommes, Office of
Transportation, USDA, P.O. Box 96575, Washington, D.C. 20090-6575.
Phone 202 653-6305.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 10</NOTE>
