<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0561</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market surged, putting in its
second-best performance so far this year after taking a cue from a
stronger dollar and lower interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 64.16 points to
close at 2,061.67 Wednesday _ the biggest rise since it climbed
76.42 points Jan. 4.
   The Dow's advance was so strong it triggered a 50-point
voluntary restriction on computerized program trading on the New
York Stock Exchange for the first time since the limit was
announced Feb. 4.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Rust Belt renaissance gave America's mightiest
manufacturers record sales and soaring profits last year, despite
fears of a recession raised by the October stock crash, Fortune
magazine said in its annual elite ranking of the 500 biggest U.S.
industrial companies.
   Fortune said Wednesday that total sales of the 500 climbed 9
percent last year to a record $1.88 trillion, up from $1.72
trillion in 1986 and higher than the previous record of $1.81
trillion in 1985.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Big Three automakers said they had strong
sales in late-March and in the first quarter due to sales
incentives.
   But import carmakers reported less uniform results Wednesday for
the 10-day late-March period and the quarter, with some citing the
impact of a weaker dollar that effectively raised their prices for
American buyers.
   Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. reported more than 18 percent
jumps in daily sales rates for the quarter while General Motors
Corp., the top seller, reported nearly a 10 percent rise.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of Chrysler Corp.
workers voted to seek the job protections and economic benefits won
by the United Auto Workers union in contracts signed last fall with
General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co.
   ``We've had a pattern settlement before us now for almost a
year. ... It should not take a long time for us to put this
together,'' UAW President Owen Bieber told reporters Wednesday,
after addressing the 140-member UAW national Chrysler Council.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge ruled that Britain's Brian
Beazer cannot proceed with his $1.7 billion hostile tender offer
for Koppers Co. until at least April 15.
   A U.S. District judge in Los Angeles had suspended the
$60-a-share offer indefinitely on antitrust grounds. But U.S.
District Judge Maurice Cohill in Pittsburgh Wednesday said if
Beazer succeeds in overturning the California ruling, his order
immediately blocks the offer until he rules on Koppers' arguments
that the unwanted suitors violated securities law.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. emerges today from nearly a year
under bankruptcy court protection, free at long last from its
bitter legal war with Pennzoil Co.
   Under an reorganization plan approved March 23 by a federal
bankruptcy court judge, the White Plains, N.Y.-based oil giant will
transfer $3 billion to a Houston bank account in Pennzoil's name,
and begin making another $2.6 billion in payments to its other
creditors.
   In exchange for the $3 billion, Pennzoil will drop its claim to
a $10.3 billion judgment against Texaco that Houston-based Pennzoil
was holding when Texaco filed for Chapter 11 protection from its
creditors on last April 12.
</TEXT>
