<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   G.D. Searle & Co. said it will expand a program
of giving heart disease drugs to the poor, a move observers say
puts the company at the helm of the pharmaceutical industry's
efforts to help the indigent.
   Under a year-old pilot program, Skokie-based Searle gave $9
million worth of high blood pressure medicine to 20,000 patients.
The company said Wednesday it would expand its ``Patient In Need''
program by making all seven of its heart medicines available.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oversupply of doctors that is widely predicted
for the turn of the century will not materialize, and there could
be a shortage instead, two reports predict.
   The reports, published in today's New England Journal of
Medicine, contradict an often-repeated prophesy that the nation
will have tens of thousands too many physicians by the year 2000
and so should train fewer doctors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter told
the governments of Britain, France, West Germany and Spain they are
risking a trade war by their ``enormous subsidies'' to Airbus
passenger planes.
   The major trade bill now before Congress would permit the
charging of extra ``countervailing'' duties on imports of the
Airbus. They would be designed to compensate for the subsidies,
raising the price of the foreign planes and thus improving the
chances of U.S. aircraft manufacturers making sales to airlines
here.
   Yeutter made his remarks Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 32-year-old San Diego entrepreneur is waging
an unusual coast-to-coast campaign to oust the management of US
Sprint Communications Co., the company for which he says he
recruited hundreds of thousands of residential customers.
   Paul Walton brought his grass-roots movement to install himself
as US Sprint president to the nation's capital on Wednesday with a
speech to a small but curious lunchtime crowd outside the Federal
Communications Commission.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of Americans have home computers, but
only about half of the adults with them actually use the machines,
the Census Bureau reported.
   Nearly three-quarters of children who had access to a home
computer used it, however, the bureau said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market soared Wednesday, as the Dow Jones industrial
average advanced 64.16 points to close at 2,061.67.
   The dollar rose against most major currencies.
   Bond prices rallied in response to the stronger dollar.
   Precious metals futures fell sharply.
</TEXT>
