<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     04-07 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Rally, Testing Trading Limits, As Dollar Strengthens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A stronger dollar and weaker interest rates sparked Wall
Street's second best day of 1988, with stock prices rising so
strongly they triggered the New York Stock Exchange's self-imposed
limits on one type of trading.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 64.16 points to
2,061.67 on Wednesday, its biggest gain since the widely-watched
market barometer rose 76.42 points on Jan. 4, the year's first
trading day.
   In Wednesday's only major economic report, Detroit's Big Three
automakers reported that dealer sales incentives paid off with
strong late-March and first-quarter sales increases.
   On the New York Stock Exchange, nearly three stocks rose in
price for every one that declined as Big Board volume rose to
189.76 million shares, from Tuesday's 135.29 million.
   By swinging more than 50 points, the Dow industrials triggered
an NYSE restriction on computerized program trading for the first
time since the so-called ``collar'' was announced on Feb. 4.
   Program trading, a technique used to profit on price differences
between stocks traded in New York and corresponding stock-index
futures traded in Chicago futures markets, has been blamed for
injecting volatility into the market and frightening investors.
   Analysts said Wednesday's gain was due to a strengthening of the
dollar in foreign exchange, which in turn prompted a decline in
long-term interest rates in the credit markets.
   The dollar moved higher, analysts said, on speculation the major
industrial nations may be moving toward a fresh agreement to
support the U.S. currency. A meeting of the industrial powers is
planned for next week.
   The dollar rose to 126.03 Japanese yen late in New York from
125.28 yen late Tuesday.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond ended the session up
nearly $10 per $1,000 face amount. Its yield, which moves inversely
to its price, slipped to 8.75 percent from 8.84 percent.
   In Detroit, Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. reported more than
18 percent jumps in daily sales rates for the quarter. General
Motors Corp., the top seller, reported a nearly 10 percent rise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
