<DOCNO> AP880407-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     04-07 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crude Prices Slightly Higher; Products Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hopes continue waning in the oil markets that an
upcoming OPEC committee meeting will result in actions to stabilize
crude prices.
   In quiet trading Wednesday on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
crude oil futures prices finished marginally higher while refined
oil products were mixed.
   Contracts for May delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark U.S. crude, edged up 2 cents per barrel to $16.81. Other
contract months gained between 1 cent and 3 cents.
   Among refined products, wholesale heating oil for May delivery
rose 0.14 cent a gallon to 45.34 cents, while most longer-term
months declined. Wholesale unleaded gasoline for May fell 0.22 cent
a gallon to 48.42 cents, but longer-term contracts advanced.
   Crude prices failed to reach the $17-a-barrel level, which they
had tumbled below Tuesday following reports that the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries' pricing committee would not
recommend a full ministerial conference of the cartel at its April
9 meeting.
   The upcoming meeting in Vienna, Austria, earlier had incited
hope that the 13-nation cartel would act aggressively to stabilize
prices and enforce production limits to curb excessive supplies.
   ``The market is no longer expecting great shakes'' from the
April 9 meeting, said Bob Baker, an oil analyst for
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   But Baker said prices were supported by the latest weekly
statistics on the nation's oil supply and demand, which showed a
jump in oil imports and a substantial drawdown of oil stocks from
the previous week.
   The data, released late Tuesday by the American Petroleum
Institute, an industry group based in Washington, were construed as
indicating continued robust demand for oil.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
