<DOCNO> AP880407-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0317EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NewspageStocks     04-07 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newspage Stocks,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Post Broad Advance, Trigger Trading Limit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices have jumped sharply in response to
optimism over the outlook for inflation and interest rates,
propelling the Dow Jones industrial average to its second biggest
gain of the year.
   The Wednesday rise in the Dow was sharp enough to trigger a New
York Stock Exchange restriction on computerized program trading for
the first time since the limit was announced Feb. 4.
   But stocks kept rising even after the restriction _ effective
once the Dow industrials moves more than 50 points up or down from
the previous day's close _ kicked in late in the session.
   The Dow industrials finished 64.16 points higher at 2,061.67. It
was the average's ninth-biggest gain ever and the largest since it
rose 76.42 on Jan. 4.
   Nearly three issues rose for every one that fell among
NYSE-listed issues. NYSE trading volume grew to 189.76 million
shares from 135.29 million shares on Tuesday.
   Analysts said the market's rise was triggered by a news report
from Japan that officials of the seven major industrial countries
likely would agree on a plan to support the dollar in foreign
exchange.
   A strong dollar would diminish inflationary pressure, which in
turn could ease upward pressure on interest rates, analysts said.
   Recent expectations that the Fed would tighten credit and push
interest rates higher had depressing stock market psychology, said
Newton D. Zinder, a market analyst for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   But some analysts were skeptical about how long the strong gains
would last, given the market's recent volatility.
   The NYSE program trading restrictions took effect after the Dow
industrials passed the 50-point gain mark at about 3:19 p.m. EDT, a
spokeswoman for the exchange said.
   Program trading is a technique used by big investors to profit
on price differences between stocks and the corresponding
stock-index futures. It has been blamed for injecting volatility
into the market, frightening investors away and harming the
securities industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880407-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0318EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NYSECapacity     04-07 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NYSE Capacity,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYSE Gears For 1 Billion-Share Day By Late Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crushing trading volume during last year's stock
market crash has prompted the New York Stock Exchange to broaden
the planned expansion of its trading systems, with a daily
capability of 1 billion shares targeted by the end of 1989.
   ``At a time when many firms are cutting costs, we believe the
securities industry needs to take action to insure the ability to
handle high volume,'' NYSE President Robert Birnbaum said Wednesday.
   The exchange now can efficiently process the buying and selling
of 200 million shares a day. It initially planned to broaden its
capacity to 400 million shares a day this year, but increaesd that
target following the October stock market crash.
   Volume exceeded 600 million shares on both Oct. 19 and 20,
representing 200 million shares more than the system's current
theoretical capacity.
   The exchange now expects to be able comfortably to handle daily
volume of 600 million shares by June, according to its operations
advisory committee, which is coordinating the upgrading of the
securities industry's trading and communications systems.
   Last year trading volume averaged 197 million shares a day.
   Among additional measures the NYSE has taken to upgrade its
systems capacity since the October market crash are:
   _Increasing and restructuring the Designated Order Turnaround
(DOT) System's memory for more efficient order processing.
   _Program changes to the limit order systems to reduce
bottlenecks during peak volume periods. A 50 percent capacity
increase is targed for this month.
   _Adding 20 printers to the trading floor, thereby increasing
capacity by 20 percent, and increasing the number of electronic
display books on the floor by 25 percent.
   _Replacing the automated pricing and reporting system.
   Since 1982 the NYSE has spent more than $250 million upgrading
its systems and technology. The exchange has budgeted another $200
million to be spent on improvements over the next five years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
