<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0711EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Mexico-Debt     04-07 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Debt,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico Will Press Ahead With Efforts to Erase Foreign Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico will continue pursuing efforts to pare
its $100 billion foreign debt despite the limited success of its
novel program to swap some loans for U.S.-backed bonds, according
to the nation's chief debt negotiator.
   Jose Angel Gurria, director of public credit for the Treasury
Department, told foreign reporters that the nation's debt outlook
had improved dramatically since the beginning of the crisis in 1982.
   But, he said, ``the matter of the foreign debt continues being a
matter of fundamental importance (and) great worry for Mexican
authorities.''
   ``It's obvious that today we have a situation drastically
different (from 1982), and obviously from a positive point of
view,'' he said.
   ``The situation is much better, it is more comfortable,'' he
said.
   But foreign debt remains a problem because of the hefty amount
of interest Mexico must pay its creditors. Mexico paid $8 billion
to $9 billion in interest on its debt last year, second-highest in
the developing world after Brazil.
   Gurria talked to foreign reporters late Tuesday on the condition
that his remarks not be released as a matter of ``courtesy'' before
he spoke to a panel of the Mexican legislature on Wednesday.
   The Treasury official said Mexican officials were pleased with
the concept of the program to erase some of its foreign debt by
exchanging old loans for special U.S.-backed bonds.
   But he acknowledged February's auction of the bonds had not
lived up to expectations. The operation was ``smaller than what we
had expected, certainly smaller than what we had wanted,'' Gurria
said.
   The program involves exchanging some of the debt Mexico owes
foreign commercial bankers for new, 20-year-old bonds issued by the
Mexican government. The bonds are backed by special U.S. Treasury
securities and carry a higher interest rate than Mexico is paying
on the old debt.
   During the Feb. 26 auction, Mexico received bids from 139 banks
in 18 countries but rejected 45 percent of the bids.
   The bids that were accepted will result in retiring $3.66
billion in debt at an average discount of 69.77 cents on the
dollar, offering $2.56 billion worth of bonds in exchange.
   That sale will reduce the Mexican debt by $1.1 billion, a small
amount in comparison with the total oustanding credit. But the
cancellation of debt will mean savings of $1.5 billion in interest
charges over the next 20 years, the government said.
   Gurria said officials were pleased with the discount on the
loans. Mexican debt has been selling for about 50 cents on the
dollar in the secondary market.
   In his remarks to foreign reporters and the legislature, he
emphasized Mexico's desire to erase some of its foreign debt, while
capturing more new money to use in developing the economy.
   ``The balance is difficult to achieve and the final objective
even more so: to reduce the burden of the debt without closing off
to the country doors to possible support that will be required in
the future,'' he said in remarks released by the Treasury
Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
