<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Japan-Autos     04-07 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Autos,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sales of Imported Cars in Japan Surge 41.1 Percent In Fiscal 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of imported cars in Japan surged by 41.1
percent in the fiscal year ended in March to a record 104,340
units, partly because of the rising yen and government efforts to
simplify inspection procedures, an industry group announced today.
   Import sales surpassed the previous record of 73,924 units in
fiscal 1986, according to officials of the Japan Automobile
Importers-Association.
   German-made cars topped the list, accounting for 78,468 units of
the total sales, followed by 7,541 British and 4,675
U.S.-manufactured cars.
   The group said that in March, overall import car sales rose 26.1
percent from a year earlier to 11,976 units, also a record. March
marked the 51st consecutive month in which sales rose from the
year-earlier levels, officials said.
   German-made cars accounted for 74 percent of the total import
sales in March, they said.
   The group said the rise in import car sales, both in fiscal 1987
and in March, stemmed from lower interest rates on auto loans and
the yen's sharp appreciation, which makes imported goods cheaper.
   They also said the government simplified inspection procedures
as part of its attempt to bolster imports and cut the nation's
large trade surplus, while foreign car makers stepped up marketing
campaigns in Japan by establishing local subsidiaries.
</TEXT>
