<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     04-07 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher Following Wednesday's Rally, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was higher in early European trading
today, still boosted by a report that finance ministers of the
seven major industrialized nations will set a floor for the
American currency at a meeting next week.
   Gold prices were lower but steady following Wednesday's falls.
   Dealers said foreign exchange markets had calmed down
considerably following the dollar's frantic rally Wednesday after
the Japanese report that the so-called Group of Seven would set a
bottom rate for the dollar of 125 yen.
   Although traders said they doubted the group has set a specific
minimum for the dollar, the market appeared to be reluctant to sell
dollars before the meeting in Washington next Wednesday.
   ``Until the Group of Seven meeting, it probably won't go any
lower,'' one dealer at a European bank in Frankfurt said.
   While the group may not have specific targets, one trader in
Rome said, ``it is clearly the intention of the central banks,
especially of the United States, to maintain the dollar stable in
order to avoid a negative impact on the stock market.''
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.67 yen to a closing 125.70 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted fractionally higher at 125.85 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.6787 West German marks, up from 1.6700; 1.3890
Swiss francs, up from 1.3775; 5.6975 French francs, up from 5.6570;
1.88325 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8720; 1,244.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,236.50; and 1.2445 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2401.
   In London, the dollar also gained against the British pound. It
cost $1.8685 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.8790 late Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $446.60 a troy ounce and
at midmorning the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $446.25, both down from Wednesday's late bid
of $449.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $446.40, down from $449.50 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $5.56 to close at a bid $447.65.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.45 a troy
ounce, down from late Wednesday's $6.57.
</TEXT>
