<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     04-07 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nikkei Index Hits All-Time High, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices surpassed their pre-crash best levels
and reached an all-time high today in Tokyo, while the dollar
gained ground against the Japanese yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which gained 195.82 points Wednesday, gained
another 258.05 points, or 0.97 percent, closing the day at
26,769.22.
   The overnight surge in New York helped release bullish sentiment
pent up for several days because of concern over how Wall Street
would fare if the dollar fell further or U.S. interest rates rose,
traders said.
   The Nikkei average close today was more than 100 points above
the previous high recorded just before the worldwide stock market
crash last Oct. 14, when it closed at 26,646.43.
   ``Share prices rose almost across the board,'' said Yoshio
Shimoyama of Nikko Securities.
   The key market barometers regaining their pre-crash levels
indicated the strong fundamentals of the Tokyo market, he said.
   Prominent among gainers were electricals and automobiles.
Financials were also firm. Volume of the first section trade was a
heavy 1.6 billion shares.
   Meanwhile, the dollar closed the day at 125.70, the day's high,
up 0.67 yen from its close of 125.03 yen Wednesday. It had opened
the day at 125.60 yen and ranged between 125.40 and 125.70 yen.
   ``Trading was mixed in dollar-buying and selling, but the market
was generally quiet,'' said an exchange dealer at a major
commercial bank in Tokyo, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He attributed the quietness to participants sidestepping the
market in advance of the meeting of seven major monetary nations in
Washington next week.
</TEXT>
