<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Posner 1stLd-Writethru   04-07 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Posner, 1st Ld-Writethru,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Tycoon Launches Program to Aid Homeless</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH1</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf, `While the ...,' with 2 grafs to add
background on Kellner's motion. Picks up in 5th graf pvs, `At a ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millionaire industrialist Victor Posner, sentenced
for tax fraud to create a $3 million project to aid the homeless,
insists he wants to go ahead with the plan despite the objections
of a federal prosecutor.
   Posner, 69, faced what could have been up to a 40-year prison
term after pleading no contest to inflating that value of land
donated to a college in order to deduct it from his tax return.
   Instead, the Miami Beach financier was ordered to set up the $3
million project to aid the homeless and pay $4 million in back
taxes, interest, fines and court costs.
   While the $4 million part of Posner's sentence won't be changed,
U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner, who did not prosecute Posner, has
argued the sentence gives the appearance that the wealthy can buy
their liberty.
   Kellner said in his motion he was ``duty-bound to call to this
court's attention the fact that this court does not have the power
to order a criminal defendant to make charitable contributions as a
condition of probation.''
   At a hearing Wednesday, Judge Eugene P. Spellman required the
69-year-old Posner to state under oath that he did not wish the
sentence set aside and that he was going ahead with the plan
``freely and voluntarily.''
   Posner and a 10-member blue ribbon committee met Wednesday in
Spellman's courtroom to discuss the first stage of the program, a
study of the homeless in south Florida.
   ``Since February, I have been studying and learning about the
problems of the homeless both nationally and in Florida,'' Posner
said in a brief statement. ``All the studies in the world will not
help one homeless person. I will come to you with what will solve
the problem.''
   Posner's attorney, Edward Bennett Williams, must formally reply
within 30 days to Kellner's motion, which was filed Monday,
Spellman said.
   The initial study will include a six-part census of south
Florida's homeless; an examination of subpopulations such as
alcoholics, the mentally ill and families with children; and a
review of how government policy affected the problem and what
services are available to the homeless in each community.
   Spellman said he didn't plan to take an active role in the
committee's deliberations but suggested that the initial study not
use more than $500,000 of Posner's donation.
   Findings are scheduled to be available by May 16, said David
Fike of Barry University, which was chosen by Posner to administer
the study because of its social work program.
   Sister Jeanne O'Loughlin, president of Barry University, praised
the tycoon's ideas and said she hoped that Posner's donation would
be the nucleus of a program that might grow to $300 million.
   ``He has a very fast mind,'' she said. ``He's creating solutions
even before we give him all the data.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880407-0272 </DOCNO>
