<NOTE>Eds: updates with shares higher in later trading.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Rise Sharply in London</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices jumped on the London stock exchange
Thursday, boosted by the previous strong gains on the New York and
Tokyo markets.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was up 22.2
points, or 1.3 percent, at 1,767.0 at midday.
   Volume was 261.9 million shares, compared with 220.9 million
shares at the same point Wednesday.
   Share prices were marked up as soon as trading started in
reaction to the strong rises in New York and Tokyo.
   All three markets were helped by an unconfirmed Japanese report
that the Group of Seven industrialized nations' finance ministers
would seek to maintain a floor for the dollar at around 125 yen at
a meeting to be held in Washington on Wednesday.
   However, banking shares were sharply lower after Barclays PLC, a
major British bank, announced it would raise 921 million pounds, or
$1.72 billion, by offering its shareholders the opportunity to buy
one new Barclays share at a substantial discount for every two they
already own.
   But news of the issue had little effect on the market overall,
which remained focused on the Wall Street and Tokyo gain.
   Dealers said rumors of a large issue were circulating late on
Wednesday, reducing the impact of Barclays' announcement.
</TEXT>
