<1ST_LINE>u f PM-CBOT-Tokyo     04-07 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CBOT-Tokyo,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board of Trade, Tokyo Exchange to Form Partnership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade says it intends to
cooperate with the Tokyo Stock Exchange in trading futures
contracts on Japanese and U.S. government bonds and a Japanese
stock index.
   CBOT officials say they met in Japan with executives of the
Tokyo exchange to discuss the ventures, which will be launched
later this year.
   A spokesman for the Board of Trade said Wednesday the link
between the two exchanges will be the first cooperative effort
between a U.S. and Japanese exchange.
   ``The Asia-Pacific region is extremely important to the entire
futures industry,'' said Board of Trade Chairman Karsten Mahlmann,
adding that the exchange plans to open an office in Tokyo later
this year.
   Fred Grede, a CBOT vice president, said the two exchanges aren't
discussing a trading link that would permit contracts to be bought
at one exchange and sold at another.
   Instead the two exchanges will work together in developing the
contracts to make them more appealing to U.S. and overseas traders.
   The Tokyo exchange will license use of its ``Topix'' composite
index to the CBOT. Topix futures have yet to receive Japanese
regulatory approval, but the CBOT could begin trading the index
contract as soon as it is launched in Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
