<DOCNO> AP880407-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0902EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Taiwan-Trade     04-07 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Taiwan-Trade,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan's March Trade Surplus Lowest Since January 1983</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taiwan registered a trade surplus of $163
million in March, the lowest monthly surplus in six years, the
government reported Thursday.
   Taiwan's surplus with the United States, the island's largest
trading partner, totaled $298 million in March, down sharply from
$1.27 billion a year earlier, the government said.
   The monthly surplus was down sharply from $994 million in
February, according to the Directorate General of Budget,
Accounting and Statistics.
   Exports totaled $4.51 billion, up 10.9 percent from March last
year, while imports amounted to $4.35 billion, up 67.6 percent, the
report said.
   Taiwan's monthly surplus has not been that low since April 1982,
when it was $60 million.
   The United States in January replaced Japan as the country
sending the most goods to Taiwan, with U.S. imports reaching $1.3
billion in March, up 152 percent from a year earlier. Taiwan's
exports to the United States equaled $1.6 billion, down 10.5
percent, the report said.
   Trade officials attributed the surplus decline to tariff
reductions on 3,500 items and the 39 percent appreciation of the
Taiwan dollar against the U.S. dollar since January 1986, which has
made American products less expensive here.
   Taiwan has been under U.S. pressure to reduce its massive
bilateral trade surplus, which totaled a record $16 billion last
year, the third largest surplus with the United States after those
of Japan and Canada.
   Taiwan's trade deficit with Japan, its second largest trading
partner, totaled $601 million in March, up 27 percent from the same
month last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
