<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Federated     04-07 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Campeau Official Meets With Federated Employees</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CS1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Morosky, a key player in Campeau
Corp.'s victory in the takeover fight for Federated Department
Stores Inc., is meeting with Federated executives but won't say how
many will be retained.
   Morosky told a news conference Wednesday his first priority is
to refocus the attention of Federated employees, who have been
involved in the 2-month-long takeover war, on retailing.
   ``I'll be concentrating on getting people back to business, back
to selling merchandise,'' he said.
   Morosky declined to say whether Campeau Chairman Robert Campeau
will allow Federated's two top executives to keep their jobs. He
said Federated Chairman Howard Goldfeder and President Norman
Matthews face a decision.
   ``I'm looking forward to sitting down with both of them,''
Morosky told reporters during his tour of Federated's Cincinnati
headquarters tower.
   He began meeting with Federated executives, saying he hopes many
of them will choose to stay with the company, which operates more
than 650 stores nationwide and had $11.1 billion in sales last year.
   Morosky has said the Toronto-based Campeau will streamline
Federated, combining purchasing, marketing and other operations now
done independently by Federated's store groups.
   Some Allied executives will be relocated to Cincinnati, but
others will remain in New York, Morosky has said.
   Morosky, 46, a retailer of 17 years' experience, is president of
Allied Stores Corp., the retailer purchased by Campeau in December
1986.
   Campeau sold off many Allied divisions to pay off its debt in
that purchase and analysts have said they expect Campeau will do
the same with Federated.
   Morosky repeated Campeau's intention to keep Federated's ``crown
jewel'' store groups: Burdine's, based in Miami; Bloomingdale's and
Abraham & Straus based in New York; Lazarus in the Midwest; Rich's
in Georgia and Goldsmith's in Tennessee. He said Campeau also plans
to keep Ralphs, a Los Angeles-based supermarket chain.
   R.H. Macy & Co. Inc., the New York retailer Campeau beat out in
the fight for Federated, completed an agreement with Campeau last
week under which Macy will buy the Los Angeles-based Bullock's
stores and the San Francisco-based I. Magnin store group.
   Campeau has said it agreed to sell the Houston-based Foley's
store group and the Boston-based Filene's store chain to May
Department Stores Co.
   Also on the block are the Columbus-based Gold Circle discount
store chain and Federated's specialty stores.
</TEXT>
