<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-UAW-Chrysler     04-07 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UAW-Chrysler,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW Members Still Wrangling Over Chrysler Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Auto Workers members moved closer
to wrapping up demands for mid-April Chrysler Corp. contract talks,
but continued wrangling internally over whether to extend the
contract's protections to some former American Motors Corp. workers.
   About 140 delegates from 49 Chrysler local unions approved
contract proposals Wednesday that closely mirror economic and
job-protecting provisions in contracts signed last fall with
General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co.
   The union's main strategy in talks set to open April 18 is to
return to uniform bargaining with the Big Three U.S. automakers by
imposing the Ford-GM pattern contract on Chrysler and by limiting
the contract to two years so that all three contracts expire
together in 1990.
   ``We've had a pattern settlement before us now for almost a
year. ... It should not take a long time for us to put this
together,'' UAW President Owen Bieber said of the coming
negotiations after addressing the delegates.
   The strategy prevents the union from seeking to win Chrysler's
59,500 active and 8,000 laid-off workers any significant
improvement on the GM-Ford pattern in this year's talks. But it
will strengthen the UAW's bargaining power in 1990, when its
members' jobs will be further threatened by as many as eight
Japanese-owned U.S. factories capable of building up to 2.5 million
vehicles a year.
   The decision against asking for pay raises breaking the GM and
Ford pattern angered some Chrysler bargainers.
   ``We're stuck with something that was negotiated with GM and
Ford,'' Gregg Betts, unit chairman of Local 573 of the Office and
Clerical Workers, told The Detroit News. ``We're not getting any
raises, and the membership doesn't want it.''
   Like the GM and Ford contracts, the UAW's Chrysler proposals
would give workers yearly bonuses equal to 3 percent of their
annual wages, forbid plant closings and prevent layoffs for any
reason except a drop in sales.
   But unlike the two earlier pacts, the Chrysler proposal also
would forbid sale of plants or operations during the life of the
contract, an attempt to force Chrysler to back further away from
plans to sell its 28,000-worker Acustar Inc. parts subsidiary.
   The council was scheduled to finish approving demands today and
to vote on whether to include nearly 1,000 former AMC workers at an
engine and stamping plant in Kenosha, Wis., under the Chrysler
contract or to leave them to bargain for themselves, as they did
before Chrysler bought AMC last August.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
