<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Koppers 1stLd-Writethru   04-07 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koppers Wins Second Injunction Against Beazer-Shearson</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS new 3rd graf with Beazer group extending offer; picks up
3rd graf pvs bg'ng, A federal ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koppers Co. has won a second federal court
injunction blocking hostile suitors led by British industrialist
Brian C. Beazer and the investment firm Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   ``The scale comes down on the side of Koppers,'' U.S. District
Judge Maurice B. Cohill Jr. wrote in issuing a preliminary
injunction Wednesday preventing the Beazer group from proceeding
with its $1.7 billion tender offer before April 15.
   The Beazer group said today it would extend its $60-a-share
offer, launched March 3, from its scheduled expiration at midnight
today until midnight April 15.
   A federal judge in Los Angeles issued an injunction Monday
blocking the hostile $60-a-share offer indefinitely on antitrust
grounds. Cohill said if Beazer succeeded in overturning the
California ruling, his order immediately blocks the offer until
April 15, when he intends to rule on Koppers' claims that the
tender offer violates securities law.
   Koppers stock fell 87{ cents to $55.37{ a share on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   A federal judge in Delaware last Friday rejected the Beazer
group's request to invalidate Koppers' ``poison pill'' takeover
defense, which greatly would increase the cost of a hostile
takeover.
   It was not immediately clear how the hurdle raised by Cohill
will affect the tender offer from BNS Inc., the takeover company
formed by Beazer, Shearson and National Westminster Bank PLC.
   BNS attorney Edwin Mishkin told Cohill the investors were
prepared to extend the tender offer _ scheduled to expire at
midnight tonight _ until his ruling. BNS had contended that delays
in closing the deal could jeopardize its financing.
   Meanwhile, Koppers Chairman Charles R. Pullin testified before
Cohill Wednesday that he expects the Koppers board eventually to
reject as inadequate the $60 offer as it did Beazer's earlier bids
of $45 and $56 per share.
   Koppers board stated Tuesday it would take no position on the
latest offer immediately due to the pending litigation and the
company's ongoing attempts to seek alternatives to the hostile
buyout.
   The 64-year-old Koppers chairman said he expected someone to
beat the $60-a-share offer, but ``I'm not sure I could hazard a
guess as to when.''
   Pullin testified that the board was considering selling an
interest in all or part of the company, which has operations in
construction materials and services and chemicals. Management
prefers to sell no more than 20 percent to 25 percent of its valued
construction materials and services group, he said.
   Koppers has said it also was considering a recapitalization
plan, or the sale of the entire company.
   ``Some management people have talked about a leveraged buyout,''
of the chemicals businesses _ which Beazer has indicated he would
sell if successful in his takeover of Koppers _ although pollution
cleanup obligations make that option less likely, Pullin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
