<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Texaco 1stLd-Writethru   04-07 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco, 1st Ld-Writethru,0741</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco Officially Emerges From Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES to show transactions completed; Picks up 3rd graf pvs
``In exchange ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. officially ended a year under
bankruptcy court protection today, completing its epic legal fight
with Pennzoil Co. but facing continued pressure from dissident
shareholders and takeover strategists.
   Under a reorganization plan approved March 23 by a federal
bankruptcy court judge, the White Plains, N.Y.-based oil giant
transferred $3 billion to a Houston bank account in Pennzoil's name
today. Texaco also will begin making another $2.6 billion in
payments to its other creditors.
   The four wire transfers to Texas Commerce Bank began at 10:03
a.m. CST today and took 10 minutes to complete, officials at the
Texas Commerce Bank said.
   In exchange for the $3 billion, Pennzoil will drop its claim to
a $10.3 billion judgment against Texaco that Houston-based Pennzoil
was holding when Texaco filed for Chapter 11 protection from its
creditors on last April 12.
   Texaco said it took that action to avoid having to post a
potentially ruinous multibillion-dollar security bond while
appealing the judgment awarded Pennzoil by a Houston jury in
November 1985.
   The jury found Texaco had improperly interfered with a January
1984 Pennzoil acquisition of part of Getty Oil Co., then bought all
of Getty itself.
   Following U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Howard Schwartzberg's
approval of the plan _ worked out in December by the two companies
and committees representing Texaco creditors and shareholders _
Pennzoil borrowed $2.7 billion from a consortium of banks.
   The loan was to be repaid today once the $3 billion is deposited
in Pennzoil's account at Texas Commerce Bank in Houston, Pennzoil
spokesman Mike White said in a telephone interview Wednesday.
   Bob Harper, another Pennzoil spokesman, said today that no
company celebration was planned to mark the occasion, but he added
he was glad to see the case finally end.
   ``It's obviously been a very protracted affair,'' Harper said.
``I think it is important that all the parties concerned move into
the mainstream of what we really do best, and that's run our
companies.''
   The money Pennzoil borrowed has been invested in short-term
securities such as government securities and high-grade corporate
bonds, Harper said. Pennzoil borrowed the money before actually
getting the cash so the company could invest it ``in an orderly
manner.''
   Harper said he does not expect any immediate major investments
by Pennzoil.
   ``Our board really wants to take a look at all the options out
there,'' he said. ``We've been looking at various opportunities.
Our board will meet in early June to assess various possibilities.''
   Officials of both companies have said they chose to settle the
matter so they could get back to their businesses without the
prospect of endless litigation.
   Takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn, who holds 14.8 percent of
Texaco's stock and is its largest shareholder, last week filed an
appeal of the reorganization plan objecting to certain financial
conditions and provisions giving legal releases to Texaco officials.
   But Icahn stressed he never opposed the plan as a whole.
   ``I'm glad they came out of bankruptcy, and did not want to
stand in the way of that event,'' he said in an interview Wednesday.
   Icahn added that he thought it was ``wrong that shareholders
were forced to give releases to those involved (in the Getty Oil
acquisition) without having to vote on the releases separately.''
   His objection _ joined by other shareholders _ has been that
Texaco was throwing away a chance to recoup some of its losses by
suing the people who were responsible.
   Icahn also opposed a default provision of a loan Texaco will use
to help fund the reorganization.
   Under a provision of Texaco's agreement with a consortium of
about 25 banks providing up to $3 billion in credit, the loans
would be callable, on a vote by two-thirds of the banks, if control
of the company changed hands.
   Attorneys representing Icahn and some shareholders criticized
the indemnity and change-of-control provisions as devices for
entrenching Texaco's management.
   But Schwartzberg, in approving the plan, cited contentions by
Texaco and Pennzoil that the indemnities were necessary to end the
litigation.
   He also cited testimony that the banks insisted on the
change-of-control provision as a requirement for granting Texaco
the $3 billion loan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880407-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1145EDT</FILEID>
