<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-AlligatorExports     04-07 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Alligator Exports,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Plans to Breed Alligators in Spain for Meat and Skin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Danish investment group plans to
set up Europe's first alligator farm in southern Spain to produce
skins and meat for export, the project's organizer said Thursday.
   ``The baby alligators would come from the United States and be
bred at the farm in Spain, but it would take three to four years
before production and export of the reptiles' skin and meat could
begin,'' said Leif Skovgaard in a telephone interview with the
Associated Press.
   Skovgaard, a chartered accountant who is organizing the project
for a group of seven Danish investors, said 10,000 to 12,000
alligators would be bred yearly at a farm near the town of San
Roque.
   European Alligator Institue, as the project is called, is
seeking financial support from local and state governments in Spain
as well as the European Economic Community.
   The farm, which the group hopes to open by the beginning of
1989, would employ about 100 people, Skovgaard said.
   ``As alligators are dangerous at any age, our personnel will be
specially trained to cope with them so they don't lose fingers,''
he added.
   The investors hope to develop a nature park where visitors can
observe the animals, which can grow to 15 feet in length, in an
outdoor environment.
   Alligator meat, according to Skovgaard, tastes like something
between veal and chicken, and is popular in American, British and
French fish restaurants.
   The skins are used for shoes, handbags and other leather
assessories.
   Skovgaard said he did not anticipate protests from animal
protection or environmental groups.
   The United States banned hunting alligators because the species
was disappearing. but the ban was lifted recently after the
alligators made a strong comeback.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880407-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Barclays     04-07 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Barclays,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barclays to Raise $1.72 Billion in New Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barclays PLC, a major British bank, said Thursday
that it would raise 921 million pounds, or about $1.72 billion at
current exchange rates, by offering its stockholders the
opportunity to buy new shares.
   A spokeswoman in New York, meanwhile, denied rumors that the
bank was raising money to persue a friendly acquisition of Irving
Bank Corp., a New York bank holding company resisting a hostile
takeover from rival Bank of New York Co.
   ``No talks are going on and we have no interest,'' said Marion
J. Cotrone, a vice president at Barclays.
   Barclays said the stock issue _ its largest ever _ will be used
to expand domestic and international business, ``with particular
emphasis on the major economies of Europe, the (United States) and
the Far East.''
   Under the one-for-two rights issue, Barclays shareholders will
be able to buy one new Barclays share at a substantial discount for
every two they already own.
   The bank said it will issue 369.5 million new shares at a price
of 250 pence, or about $4.68, each. Expenses will be deducted from
the total raised.
   News of the issue sent Barclays shares tumbling on the London
Stock Exchange. The shares were down 48 pence each at 434 pence.
   Share prices were depressed Wednesday by rumors that a major
rights issue would be launched, but Barclays' announcement, while
knocking down bank shares, hardly had any impact on the wider
market.
</TEXT>
