<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Eastern Bjt   04-07 0915</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern, Bjt,0944</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unions Battle Back Against Lorenzo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buoyed by favorable court decisions and growing
political support, Eastern Airlines' labor leaders say they believe
they've got the momentum in the battle to save the financially
troubled carrier.
   ``There's a new sense that the right people are finally
listening to what we're saying,'' said Ron Cole, spokesman for the
Air Line Pilots Association at Eastern, a subsidiary of mammoth
Texas Air Corp.
   ``It's very heartening to a lot of employees,'' Cole said. ``Up
until not long ago, everyone thought (Texas Air chairman) Frank
Lorenzo was unbeatable.''
   ``I have felt a lot of confidence all along that we were gaining
momentum, that we were going to get justice,'' added Charles Bryan,
veteran leader of the Eastern Machinists union, which represents
12,000 maintenance and ground workers in a company with 33,000
employees.
   ``Lorenzo was just arrogant ... thumbing his nose at justice.
We've been able to hold the resistance movement together very
effectively.''
   Speaking in his union office less than five miles from the Miami
offices of the Contra rebels _ the Nicaraguan resistance _ Bryan
smiled as he realized his description of the unions as ``the
resistance movement.''
   ``We're an occupied country right now,'' said Bryan, 54, a
32-year veteran of Eastern. ``It's our airline, we built it up. But
we've been invaded.''
   Eastern management officials declined to be interviewed about
the recent developments.
   Spokesman Robin Matell said the situation was too uncertain to
speculate. But he said the unions have exaggerated the significance
of court rulings and added that management still considers reducing
labor costs crucial to salvaging the carrier, which has lost $900
million in the past 10 years.
   ``It still comes down to this: `Do you pay baggage handlers
$47,000 a year?''' Matell said.
   U.S. District Judge John Pratt in Washington declared March 10
that Eastern was in contempt of court for trying to sell its
profitable Northeast shuttle to another unit of Texas Air. Earlier
this week, Pratt said he has accepted a report from Eastern
officials that the airline no longer planned to sell off the
shuttle and would not find them in contempt if they follow through
with that pledge.
   On March 28, U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker, also in
Washington, granted a preliminary injunction sought by Eastern
pilots which would prevent Eastern from using its planes to train
pilots from Orion Air.
   Eastern management hoped to use the North Carolina cargo line to
fly Eastern routes in case of a strike.
   The rulings were crucial to halting what the unions believe are
two major pushes by Lorenzo, who began taking over Eastern two
years ago following his successful takeover of Continental Airlines
and has since swallowed up New York Air, People Express and other
small carriers.
   Stymied by Continental unions in 1983, Lorenzo shut the airline
down, took it into federal bankruptcy reorganization, got union
contracts voided, and emerged with a low-cost carrier.
   The Pratt injunction halted the ``spin-off'' of the shuttle,
which the labor leaders see as part of a strategy by Lorenzo to
cannibalize Eastern's assets. The Eastern reservations system was
bought by Texas Air last year, and planes and gates have also been
sold off.
   The Parker injunction against training Orion pilots sets back
Eastern's strike contingency program. Bryan warned machinists last
December, when labor talks deadlocked, to be ready for a
management-provoked strike that he said was aimed at crushing the
union.
   But the federal mediator sent in for the talks has so far
declined to classify the talks ``at an impasse.'' If he makes that
declaration, a 30-day cooling off period must follow.
   The unions, in a national election year, have rallied political
support.
   Democratic presidential candidates Michael Dukakis and Richard
Gephardt criticized Eastern management during February campaign
appearances here. Congressional hearings have been held into
Eastern safety practices and some congressmen are calling for a
federal probe into the Texas Air takeover.
   A report by the House Committee on Government Operations said
Orion Air should correct ``deeply rooted and pervasive problems''
before gaining Federal Aviation Administration permission to fly
Eastern planes.
   Other unions have joined Eastern employees in ``Jobs for
Justice'' rallies on the Capitol steps and other locations.
   ``The attitude in other unions is if Frank Lorenzo's model for
destroying unions is successful, it may well spill over. It
threatens most unions,'' Bryan said.
   The unions have numerous court cases, including lawsuits from
fired employees and hundreds of pending grievances. The Machinists
filed a new federal suit March 31 in Washington charging Eastern,
Texas Air and other defendants with systematically violating
federal securities and labor laws.
   More than a year ago, Eastern management called for a 30 percent
reduction, or $490 million, in labor costs. Union leaders responded
that Eastern employees have made concessions for years and are
tired of paying for bad management.
   The employees say they want to buy Eastern and run the airline
themselves.
   ``Eastern has everything it needs to be a success: an
established name; dedicated professional employees, good routes,
major airports. We could make it the airline it should be,'' said
Nancy Currier, a vice president of the Eastern flight attendants
local.
   Takeover strategist T. Boone Pickens last month expressed
interest in helping the unions realize their dream of taking the
airline from Lorenzo. Independent analysts have said such a
takeover seems unlikely but could intensify pressure on Lorezno,
whose Texas Air empire is $5 billion in debt.
</TEXT>
