<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AT&T-AffirmativeAction     04-07 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AT&T-Affirmative Action,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Shareholder Wants More Affirmative Action At AT&T, Not Less</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alex S. Tillman feels left out when he reads
about the National Alliance, the white supremacist group that wants
to abolish affirmative action at American Telephone & Telegraph Co.
   Tillman, a 42-year-old black executive at Bell Laboratories, is
wondering why no one has paid attention to his own proposal _ for
AT&T to increase its affirmative action.
   While the National Alliance occupies No. 5 on the AT&T
shareholders' ballot, Tillman is an uneasy neighbor at No. 4.
   ``I don't have any ax to grind with AT&T. I'm very pleased with
my employment here. ... But our name carries America in it. If
anybody should be setting the example, it should be AT&T,'' Tillman
said Thursday.
   Tillman said he is worried the National Alliance's resolution
might get a significant number of shareholders' votes at the annual
meeting April 20 in Denver.
   AT&T managers might allow a big vote for the National Alliance
proposal to justify weakening their commitment to hiring and
promoting minorities and women, Tillman fears.
   ``I'm not speaking out against white males. I'm saying in God's
land, there's space for everybody,'' Tillman said.
   Tillman, who joined Bell Labs in 1971, handles accounting and
budget preparation for a Bell Labs unit in Murray Hill, N.J. He has
recruited minorities for the company and visits colleges under the
Urban League's Black Executive Exchange Program.
   Tillman is casting his argument in terms that he thinks
shareholders will appreciate: Shifting trends in population mean
that more of the new entrants to the work force through the year
2000 will be minorities and women _ as much as 90 percent of all
new entrants, Fortune magazine said in its April 11 issue.
   ``We're in an economic race, with worldwide competition. To have
people with potential and not use that potential to the fullest is
something America cannot afford,'' he said.
   AT&T promoted only one black to the level of vice president from
1979 to the end of 1987, namely Naseby ``Pete'' Rhinehart Jr., a
corporate vice president for tax planning and compliance, Tillman
said.
   AT&T says 3.9 percent of its senior managers were women and 1.6
percent were minorities as of the end of 1987. In contrast, 46.2
percent of all company employees are women and 20.8 percent are
minorities.
   AT&T spokeswoman LuAnn Gardner said the company's started an
affirmative action advisory board last year and has increased its
hiring of women and minorities. It added a second black vice
president earlier this year.
   ``There have been some improvements under the Jim Olson
administration, but not enough,'' Tillman said, referring to
Chairman James Olson. ``Today it is sound business to ensure that
minorities and women are fully utilized in upper levels.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
