<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BurgerKing-Amoco     04-07 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Burger King-Amoco,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Denver Chosen As Test Market For Fast Food, Gasoline Venture</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Suanne is cq in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the next 18 months, those in a hurry here can
fuel up their cars and themselves in one stop in what's believed to
be the nation's first combination fast food, gasoline outlet.
   The city was chosen as the test market for an 18-month joint
venture, which began Thursday, by Miami-based Burger King Corp. and
Chicago-based Amoco Oil Co.
   ``Basically, we're both in the energy industry,'' said Suanne
Map, a Burger King spokeswoman in Denver. ``Amoco provides food for
the car and we provide the food for the body.''
   Walt Knake, an Amoco marketing specialist, said both companies'
clientele are similar.
   ``Our typical customer is between 18 and 49. So that means our
customers will match up pretty well with Burger King's customers,''
he said. ``And the typical Amoco and Burger King customer wants
speed. They want to save time.''
   Amoco's end of the operation consists of four pump islands, a
security booth and a cashier. The Burger King restaurant sits at
the rear of a 150-foot lot and consists of a drive-through and
walkup window but no sit-down service.
   Burger King customers can use their Amoco credit card to pay for
food.
   Amoco first approached Burger King in early 1986 with the idea,
Knake said. He said the operation will be evaluated during the next
18 months.
   ``There are no plans to roll it out, because we don't know how
it's going to work,'' he said. ``We're going to have to evaluate
it.''
</TEXT>
