<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-RealEstate     04-07 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Real Estate,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Investment In U.S. Real Estate To Remain Strong, Bank
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese appetite for U.S. real estate
is expected to remain strong this year but may not exceed the $6
billion they invested last year, Bank of America said Thursday.
   ``At minimum, we expect Japanese investment to be equal to or
slightly below 1987 levels,'' said Jack S. Cooper, managing
director of the bank's Investment Real Estate Group.
   The Japanese remain concerned about volatility in the U.S. stock
market as well as the nation's huge trade and budget deficits. But
Cooper said in a statement that if there is improvement in ``the
global economic and political issues that are causing'' those
concerns, the amount invested in this country could be
substantially higher than last year.
   Investment will continued to be focused on the west and east
coasts, but the Japanese increasingly are looking beyond the major
cities for opportunities. Among the new spots to draw attention are:
   _Atlanta. More than 150 Japanese companies have established
subisidiaries in Atlanta, according to Bank of America, and that
will serve as a magnet for more Japanese investment.
   _Nashville, Tenn. The bank cites Tennessee officials as saying
about 10,000 workers are employed by Japanese firms within the
state. As in the case of Atlanta, that is likely to lead to
additional real estate investment there.
   _Portland, Ore. The city is becoming ``an increasingly
well-known market in Japan'' largely because of its own promotion
efforts, the bank noted.
   _Seattle. Bank of America noted that this city is particularly
convenient because of simple airline connections to Japan.
Investors are likely to be attracted by its port and diverse
economy.
   _San Diego. Physical limitation of the city's growth, because of
the Pacific Ocean, the Mexican border and the desert, increase the
potential for strong real estate appreciation, the bank said.
   _Washington, D.C. Japanese recognize the city's growing demand
for offices, housing and shopping centers, the bank said.
   _Sacramento, Calif. Japanese investors are likely to turn to
this city as an alternative to the higher-priced San Francisco and
Los Angeles markets, Bank of America said.
   _Phoenix. Continued population growth of this city has
maintained a need for apartments and shopping centers.
</TEXT>
