<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Guinness     04-07 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Guinness,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stockbroker Charged in Guinness Affair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police charged David Mayhew, a partner with
British investment firm Cazenove and Co., with three offenses
related to Guinness PLC's 1986 takeover of Distillers Co.
   Mayhew was arrested Thursday and taken to a London police
station to answer questions about the Guinness affair and was later
charged.
   The first charge accuses him of inducing Distillers shareholders
to dispose of their shares ``by dishonest concealment of a material
fact,'' the police said.
   The second charge alleges unlawful financial assistance, and the
third accuses him of involvement with an undisclosed party, which
purchased Distillers shares in April 1986.
   Mayhew, who was released, is scheduled to appear in a London
magistrate's court on Friday to hear the charges.
   He is the seventh person to be charged by British police in
connection with the Guinness affair.
   The other accused are former Guinness chairman Ernest Saunders;
Roger Seelig, a former corporate finance director for Morgan
Grenfell and Co. Ltd.; financier Sir Jack Lyons; Heron Corp.
Chairman Gerald Ronson; Lord Spens, a former director of Henry
Ansbacher and Co.; and stockbroker Anthony Parnes.
   British police have also issued a warrant for the arrest of
former Guinness director Thomas Ward, a Washington lawyer.
   Guinness has admitted that its former management arranged for
company outsiders to purchase the brewer's shares to boost their
price in order to make Guinness' cash and stock offer for
Distillers more attractive than a rival bid.
   Cazenove, which acted as Guinness' broker during the Distillers
bid, reaffirmed on Thursday a 1987 statement in which Cazenove
denied that any of its representatives broke the law or offered
``improper indemnities or inducements'' to purchase Distillers
shares.
   Cazenove insisted on Mayhew's innocence, saying he would remain
a partner and would continue to have the firm's complete support.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
