<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1558EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Texaco-Pennzoil-Scene Bjt   04-07 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texaco-Pennzoil-Scene, Bjt,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$3 Billion In 10 Minutes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Texaco-Pennzoil, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four years and two months after the start of an
epic legal battle between two oil industry rivals, it took just 10
minutes Thursday for Texaco Inc. to deliver a $3 billion settlement
into the bank account of Pennzoil Co.
   A half-dozen tight-lipped executives from Texas Commerce
Bank-Houston and Pennzoil huddled around a computer terminal in a
sterile bank office, waiting like expectant parents for the green
computer screen to signal the beginning of the largest cash
settlement in the nation's judicial history.
   ``I'll be glad when it's over,'' a tense Dave Alderson,
assistant treasurer of Pennzoil, said. ``It'll be a relief.''
   Bank officials warned about a dozen reporters and photographers
before escorting them into Room 1760 of the bank's Electronic
Services Division-Funds Transfer Section that the place was a
high-security area and they would not be allowed to wander.
   Ironically, the bank is two blocks south of Pennzoil's Houston
headquarters and two blocks north of the downtown Texaco Building.
   Margo Somers, an operations officer at Texas Commerce Bank,
repeatedly punched in the Pennzoil account number on her terminal
to see if the Texaco money electronically appeared on the bank
ledger.
   ``This is the largest one I've ever handled,'' she said.
   To get an idea of how much $3 billion really is, consider this:
If you spent $1 every second, it would take 92 years to go through
$3 billion. If comprised of $1 bills only, the stack would reach
203 miles high and weigh 3,061 tons, according to Ira Polikoff, a
spokesman at the U.S. Treasury's Bureau of Engraving and Printing.
   At Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co., which handled Texaco's end
of the transaction from New York, James P. Witkins, a senior vice
president, gathered the cash from 26 or 27 banks using a task force
of four people.
   ``It's not really the raw money itself, it's the sensitivity and
the technicality,'' he said. ``You want the thing to shut out in
one day. Three billion dollars works out to about a half a million
dollars a day in interest. Money like that doesn't sit around
idle.''
   At 10:03 a.m CDT, the first payment _ $600 million _ came in to
Houston.
   ``So far, so good,'' someone said.
   Alderson smiled faintly.
   Bank officials notified Manufacturers Hanover the payment had
been received.
   Then they waited, eyes still glued to the computer screen.
   There was little small talk. The minutes dragged. A bank
spokesman explained that the next wire transfer probably was hung
up in the computer queue behind other business.
   Mrs. Somers typed in the Pennzoil account number again.
   Payment No. 2 arrived at 10:10 a.m. Pennzoil had another $800
million.
   Alderson smiled a bit more.
   He and Linda Condit, director of treasury operations for
Pennzoil, scribbled notes on legal pads.
   At 10:12 a.m., another $700 million appeared in the Pennzoil
account.
   Alderson's smile grew.
   Just a minute later, at 10:13 a.m., the fourth and largest
single payment _ $900 million _ arrived.
   ``There it is,'' Mrs. Somers said. ``It's all in.''
   Alderson flashed a $3 billion grin.
   A few people began applauding.
   ``We're all very glad it's all over,'' Alderson said, accepting
congratulations, but hurrying out of the room.
   ``Going to call the boss?'' a reporter asked.
   ``Exactly right,'' the assistant treasurer said.
   A few blocks away, Joe Jamail, the colorful Houston attorney who
headed the Pennzoil legal team and stands to make millions from the
case, was in court, trying another case.
   ``I don't have any gloating feeling,'' he said. ``I'm just glad
that the system of justice prevailed and we won. Now I hope they
(Texaco) quit crying about it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880407-0306 </DOCNO>
