<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 2010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SurfwearBankruptcy     04-07 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Surfwear Bankruptcy,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surfwear Firm a Victim of Shifting Tides in Fashion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maui and Sons, the fast-growing maker of
beachgoer garb, has found itself the victim of shifting tides of
fashion.
   The Orange County-based surfwear company sought protection from
creditors by filing for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in federal
court on Tuesday, listing liabilities of $7.1 million and assets of
$2.5 million.
   The company listed more than 200 creditors in court documents.
   ``We just needed the Chapter 11 to get over the cash-flow glitch
that was created from the fall line not doing well,'' said the
company's attorney, William Lobel.
   ``Fortunately for us, the demand for Maui and Sons clothing
right now is extraordinary. The company's problem is ... finding
the cash to buy the merchandise to fill the orders,'' Lobel said.
   Under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, a company is
protected from creditors and permitted to continue operating and
restructure itself under court supervision.
   The surfwear industry is fast-growing but highly volatile, made
up mostly of tiny entrepreneurial companies. Sales industrywide
this year are expected to be between $1 billion and $3 billion.
   Maui and Sons is considered a leader in the industry even though
its annual sales are only $12 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
